I also encourage women to make better, more simple choices if they are too busy to cook. Another common problem I see most women have when they are trying to change their body shape is time to commit to a programme. 

We all lead such busy lifestyles these days. We give time to our families, our friends, and work and we are left with little to no time. 

It's so frustrating because you're trying to be a good friend, mother, daughter, sister, colleague, or employee. But what's left for you? Or maybe there is time? 

I've found that most people usually can find time. Maybe instead of an hour of Netflix we could swap it for a workout? Maybe instead of scrolling we could be walking? Or instead of picking up a takeaway on the way home from work, we could pick up a ready meal in a supermarket? The problem lies in trying to do too much.

caption:
â€˜Why most women will NEVER have visible absâ€™

And thatâ€™s ok! 

Firstly, we need to understand some biology here. Women have approximately DOUBLE the amount of essential body fat that a man has. What does essential mean? We need it. Itâ€™s necessary for our overall health. 

Secondly, understand when a female has visible abs - they are usually on the threshold of that healthy/unhealthy body fat percentage. 
If they are super active or athletes and consuming adequate calories and have a higher lean muscle mass - often theyâ€™re body fat percentage is healthy for their level. On the other hand, someone who has <18% Body Fat from extreme dieting with low lean muscle mass is mostly considered an unhealthy body composition.

Lastly and MOST importantly, the main reason why most women will never have visible abs is because they are simply not willing to make the sacrifices to achieve them. And thatâ€™s PERFECTLY alright. In a lot of instances women would have to give up social occassions, wine & chocolate. And have to engage in a lot more activity than their time schedules allow! ğŸ™

caption:
We all have the same 24 hours in the day ğŸ’â€â™€ï¸

I actually hate this statement. Although TECHNICALLY correct - peopleâ€™s priorities are very different.

Let me give you an example. Comparing my 24 hours with a 40 year old working mother of 4 is just INCOMPARABLE!!!!

Itâ€™s not that the 40 year old mother of 4 doesnâ€™t WANT to look after her health and fitness (I literally have women with these credentials doing the Strong and Sassy Programme).

I have the luxury of working from home. Because of time differences with clients - the bulk of my work is done mornings and evenings so my free time is during the day. Iâ€™ve no kids. No mortgages. Life is EASIER for me! So my 24 hours are very different to my clients.

Like Mandi who is a mother of 5 and runs her own business. She prioritises her workouts when her kids are gone to schoolğŸ’ƒ

Or Elaine who is a doctor - has to get her workouts done on her lunch break ğŸ’ª

Jacqui is doing tennis as her exercise - she gets to socialise and exercise ğŸ¾ 

Gillian who doesnâ€™t want to make different meals for her family - controls portions and adds extra veg.

Lucy who is commuting 2hours a day - has her meals and snacks prepared! 

We all have the same 24 hours in a day. But we all have different priorities. What are your priorities? ğŸ¤”

Want results that seem unimaginable right now? ğŸ§

Did you know itâ€™s ğŸ’¯ within your reach? ğŸ‰ğŸ’ƒ

We all have to start somewhere - had you told my 21 year old self who started on ring rows - 10 years later Iâ€™d be doing ring muscle ups - Iâ€™d be pretty pissed off that it took 10 years ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜ But you know what - the time passed anyway! 

I could lie to you and tell you the Strong and Sassy programme is the best strength programme around. But truth is all programmes can work - if you can be consistent with them. How can we stay consistent with them?

I spoke with a friend yesterday who used to do classes in the gym and has recently started an online programme. She said â€˜it actually keeps her more accountable- because if she misses a day of the programme - it messes up the rest of her programme. Plus she has someone checking in with her each weekâ€™. The accountability of her programme is MAKING her be more consistent. With classes, if she missed a day - no one checked in to see why? It didnâ€™t have an impact on the rest of her programme, she just picked up where she left off?

Online programmes allow you to have more flexibility and freedom. But also, regular check ins mean youâ€™ve always someone holding you accountable.

Want to finally be consistent with your health and fitness? Find a way that works for you ğŸ’ª

Picture of a happy girl who just got her period ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰

As a woman, one of the greatest signs of health is a regular, monthly cycle. ğŸ™â¤ï¸

I know itâ€™s a nuisance. I know it can be painful. I know it can cause us to be a bottomless pit ğŸ· (p.s out BMR actually increases the week before our period - so we actually NEED extra calories ğŸ˜)

But if overall health is your goal - a regular monthly cycle is the pinnacle of health. If for some reason, youâ€™re not getting a monthly cycle (unknown reason) - please reach out to your doctor.

Iâ€™m particularly happy to see mine this time around. Why?

Because mine arrived 7 days LATE! We knew we werenâ€™t expecting any baby Boyceâ€™s- I knew EXACTLY why my period was late and I actually anticipated it.

Iâ€™m SUPER in tune with my body. I know whatâ€™ll put it out of whack. I know that travel causes disruptions to my cycle. I know that alcohol has an effect on it and I know the impact stress has on my body too.

As Iâ€™ve harped on about the last few weeks have been super stressful for me. You could join the dots with all spots on my neck and chest and I knew something had to give.

Do NOT underestimate the affect of stress on your body. It affects our health in more ways than people could even imagine. Accumulation of stress can lead to much greater health risks than a delayed period - so do something about it today â¤ï¸ğŸ™

Hopefully some menstrual gains today - for yet another comp ğŸ’ªğŸ‰

caption:
Hazel

45 

Lecturer 

Hazel is super active. She actually just completed an Iron Man at the weekend ğŸ’ª

There were 3 main reason Hazel wanted to join the Strong and Sassy programme

1. Get a home based strength programme to accomodate her training goals

2. Work on her nutrition - sheâ€™s always been active but knows she needs to work more on her nutrition (not just for weight loss but also to match her activity)

3. As sheâ€™s getting older, she wants to support her overall health. Prepare her body as best as possible for the next stage of her life ğŸ™

Sheâ€™s already reaping the rewards as she completed her Ironman at the weekend.

Iâ€™m so proud of this lady and the commitment she makes even with a super busy schedule ğŸ”¥

If youâ€™re looking to make a change, why not dm me today?! ğŸ“

Moving house has been listed as one of the most stressful events in your life. Up there with loss of a loved one and divorce.

Unfortunately, Iâ€™ve experienced 2 of the 3.

I can honestly say the strain it puts on your physical and mental health is difficult but the most notable stress was the one I experienced with Owen. 

I was moody, complaining constantly and actually quite aggressive. But thankfully, it was short term and Iâ€™m back to my normal happy, bubbly self ğŸ™

This reminded me of a client (a couple of them actually) who was constantly agitated and barking at her partner. The poor fella couldnâ€™t do anything right. 

Why? Why was she constantly cranky to her partner? We soon realised two things that were causing these mood disturbances.
1. She was on crazy low calories - constantly hungry and lacking in energy (anyone who has been HANGRY understands ğŸ™ˆ)
2. She was desperately unhappy in how she viewed herself. This unhappiness in herself projected into her moody outbursts and they were becoming too frequent.

She was GENUINELY worried these feelings were going to have a long term impact on her relationship.

So what did we do?
1. The first one was easy - increasing calories to a normal level while still allowing her to achieve her goals. Her energy levels sky rocketed and her mood instantly improved.
2. Working on self confidence and self esteem was a little trickier. We started to focus on her health from an internal perspective and not just what her body looked like on the outside. We started to do resistance based training and she started to appreciate what her body could do instead of just â€˜burning caloriesâ€™.

Within weeks, her mood improved dramatically, and the cranky outbursts declined steadily. She is now happier in herself than ever before and her partner is also reaping the rewards!!!

Sound familiar? Youâ€™re not alone! But you CAN change - with the right guidance and support anything is possible ğŸ™

Letâ€™s talk mindset ğŸ¤¯

I stand out of my comfort zone pretty regularly. But twice this year, I stood out of my comfort zone big time.

First, was a novice Weightlifitng competition. Second, a half marathon. 

Why take on these challenges?

Because guess what - itâ€™s not your body thatâ€™s saying no. Itâ€™s your mind. Your body is capable of a lot more than you think.

Itâ€™s not easy going to competitions knowing you wonâ€™t win. Itâ€™s not easy being 20kg behind other peoples lifts. Itâ€™s not easy running 21km. 

But it helps you learn. It builds character. Everytime you step outside that comfort zone you build a little more resilience, a little more confidence. 

I spoke to a client last week and she talked about how increasing calories was mentally challenging. I get it I do, comfort zones are easier.

Itâ€™s easy to continue training and exercising while ignoring the biggest problem thatâ€™s not allowing you achieve your goals (nutrition ğŸ™ˆ). Itâ€™s easy to do 6 week challenges every quarter - lose weight and regain it because you couldnâ€™t sustain it.

Whatâ€™s not easy? 
Committing to a 6 month programme to improve your habits and make LONG TERM sustainable change.

We want results yesterday. Believe me. I get it. But unfortunately, thatâ€™s not how the cookie crumbles.

And the longer you waste on short term, quick fixes. The longer it takes to actually get to your final destination ğŸ™ŒğŸ™

â„ğ• ğ•¨ ğ•¨ğ•–ğ•ğ• ğ•’ğ•£ğ•– ğ•ªğ• ğ•¦ ğ•£ğ•–ğ•”ğ• ğ•§ğ•–ğ•£ğ•šğ•Ÿğ•˜?
.
.
Quite often people think you need to do more to achieve your goals. And in a lot of cases that is true - more exercise, more water, better nutrition. But for some actually less is more. 
.
.
Everyone has their problem areas. 

ğŸ‘‰Some people nail nutrition and exercise and canâ€™t understand why they canâ€™t lose weight - while their bodies are in chronic sleep deprivation ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ 

ğŸ‘‰Others weigh in the week before their period and canâ€™t understand why their weight fluctuates. 

ğŸ‘‰Others would rather take a supplement than eat real food ğŸ™ˆ

ğŸ‘‰ No ice baths will not mask the fact that youâ€™ve been boozing Friday, Saturday and Sunday.
.
.
These are some of the elements to think about when it comes to your goals - in no particular order ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Nutrition and exercise are not the only 2 elements you can control. If you have those nailed why not look at other areas? ğŸ¤”
.
.

Meet Elaine ğŸ”¦

Age: 41

Occupation: Doctor

I donâ€™t say this lightly when I say Elaine has overcame more obstacles in the last year than most people do in their lifetime.

âœ… Covid

âœ… Pneumonia 

âœ… Moved Continent

âœ… Living in a country that their first language isnâ€™t English

âœ… Kids with autism 

And she STILL MANAGES to prioritise her health â¤ï¸

Half the time sheâ€™s working out with kids hanging out of her. The other half sheâ€™s squeezing a lunchtime session in.

You see the problem we have is we are waiting for these PERFECT circumstances to start. Truth is thereâ€™s never a perfect time. Life is ALWAYS going to get in the way. But something is ALWAYS better than NOTHING! 

I could not be prouder of the effort this lady has put in. The habits she has implemented and the lifestyle she has changed - all for the better.

caption:
â€˜I was too stubborn to admit I couldnâ€™t do it on my ownâ€™

From my experience, most women are control freaks (Iâ€™m one too ğŸ™ŠğŸ˜‚). We think we need to know everything. We are strong independent women afraid to rely on others for help â˜¹ï¸

We think we should â€˜know what to doâ€™ in all areas of life. But from my experience - those who delegate work to other people in different areas of their life - often have the most success.

Why?
Because itâ€™s one less thing for YOU to do.

Having a coach to help you with your health and fitness is actually a shortcut! 

Why? Because the expertise, accountability and the right plan allows you to HAVE MORE TIME! 

Not only that - youâ€™re not WASTING your time trailing methods that may or may not work for you! 

Sarah just wishes she started sooner. 

Donâ€™t make that mistake. Start today and finish 2022 strong ğŸ’ª

Did you know that every choice you make now - your future self is paying the consequence.

Iâ€™ll give you an example. 
Were you that slim 20 year old that could eat whatever she wanted without ever gaining weight. So you ate takeaways and never exercised? Your 40 year old self may not feel the same way. 

I try to educate to my clients that every action you take has a consequence. You may not be able to see it in the short term, but long term your body is thanking you ğŸ™â¤ï¸

Another example - last week I was talking to my clients about menopause. Now majority of my clients are a long way away from menopause - so why talk to them about it?
Every action they choose between now and then can have an impact on their symptoms. For example - if you start resistance training in your 20s - your menopausal body will thank you ğŸ™ 

Every action has a consequence. If you constantly rely on short term gratification- there will be long term consequences. If you decide to play the long game - stop sweating the small stuff, and be patient - your future self WILL thank you ğŸ™

caption:
Toning up ğŸš¨âš ï¸

Not going to lie - this is a trigger for me. I absolutely HATE the term. I hate it a little bit less than â€˜I donâ€™t want to get bulkyâ€™ ğŸ˜‚

Anyway hereâ€™s what you need to do to â€˜tone upâ€™

1. Understand what it is youâ€™re saying ğŸ˜‚ you want to change your body composition which is reducing your body fat mass and increasing your lean muscle mass. 

2. Lift weights - a body building style progressive overload programme is best for this if aesthetic goals are what youâ€™re looking for

3. Control your food intake - easiest achieved by a calorie deficit

4. Be consistent - it doesnâ€™t happen overnight so you may aswell enjoy the process. 

Ps think of all the other amazing goals youâ€™re achieving in the meantime (increasing bone mass density, increased BMR, reducing risk sarcopenia)

The pickiness was something that weaned itâ€™s way out as I aged and was more open to food suggestions.

The guilt and binging was a whole different kettle of fishâ€¦

This one took me years and a whole lots of self development to find! 

Itâ€™s one of the many reasons I love my job so much. I know personally how hard it is to form a good relationship with food - so when I help my clients achieve that - I feel that happiness deep in my soul!

caption:
I have high expectations. 

I give off good energy and I need people to match the effort I give off.

I donâ€™t expect people to match my energy (because letâ€™s be honest that would be hard ğŸ˜…).

But I donâ€™t appreciate negative energy!

There have be instances and situations in my life that I had to let of due to this negative energy! But every time I have - Iâ€™ve found another level of me ğŸ™â¤ï¸

Anyway - point of this post?

Donâ€™t settle. EVER! For anything in life - jobs, relationships, friends, houses etc. Donâ€™t lose yourself trying to be someone youâ€™re not âœŒï¸

Iâ€™ll be honest. Pictures donâ€™t do this programme justice.

But comments and quotes like this - these are what makes my job the best job in the world.

I am one of those annoying people who wakes up with no snooze button.

My alarm goes off Monday and Iâ€™m buzzing to see the check ins from all over the world.

I am so truely blessed with the women who venture on this programme.

Thereâ€™s not 100s of women on this course but a small select few. Women who are sick of fad dieting. Women who are sick of starting again EVERY week. Women who are taking control of their health and fitness, one step at a time! 

These women are making long term sustainable change and their future selves are already thanking them â¤ï¸

How lucky am I that I get to work with these women to help them achieve their healthiest and happiest selves? ğŸ™

I started a new sport at 29.

For anyone who knows my background, youâ€™ll know I played Gaelic football almost my whole life. 

I know 29 is NOT old. Iâ€™m well aware of this. But when youâ€™re competing against people who started in their early teens itâ€™s pretty late to the party.

I have clients who never consistently exercised until 40.

I have clients who only started becoming knowledgeable on nutrition at 50.

You see the thing is. 

We tell ourselves a story in our head.

Iâ€™ll wait until Monday.

Iâ€™ll wait until next month.

Iâ€™ll start in the New Year.

Itâ€™s easy to say weâ€™ll start - when weâ€™re ready. Or until we have time to commit to it.

You see the thing is. Weâ€™re actually not guaranteed time. My Dad died at 55. Him dying at such a young age, made me truely value time! 

If you want something, you have to start now. Not when youâ€™re ready or when the perfect circumstances arise. You have to be willing to start now.

Iâ€™ve 3 competitions coming up over the next few months and I am BUZZING! You see I decided I want to become the healthiest, fittest and strongest version of myself and thatâ€™s the commitment Iâ€™ve made to myself.

Thereâ€™s 11 weeks left in 2022. 11 weeks could get you started to becoming the healthiest and happiest version of yourself. If youâ€™re sick of waiting for the right time and want to make a change NOW. Dm me â€˜CHANGEâ€™.

Letâ€™s talk sacrifice.

Thereâ€™s no doubt about it. In order to achieve our goals - we need to make sacrifice.

I do believe however, our sacrifices have to be less extreme and a lot more sustainable.
For example: People who embark on diets of no sugar, no carbs and no alcohol would be much better off just reducing the frequency and quantity of these foods or drinks in their diet.

My client Jennifer has dramatically reduced her alcohol consumption. Sheâ€™s not taking extreme measures or going off it forever but she doesnâ€™t prioritise it anymore.

Personally, I have a lot of competitions coming up over the next few weeks so I will definitely have to make sacrifices. Socialising takes a back seat during these busy periods.

Sacrifice is inevitable. But what you sacrifice is up to you. Stop with the extremes of 0 or 100%. Find the right balance and enjoy a life where you can achieve your results and NOT give up everything you like and enjoy ğŸ™

How many times have you had an idea of what you were going to wear only to try it on, take it off and change about 7 million times after that? 

How many items of clothes are you â€˜savingâ€™ or waiting to fit back into them? ğŸ¤”

How many times have you looked in the mirror and picked at every imperfection you have? ğŸ¥¹

This has to change âŒâŒâŒ

And you my darling have the power to change this ğŸ™

You see my Strong and Sassy programme has helped people with this exact problem ğŸ™

How?
âœ… Building self confidence and self esteem
âœ… Building a bullet proof mindset 
âœ… Working on yourself - inside and out 

I want you to feel incredible in any clothes you wear whether it be a ball gown or a bikini.

And you CAN achieve this! But you have to be willing to put in the work â¤ï¸

Successful testing week âœ…

The last 4 months I have not been focusing on strength so I wasnâ€™t expecting any significant strength gains. And thatâ€™s ok, my training is periodised and I have other fish to fry so goals change.

The reason this testing week was so successful was Iâ€™ve been hugely focusing on technique and being pain free ğŸ™Œ

For me personally, this is key. Itâ€™s all well and good clocking up big numbers but if your technique sucks - it will catch up on you in one way or another.

Personal wins for me this week:

âœ… My beautiful snatch ğŸ¥° Because I am FINALLY squat snatching my numbers actually went up to but honestly if my numbers remained the same and I improved my technique I would have been happy.

âœ… Iâ€™m also finally squat cleaning - my body is still in a little bit of shock (if youâ€™re a power clean person youâ€™ll know what I mean) but slowly but surely Iâ€™m getting more confident and comfortable under that bar.

âœ… PB Split Jerk - again due to technique improvement ğŸ™Œ

âœ… Shoulder Pressing - pain free. For a LONG time Iâ€™ve had pain while shoulder pressing and it made me shy away from the movement. How good is it to move a weight without pain ğŸ™

âœ… Gymnastics - my obvious downfall when it comes to CF but with INCREDIBLE guidance and coaching - this weakness is starting to become much better. And again, doing it with a structured programme has allowed for pain free movement.

Iâ€™ve realised with the right programme and mentoring anything is possible. 

So please no matter what your goals are there is a roadmap for you to achieve them. You may not have found it in the past, but that doesnâ€™t mean you canâ€™t find it in the future. Remember your goals. Remember not everyoneâ€™s are the same and what works for someone else - may not work for you. But donâ€™t give up trying ğŸ™

caption:
I knew that taking more time to work on kicking and shooting would mean that I would improve at scoring. Itâ€™s a known fact. Work on your skill. Drill that skill. You become better.

But I never did it. And thus, I NEVER became better at scoring ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸

Information is NOT transformation.

You see I get this all the time.

â€˜I know what to do. I need to eat better and move more.â€™

But information is NOT transformation.

Just because you know it - doesnâ€™t mean youâ€™ll do it!

During my whole football career, I wanted to be a forward. But I didnâ€™t apply my knowledge. 

This story reminds me of most peoples health and fitness journey. Most people know what to do - but donâ€™t apply it!

Maybe if I had someone keeping me accountable - Amanda to achieve x, you need to do extra shooting drills 3 times a week. Honestly, I think I would have done it! Or if I had some encouragement to try and achieve it!

Maybe all youâ€™re missing is that encouragement to go and achieve your health and fitness goals. Maybe you need someone to be accountable to you - to do the work for you.  You need to eat x,y & z and train Monday, Wednesday, Friday.

Information is NOT transformation!

Who knows if I had used my information more wisely - maybe Iâ€™d still be playing today ğŸ˜‚

caption:
Real women. Real results.

Thereâ€™s no criteria to becoming a Strong and Sassy female. Thereâ€™s no age limit or fitness level required.

What I do expect - 
ğŸ”¥ Commitment
ğŸ”¥ To show up 
ğŸ”¥ Enjoy the person you are about to become

âœ¨Aoibheann has been with me for quite awhile. She originally started during lockdown and had fantastic physical results. She came back to me recently to strike a balance between socialising and commiting to her health and fitness. Having turned 30 at the weekend - she is feeling the best

âœ¨ Simone is a working momma who initially signed up for 6 months but ended up staying a year ğŸ˜ She honestly had every excuse to NOT prioritise herself but she didnâ€™t let the excuses get in her way. 8kg later - sheâ€™s the healthiest fittest version of herself and everyone is noticing.

âœ¨ Teresa had been consistently training before coming to me. Once she had that nailed she wanted to dial in on her nutrition. While she worked immensely hard on her nutrition we also educated her on the importance of sleep and stress management and her coffee intake DRAMATICALLY decreased.

âœ¨ Laura (teacher) wanted to find a balance and get back into a good exercise regime. Not only did she lose weight on the scales but her confidence grew exponentially.

These are just the physical results you can achieve from doing my Strong and Sassy programme. In my opinion, the mental changes are what makes this different!

I almost cried when I woke up Monday morningâ€¦

Teresa had sent me this photo -beaming from ear to ear with pride.

She had just completed a half marathon in 2hours 18mins.

Let me tell you a little bit about Teresaâ€™s journey.

Firstly, and probably most importantly - she thought Online Coaching was a scam ğŸ˜…

She didnâ€™t know what she had signed up to with her initial call with Brian but she went for it anyway ğŸ™ˆ

After realising it wasnâ€™t a scam and after a great consultation call - she actually realised this was the perfect programme for her lifestyle (sheâ€™s a working mother).

She initially signed up to 12 weeks and had an initial goal of running a 10km.

6 months later - she has signed up for ANOTHER 3 Months AND completed a half marathon.

This isnâ€™t a fluke.

This is what you get when you surround yourself with a great like minded community and a coach who supports and educated you.

Teresa now describes the programme as â€˜her timeâ€™ and the best investment sheâ€™s ever made in herself.

If youâ€™re a working mum like Teresa, and gyms donâ€™t work for you, you need guidance and education or even just a little bit of â€˜you timeâ€™ get in contact today ğŸ™Œ

I had a conversation in my DMs at the weekend that really made me smile so I thought Iâ€™d share.

I put up a question box asking â€˜why people like following meâ€™ and a lovely lady responded â€˜Confident, go getterâ€™.

Wow ğŸ¤© 

That is EXACTLY how Iâ€™d like to be described.

This absolutely warmed my heart because honestly that has not always been the case.

When I was younger I conformed to societal norms. I REALLY REALLY wanted to be liked. I craved attention so badly. To the naked eye - I probably appeared Uber confident. I was loud and always trying to be the centre of attention. 

I defined my worth on how many friends I had. How much money I had. Having the latest brands and caking my face in make up. I genuinely believed â€˜that is what confident isâ€™.

But I couldnâ€™t have been more wrong.

I was young and immature. 

I donâ€™t regret it. Because I truely believe these things mould you into the person you become.

I now realise confidence is not walking into a room expecting and hoping people will like me. Confidence is walking into a room and not caring if they do!

Confidence is wearing a bikini or dress at any time of the year and not worrying about what anyone else thinks.

Confidence is belief in yourself and your own abilities but never belittling someone else for your gain.

Confidence is NOT something youâ€™re born with. Confidence is something you have to work on -  day in day out. Itâ€™s something you have to talk to yourself about. Something that needs reassurance from time to time. 

But confidence will make you happier than any scale weight, any dress size or any weight lifted.

And guess what - itâ€™s my speciality.

So if youâ€™re looking to gain some confidence - hit me up ğŸ¤™

How can I eat up to 3,000 Calories a day â¬‡ï¸

1. My lean muscle mass means that my BMR is higher. More muscle = more calories

2. Resistance training - lifting weights supports an increased BMR. Lifting weights does not need to be in a gym - remember half my clients train from home and achieve incredible results.

3. Iâ€™ve been training at a high level - both cardio and strength for 10+ years - time frame matters

4. The type of food I consume - NOT JUST CALORIES - I support a balanced lifestyle but most of my nutrition comes from wholefoods

5. I sleep 7.5-8 hours a night

6. Alcohol is not a priority. It doesnâ€™t mean I donâ€™t drink. It means Iâ€™d rather train on a Saturday morning than drink on a Friday night. 

If you want to stop fad dieting and you donâ€™t want to spend your life on 1,200 calorie diets, miserable and hungry - come to the dark side ğŸ‘¹

caption:
Yesterday, I told you about a common problem that most women experience when trying to change their body shape. 

No matter what diet they do, they can't stick to it at weekends.... 

To fix this problem I get my clients to find their non negotiables. 

What are non negotiables?
They are habits you can stick to NO MATTER WHAT the circumstances are. 

I usually recommend 3 of them.. 

3 things you can stick to every weekend.
For example - Drink 2 litres of water, walk 10,000 steps daily and 1 piece of fruit. 

It's pretty simple. Try this out and let me know how it goes. 

P.s I'm looking for 5 MORE ladies who want to be bikini confident year round without giving up the foods they enjoy. If that's you DM me 'Bikini'.

A common problem I see most women have when they are trying to change their body shape is their struggle to stay on track at weekends ğŸ’ğŸ· 

You may notice yourself cutting calories during the week and then all hell breaks lose at weekends and you're afraid that if you continue this way you'll never achieve that bikini body ğŸ˜¢ 

It's so frustrating because you're really trying to make a change. What's actually causing this is a binge restrict cycle that you've developed over the years. We only know and understand nutrition at 2 levels - 'really good' or 'really bad' 

I've found the best solution to fix this is to SAY NO to the all or nothing approach - but this will require help. Accountability to someone who knows what they're talking about can definitely help with this. I've also found having non negotiables proves very helpful. 

Are you interested in learning about non negotiables? I'm going to teach it to you tomorrow. 

Comment 'me' below and I'll tag you tomorrow when it's up.

ğŸš¨ ATTENTION ğŸš¨

I'm looking for 3 fabulous females who want to be bikini confident year round without restriction in the next 12 weeks. 

Take a look at how some of my Strong and Sassy females did: 

- Simoneâ€™s (busy mum) habits are now as engrained as brushing her teeth

- Emily (new mum) lost 14kg and in her words â€˜is in the best shape of her lifeâ€™ 

- Michelle (busy professional) lost NOTHING on the scales but look at the change to her shape

I'm looking for a few specific things from my ladies. So if you: 

 ğŸ”¥Are committed to finally changing your habits.
ğŸ”¥Are able to train 3 times a week
ğŸ”¥ Consider yourself to be coachable
ğŸ”¥ And are ready to get pushed out of your comfort zone. 

Then just comment below with the words 'I'M IN' and I'll be choosing people today. 

(Check your DMs and/or message requests regularly ğŸ˜ If you don't want to miss a message from me)

Not just a one trick pony ğŸ”¥

Being fit is hugely important to me. But fitness is pretty all rounded. I donâ€™t just want to be able to lift weights and be out of breath walking up stairs.

One of the main reasons I love CrossFit is because it incorporates so many elements of fitness. I feel proud to have a body weight and a half back squat but also a 7.42 2km Row.

I set myself this challenge of completing a half marathon in sub 2 hours. With 13 runs in the bag over the last 2 months - it hit my target ğŸ¯ 

Thank you so much for all the well wishes and to everyone who donated to â€˜Australian Cancer Research Foundationâ€™. 

As much as my Dad would be so proud looking down on me today. I am not a runner ğŸ˜‚ But challenge âœ…

caption:
Is protein really that important? ğŸ¤”
.
.
1. Amino Acids are proteins building blocks and we NEED these for recovery. Remember recovery is not only essential if you train, our bodies recover every single day.

2. Satiety - every sit down to eat 3 chicken breasts? Doubtful because protein rich foods are so filling. They also help stabilise our blood sugars and reduce cravings. So get your protein in ğŸ‘Š

3. Thermic Effect from Food (TEF) - Did you know that TEF has the same effect on our TDEE as purposeful exercise? ğŸ¤” Did you know protein actually requires more energy to break down than fats or carbohydrates? ğŸ¤” So double whammy here ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Long story short - eat yo protein ğŸ¤¤
.
.
 How much?
ğŸ’« Gold Standard = 2g/kg BW/day 
(But anything between 1.5-2 is very good)
.
.

5 Reasons youâ€™re not achieving your results ğŸš¨ğŸš¨

2. You are impatient - we want results yesterday ğŸ˜– As opposed to playing the long game with our health, we put a time line on it and expect our results to reflect that time line.

3. Your goals are totally unrealistic - Having abs as a female (for majority of females) requires two things.
A. An unhealthy body fat percentage 
B. Sacrifices most people are NOT willing to make to achieve it. 
So lower your expectations ğŸ™

4. What is your why? 
I want to lose weight is not enough. When the motivation is low - â€˜I want to lose weight wonâ€™t cut itâ€™. 

â€˜I want to feel amazing on my wedding dayâ€™

â€˜I want to feel comfortable in a bikiniâ€™

Anyone who has ever played sport - if the other team scores do you just quit? No you continue playing until the end.

Unlike sport, your health and fitness should not have an end date or time. You should always be playing the long game and finding a sustainable approach to the person you want to become.

Protein Squares

Ingredients: (makes 6)
Tbsp maple syrup
3 tbsp coconut oil
4 heaped tbsp peanut butter 
2 scoops protein powder
4 Corncakes
50g Dark Chocolate 

Heat coconut oil, syrup and peanut butter. Add 2 scoops protein and stir. Crush corncakes and add to mixture. Stir and coat corncakes. Place in baking tray and spoon melted dark chocolate over. Place in fridge for 2 hours.

Save for later.

caption:
Throwback to one of my last trips away. Next on the agenda is Fiji ğŸ‡«ğŸ‡¯â¤ï¸ 

A parcel arrived yesterday with some holiday and summer pieces and it got me thinking ğŸ¤” 

Things have changed so much in the last few yearsâ€¦

A few years ago, 4 weeks out from a holiday I would be cutting carbs and doing crunches for that bikini ğŸ‘™ 

Now, the bikini takes me as I am. â¤ï¸

There is nothing WRONG with wanting to look and feel good in a bikini. Actually the total contrary I think it is VITALLY important for us. 

But contrary to what people think, being smaller DOES NOT equal happier ğŸ˜±

If you are not happy in a bikini, you need to find out why ğŸ¤” When you get to the root of it, more often than not youâ€™ll realise the bikini was never the problem! 

I strived to be smaller and leaner. And at my smallest and leanest, I was still direly uncomfortable in a bikini ğŸ˜±ğŸ¥¹

Now, Iâ€™m happy, healthy and strong. Iâ€™m at least a dress size bigger and sometimes I chaf ğŸ™Š But, now putting on a bikini does not bother me.

I want to help women realise your dress size has nothing to do with your happiness. That scale weight is just one representation of progress. I want women to put on a bikini and stop worrying about how they look and focus more on how they feel â¤ï¸

This is my mission. Iâ€™m already on the road to success. Who wants to join me? ğŸ¥‚

- Iâ€™m not fit enough
- I could never look like that

If you donâ€™t try - that is the ONLY time you will fail. 

Quick story - once upon a time I studied to become a fitness instructor. I felt so far out of my depth at the gym with everyone that was there. We had to strength test. One of the tests was chin ups (I was no where NEAR being able to do a chin up) so the alternative was an inverted row. I couldnâ€™t even do 1 inverted row. Last week, I did a workout with 15 Inverted Rows which I did WITH EASE!!!! 8 years later, the effort I have been putting in is coming to fruition.

But Iâ€™d much rather a Saturday morning gym session to a Friday night drink session.

Iâ€™d rather spend my money on food and supplements than alcohol and drugs. 

Iâ€™ve more gym gear than I do â€˜normalâ€™ clothes.

Meet Michelle 

Michelle (31) is a busy dog mom who came to me in January and needed accountability. She also wanted education and a long term solution to health and fitness.

Michelle was very sporty when she was younger and when she gets into a good routine she feels great. She is competitive so exercise is not a problem for her.

Her goals included fat loss and body confidence and feeling pride in what sheâ€™s doing.

Well I guess you could say sheâ€™s achieving her goals ğŸ’ª Thankfully, she has a great training environment with incredible programming. Last week she hit PBs in all her lifts - this lady is STRONG ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª

She is getting strong AF (110kg 3 RM Deadlift, 90kg 3RM Squat, 42.5kg 3 RM bench) but her body shape is changing ğŸ‘‰

Now here is the mind blowing fact ğŸ¤¯ Michelle has not changed on the scales - this is the EXACT reason why we should NOT use scales as our only measure of progress.

6 months in and she is achieving BIG things ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª

Would you like results like Michelle? Dm me!

ğƒğ¨ğ§'ğ­ ğ§ğğ ğ¥ğğœğ­ ğŸğšğ­ğ¬
.
.
Fat gets a bad rep. 
Sure it is 9Kcal per gram but it is an essential part of a balanced fat. 
.
.
Fats provide us with energy, makes up our cell membranes of our brain and nervous system. Fats are necessary to transport vitamins A,D,E and K and make and balance certain hormones.
.
.
Dietary Fat can be found in 2 forms:
Saturated â€“ mainly found in animal products like meat, dairy, eggs, coconut
Unsaturated â€“ found in marine sources like fish oils, as well as nuts, seeds and vegetable oils
.
. 
For years saturated fat was thought to be associated with higher risk of Cardiovascular Disease and so it was deemed as â€˜unhealthyâ€™ or â€˜bad for youâ€™. The problem with saturated fat was not the actual fat itself but rather the increased consumption of processed food or the large quantities of saturated fat products. Saturated fat helps increase the cholesterol production in the body which is an essential part of metabolism and in the production of steroid hormones. So saturated fat should feature in our diet, just maybe donâ€™t latter every meal in butter.
.
. 
Unsaturated fats are made up of mono and polyunsaturated fats.  These contain our omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids. Omega 3 fatty acids open our airways and blood vessels. They reduce our blood lipids and cholesterol and lower inflammation and pain. Omega 6 fatty acids do the opposite. Both are needed in the body, without both we wouldnâ€™t heal or recover from exercise. The problem with Western diets is that we donâ€™t have the proper ratios. We are at about 10:1 where we should be at 2:1 (omega 6/omega 3).
.
. 
Low fat diets were a fad a few years ago. While people reduced calories, they increased their intake of processed foods. Diets lacked fats and fat soluble vitamins so instead of being healthier people were losing weight but were not healthier.
.
. 
Fats are an essential part of any healthy diet. Be aware that they are very calorie dense so portion control may be important and donâ€™t opt for processed versions. Enjoy them as part of a balanced lifestyle.

caption:
By saying yes to something - you are ultimately saying no to something else.

Iâ€™ll give you a little example - at the weekend I had a CrossFit competition - it meant I had to say no to a friends birthday on Saturday.

For years and years, I gave up all my social Occassions to say yes to playing football.

I used to be a yes person. I would say yes to everything - Iâ€™d help everyone.
At one stage when I lived at home I was:
Managing a gym, looking after my mother who was in hospital, playing football with Roscommon and Garrycastle, helping train Roscommon u14 girls AND Garrycastle Minor girls ğŸ˜µâ€ğŸ’«ğŸ¥´ Thatâ€™s not to mention trying to spend time with my partner and friends.

I learned how to say no from working with a life coach and it was one of the best things Iâ€™ve ever learned to do. I encourage and promote saying no to things with my clients too.

Saying no has added benefits - not only are you NOT doing what you donâ€™t WANT to do but you end up saying yes to what you do want.

An example of saying no. Last bank holiday weekend I refused to make plans - I wanted to just go with the flow - see what happened, I ultimately wanted to chill. I said no to making plans and in turn I had a lovely chilled, relaxed weekend ğŸ«¶

Are you a yes or a no person?

caption:
I've always been very open minded.
.
.
I pride myself on it actually. I've alway been a pro choice kinda girl in all aspects of life (not just health and fitness related). You'll never hear me boast about one type of diet or slate any either. You won't hear me downgrade any form of exercise, although I do openly talk about the huge benefits of resistance training ğŸ’ª I'll never tell any of my client's 'you cannot eat this for weight loss'. If someone who loves yoga comes to me, I'm not going to force them to lift weights. And if someone who is vegan comes to me, I would not force them to eat animal products. My problem with any of these things lies in the misinformation. 
.
.
Did you know that vegan fast food production has sky rocketed in recent years? ğŸ¤” Similarly, a few years ago, gluten free products were a huge trend? And before that, sugar free was the hype? This I have a problem with.
.
.
Veganism is a lifestyle choice. I have huge respect for anyone's lifestyle choices, whether they conform to my own is irrelevant. What actually annoys me is actual vegans are getting a terrible name due to all these people jumping on the bandwagon, thinking veganism is the healthiest lifestyle going. People are going into this lifestyle, uneducated and naive. ğŸ˜’ It was the same a few years ago when gluten free was the buzzword. Did you know you can have a totally adequate, balanced, healthy diet without adding one gluten free product? And thats for ACTUAL coeliacs out there, because they are the ONLY people that need to be eating gluten free toast ğŸ˜‚
.
.
What my very long winded post is trying to say is stop jumping on bandwagons. If you are and always have been vegan, that's fine. Continue with your choices. If you are coeliac, continue with your gluten free bread ğŸ™ˆ 
.
For the rest of you, stop following trends by the latest celebrity diet.
â Stop conforming to social norms âœŠ 
âStop basing your beliefs on a bloody stupid documentary ğŸ˜’ 
âœ…Get some advice from a professional. ğŸ™
âœ… Follow said advice ğŸŒˆ 
âœ… And unfollow anyone giving terrible, uneducated advice 
.
.
#propaganda #foodfear

caption:
7 things I wish I knew in my early 20s. I dont want you to make the same mistakes I made.

1. Being consistently good is better than being occasionally perfect.

2. The weekend makes up a large part of the week. If you think youâ€™re being good during the week and not making progress - take a look at your weekends.

3. Sleep is one of the most underestimated tools to help you achieve ANY goal. If youâ€™re sleep is shit and youâ€™re sacrificing it â€˜to seize the morningâ€™ and train at 6am - you may be doing more harm than good.

4. Water consumption is the simplest way to becoming a healthier version of yourself. Stop looking at fad diets, detox teas, apple cider vinegar and look at your hydration status. Dehydration affects every system in our body and can lead to lack of energy, low mood, injury and brain fog (to mention afew).

5. Human connection, vitamin D and exercise are some of the most under utilised mental health prescriptions. Try increase all of these on the daily to see an instant mood shift ğŸ™

6. Stop trying to be a people pleaser and learn to say no - you are your own most important asset. 

7. Live every day like itâ€™s your last â¤ï¸ Do what makes you happy! 

Would you add anything to the list?

How I became stronger, happier and more confident and how you can too. 

When I started in the fitness industry I was a little lost. I was focused on how I looked. I was obsessed with having abs. I only ate 'clean' food mid week which led to weekend binges. My relationship with nutrition and fitness definitely was not a healthy one. 

I wasn't happy. Not in my body. Not in my mind. I genuinely couldn't imagine continuing my life with this level of restriction and I began to resent the gym ğŸ˜¢ 

Then I stopped focusing so much on HOW I looked. I stopped looking for abs every time I walked by the mirror. I started to appreciate resistance training and I began focusing on how much stronger I was becoming. My goals changed. Performance based goals replaced the quest for abs and I found my love for exercise again. I found a balanced approach to nutrition. I still eat very healthy and nutritious but I no longer restrict myself. 

I no longer focus on HOW I look but WHAT my body can do. I wear bikinis now without dieting to get in them. I'm stronger and fitter than I've ever been and clothes sizes no longer dictate my life. I'm happier and healthier. I love the skin I'm in â¤ 

And that's why I created my Strong and Sassy Programme to help women become bikini confident year round without restrictions. Comment 'CHANGE' below if you'd like for me to personally message you today and see if I can help you!

Yesterday, I told you about a common problem that most women experience when trying to change their body shape. 

No matter what diet they do, they can't stick to it at weekends.... 

To fix this problem I get my clients to find their non negotiables. 

What are non negotiables?
They are habits you can stick to NO MATTER WHAT the circumstances are. 

I usually recommend 3 of them.. 

3 things you can stick to every weekend.
For example - Drink 2 litres of water, walk 10,000 steps daily and 1 piece of fruit. 

It's pretty simple. Try this out and let me know how it goes. 

P.s I'm looking for 5 MORE ladies who want to be bikini confident year round without giving up the foods they enjoy. If that's you DM me 'Bikini'.

caption:
A common problem I see most women have when they are trying to change their body shape is their struggle to stay on track at weekends ğŸ’ğŸ· 

You may notice yourself cutting calories during the week and then all hell breaks lose at weekends and you're afraid that if you continue this way you'll never achieve that bikini body ğŸ˜¢ 

It's so frustrating because you're really trying to make a change. What's actually causing this is a binge restrict cycle that you've developed over the years. We only know and understand nutrition at 2 levels - 'really good' or 'really bad' 

I've found the best solution to fix this is to SAY NO to the all or nothing approach - but this will require help. Accountability to someone who knows what they're talking about can definitely help with this. I've also found having non negotiables proves very helpful.

caption:
I canâ€™t believe I still have to explain this but here I go again ğŸ’â€â™€ï¸
.
.
When people said to Arnold Schwarzenegger 
'Oh but I don't want to look like you.'

He replied:
'Don't worry. You never will.'
.
.
Let me tell you. Building muscle is BLOODY HARD. You don't just wake up one day and 'are bulky' ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜…
.
.
I've spent YEARS improving myself and getting stronger, fitter and healthier. That is my goal. So don't think after lifting afew weights you're going to gain 10kg of muscle and look 'bulky'. And honestly, most people will NEVER EVER train as hard as I train ğŸ˜… 
.
.
But let me also tell you. Majority of the photos I take are mid or post training when I have a serious pump. In normal clothes, I'm a normal size 8-10 female. I don't have jacked quads or a shoulder vein ğŸ˜… (Even though I'd be happy to walk around like that)
.
.
Moral of the story: most people will never train hard enough to get bulky. Most people don't walk round jacked ğŸ˜… The 'toned' look you want is actually muscle - so if you say you want to be 'toned' and don't want muscle you're actually contradicting yourself ğŸ˜…

Oh and if it wasn't already obvious - lift weights ğŸ‹â€â™€ï¸

.
100 Calories Apple = 100 Calorie Chocolate Bar (as a measure of calories). But you cannot compare them in composition. The lack of micronutrients, the high sugar and fat content in the chocolate bar cannot be easily compared to the vitamins, mineral, water and phytonutrients in the apple ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Since when was Maths ever that simple ğŸ˜… I am not saying Calories in versus calories out is non sense, because it isn't. It makes sense and is very important. All I'm saying is, it's not the ONLY thing that is important. Food quality matters for long term health benefits and body composition ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Questions? ğŸ¤”

caption:
Is protein really that important? ğŸ¤”
.
.
1. Amino Acids are proteins building blocks and we NEED these for recovery. Remember recovery is not only essential if you train, our bodies recover every single day.

2. Satiety - every sit down to eat 3 chicken breasts? Doubtful because protein rich foods are so filling. They also help stabilise our blood sugars and reduce cravings. So get your protein in ğŸ‘Š

3. Thermic Effect from Food (TEF) - Did you know that TEF has the same effect on our TDEE as purposeful exercise? ğŸ¤” Did you know protein actually requires more energy to break down than fats or carbohydrates? ğŸ¤” So double whammy here ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Long story short - eat yo protein ğŸ¤¤
.
.
 How much?
ğŸ’« Gold Standard = 2g/kg BW/day 
(But anything between 1.5-2 is very good)
.
.

caption:
Health and Happiness ğŸ™

These are the two most important things to me. And I try to preach this believe to my clients ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸

â›”ï¸If you are looking for a quick fix, Iâ€™m not your girl.
â›”ï¸If you are looking for an 8 week challenge, Iâ€™m not your girl.

But if you want to become the healthiest and happiest version of yourself - Dm me â€˜Healthâ€™.

READ THE CAPTION! 

This one is important.

For those of you who donâ€™t know - my Dad died of pancreatic cancer aged 50 (5 days before his 51st birthday).

Since his death, two things have been hugely prominent in my life - 
1. Your health is your wealth 
2. I was put on this Earth to help people 

Yesterday I paid almost $600 on blood tests. The receptionist asked me â€˜Are you sure you want this one? Itâ€™s the most expensiveâ€™ (the blood test in Question was related to my Dads condition which I want to do any test for that I can). 
I actually couldnâ€™t believe she asked me that ğŸ¤” But I realised people have probably declined to pay that price. Iâ€™m not gonna lie the price came as a shock to me, and I had to fiddle between bank accounts to hand it over. But never ONCE did it cross my mind to not pay. You see to me, my health is priceless. I am willing to invest or hand over WHATEVER I need to, to ensure I am as healthy as I possibly can be. And to me, that money was a NECESSITY! 

I cannot believe people put a price on their health ğŸ˜± Your health literally is your wealth! 

That brings me to my second realisation. I need to help as many women as possible in this world to realise your health is your wealth. Not just physical, but mental too. 
â›”ï¸Hating your body is not healthy
â›”ï¸ Constant dieting is not healthy
â›”ï¸ Exercising to burn calories is not healthy
â›”ï¸ Trying to look like someone else is not healthy

I want to educate women about nutrition without restriction. I want to help women become the healthiest, happiest, most confident versions of themselves â¤ï¸ğŸ™
If you want to make a change to your health, Dm me â€˜Healthâ€™ today ğŸ™Œ

caption:
It's not just about WHAT you eat, but HOW and WHY you eat ğŸ™Œ
.
.
What I've learned over the last 8 years in the fitness industry:
.
.
People THINK eating better, exercising  more and losing weight will make them feel better. 
.
.
What ACTUALLY makes people feel better is healing their relationships with food and exercise. And absolutely no shape, size or weight will make you feel better unless you're happy and content within yourself ğŸ™
.
.
I've developed an ebook that will help with your mindset towards nutrition and health in general. If you're interested in a copy - comment 'ME' below ğŸ‘‡

ğ•Šğ•’ğ•ğ•– ğ•¤ğ•’ğ•ğ•– ğŸ’â€â™€ï¸
.
.
When people said to Arnold Schwarzenegger 
'Oh but I don't want to look like you.'

He replied:
'Don't worry. You never will.'
.
.
Let me tell you. Building muscle is BLOODY HARD. You don't just wake up one day and 'are bulky' ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜…
.
.
I've spent YEARS improving myself and getting stronger, fitter and healthier. That is my goal. So don't think after lifting afew weights you're going to gain 10kg of muscle and look 'bulky'. And honestly, most people will NEVER EVER train as hard as I train ğŸ˜… 
.
.
But let me also tell you. Majority of the photos I take are mid or post training when I have a serious pump. In normal clothes, I'm a normal size 8-10 female. I don't have jacked quads or a shoulder vein ğŸ˜… (Even though I'd be happy to walk around like that)
.
.
Moral of the story: most people will never train hard enough to get bulky. Most people don't walk round jacked ğŸ˜… The 'toned' look you want is actually muscle - so if you say you want to be 'toned' and don't want muscle you're actually contradicting yourself ğŸ˜…

Oh and if it wasn't already obvious - lift weights ğŸ‹â€â™€ï¸

P.s Those tan lines though ğŸ˜…

caption:
ğ•€ ğ•˜ğ•–ğ•¥ ğ•“ğ• ğ•£ğ•–ğ••...
.
.
Sick of chicken and broccoli? ğŸ¤”
.
.
You will quickly run out of ideas if you try to change whole meals so why not change up the sides ğŸ’â€â™€ï¸
.
.
From my experience, people tend to like certain foods. If you stick with the foods you like, you're more likely to stick with it ğŸ™ 
.
.
So my advice:
- Change the vegetables - not just the type but how you cook them - stir fry, boil, steam, roast. 

- Change the carb source - sick of brown rice? Add quinoa or cous cous! Sick of potato, try sweet potato.

- Rotate Week 1 - Chicken and pork based meals. Week 2 - Tofu and tuna based meals. Week 3 - Turkey & Salmon based meals. Week 4 - Prawn & Beef based meals. And start the cycle again ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Save this post for later ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸

caption:
Christmas is over ğŸ’¥ 
.
.
Now from my experience, during lockdowns or home isolation, one of the biggest habits people are  developing is daily alcohol drinking. And openly admitted when working from home, the time would get earlier and earlier ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I am not anti alcohol. Actually I am the polar opposite. I encourage clients to have a glass of wine at weekends if that is what truely makes them happy. It's important to have balance in your life ğŸ™
.
.
I do believe though that alcohol is a little too readily available and can be 'too easy' to use as an escape. 
.
.
I implore people to find other things to pass their time. Exercise, walk, bake, knit, zoom call, cook, spring clean, learn a new skill ... the list goes on. But please don't let alcohol be the ONLY thing you look forward to daily ğŸ™ğŸ™ğŸ™

caption:
Spot the difference ğŸ”
.
.
When people say to me they 'want to lose weight', more often than not - it's fat loss they are actually seeking. And there is a difference ğŸ‘†
.
.
Weight loss is a combination of fat, muscle and water. When people go on very restrictive diets they often see a huge scale shift on week 1 due to a reduction in total body water - as opposed to fat loss. 
.
.
If people focus solely on scale loss unfortunately there is likely to be muscle mass loss - which is what we don't want. As far as I'm aware some diet clubs actually discourage resistance training as it will lead to muscle gain (and essentially an increase on the scales) ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
Ladies, please please understand smaller â‰  happier ğŸš«
.
.
If someone is overweight/obese, weight loss should be the goal to a healthier overall body composition ğŸ™
.
.
Anyone else - Fat Loss is what you should be seeking ğŸ‘†
.
.

I tried to do this while managing a gym, commuting, playing with 2 football teams, studying, trying to maintain friendships and a relationship. I felt like I was just surviving as opposed to living ğŸ˜¢
.

And then I took control of my life. I started to look after myself first and everybody else's needs and wants came second.

'The app was great because it logged all the stats and I wanted to see improvements and log into that'. The programme worked around me, football and my injuries. 

Fast forward 12 weeks and Eimear cannot believe the change it has made not only to her physically but mentally too. Her confidence is through the roof on and off the pitch.

caption:
Yesterday I told you about time being a problem for women trying to change their body shape. They feel they can't give full commitment to a programme because they are too busy. 

They feel they have no time to go to the gym because they are too busy. 

Thankfully a lot of my clients train from home 3 times a week with minimal equipment. 

You see the thing is - you don't actually need hours in the gym to achieve your goals - especially if you're crazy busy. I also encourage women to make better choices if they are too busy to cook. And instead of scrolling on Social media - I set step targets for them (even if they scroll while they walk). 

You see - it's pretty simple. Try this out and let me know how it goes. 

P.s I'm looking for 5 more women who want to become bikini confident with restriction in the next 12 weeks. If that's you, DM me the word 'ME'

Another common problem I see most women have when they are trying to change their body shape is time to commit to a programme. 

We all lead such busy lifestyles these days. We give time to our families, our friends, and work and we are left with little to no time. 

It's so frustrating because you're trying to be a good friend, mother, daughter, sister, colleague, or employee. But what's left for you? Or maybe there is time? 

I've found that most people usually can find time. Maybe instead of an hour of Netflix we could swap it for a workout? Maybe instead of scrolling we could be walking? Or instead of picking up a takeaway on the way home from work, we could pick up a ready meal in a supermarket? The problem lies in trying to do too much.

caption:
How I became stronger, happier and more confident and how you can too. 

When I started in the fitness industry I was a little lost. I was focused on how I looked. I was obsessed with having abs. I only ate 'clean' food mid week which led to weekend binges. My relationship with nutrition and fitness definitely was not a healthy one. 

I wasn't happy. Not in my body. Not in my mind. I genuinely couldn't imagine continuing my life with this level of restriction and I began to resent the gym ğŸ˜¢ 

Then I stopped focusing so much on HOW I looked. I stopped looking for abs every time I walked by the mirror. I started to appreciate resistance training and I began focusing on how much stronger I was becoming. My goals changed. Performance based goals replaced the quest for abs and I found my love for exercise again. I found a balanced approach to nutrition. I still eat very healthy and nutritious but I no longer restrict myself. 

I no longer focus on HOW I look but WHAT my body can do. I wear bikinis now without dieting to get in them. I'm stronger and fitter than I've ever been and clothes sizes no longer dictate my life. I'm happier and healthier. I love the skin I'm in â¤ 

And that's why I created my Strong and Sassy Programme to help women become bikini confident year round without restrictions. Comment 'CHANGE' below if you'd like for me to personally message you today and see if I can help you!

Yesterday, I told you about a common problem that most women experience when trying to change their body shape. 

No matter what diet they do, they can't stick to it at weekends.... 

To fix this problem I get my clients to find their non negotiables. 

What are non negotiables?
They are habits you can stick to NO MATTER WHAT the circumstances are. 

I usually recommend 3 of them.. 

3 things you can stick to every weekend.
For example - Drink 2 litres of water, walk 10,000 steps daily and 1 piece of fruit. 

It's pretty simple. Try this out and let me know how it goes. 

P.s I'm looking for 5 MORE ladies who want to be bikini confident year round without giving up the foods they enjoy. If that's you DM me 'Bikini'.

A common problem I see most women have when they are trying to change their body shape is their struggle to stay on track at weekends ğŸ’ğŸ· 

You may notice yourself cutting calories during the week and then all hell breaks lose at weekends and you're afraid that if you continue this way you'll never achieve that bikini body ğŸ˜¢ 

It's so frustrating because you're really trying to make a change. What's actually causing this is a binge restrict cycle that you've developed over the years. We only know and understand nutrition at 2 levels - 'really good' or 'really bad' 

I've found the best solution to fix this is to SAY NO to the all or nothing approach - but this will require help. Accountability to someone who knows what they're talking about can definitely help with this. I've also found having non negotiables proves very helpful. 

Are you interested in learning about non negotiables? I'm going to teach it to you tomorrow.

caption:
This post may cause a little controversy... 

I'm normally very empathetic but here we go...

You can come up with every excuse under the sun...

â° Time 
ğŸ’° Money 
ğŸ“ Study
ğŸ¦ºWork 
ğŸ‘©â€ğŸ‘§â€ğŸ‘§ Kids
ğŸ¦¿ Injuries 
ğŸ« Illness 

And for every excuse I've heard. I've worked with someone who worked through hardship.

âœ”I've worked with women in pregnancy.

âœ” I've worked with people on the dole. 

âœ”I've worked with people who can only commit 20 mins to exercise because that is literally all they have. 

âœ”I've worked with mothers who get up at 5am because that's the only time they can train.

âœ” I've coached NUMEROUS people with injuries.

âœ” I've worked with people with MS to Cancer.

But at the end of the day they all made the choice to PUT THEMSELVES FIRST. They all decided they were sick of where they were and needed to make a change. They didn't make the excuses you are making to yourself. Instead they took action ğŸ‘Š

Tell me again what's your excuse? ğŸ¤”

Had you told me 7 years ago it would take 5 years for chin ups to become comfortable I'd have been pissed off...

Had you told me I'd break a wrist, dislocate fingers and my knee I'd laugh at you...

I already knew I was losing my Dad ğŸ˜¢

7 years is a long time and a lot can happen but you know what...
The time passes anyway.

7 years of getting stronger. Bring on the next 7 ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª

caption:
Grocery List Essnials ğŸ™Œ
.
.
If these were the only items on your grocery list, you'd actually have a super balanced, nutritious diet ğŸ™
.
.
ğğ«ğ¨ğ­ğğ¢ğ§
Eggs, tuna, Basa and chicken are all great sources of protein. Protein is essential for repair and recovery. Protein keeps us fuller for longer and has the highest TEF (thermic effect from food). 

ğ‚ğšğ«ğ›ğ¨ğ¡ğ²ğğ«ğšğ­ğğ¬
Rice and Oats are complex carbohydrates and give us a slow release in energy. Meanwhile, fruit are simple sugars and give us a quicker release. Carbohydrates is the body's main fuel for energy.

ğ…ğšğ­ğ¬
Avocado, cheese and eggs all contain fats. Good Fats are essential in the diet and can affect our ability to absorb fat soluble vitamins. We also need them for hormone function.

ğŒğ¢ğœğ«ğ¨ğ§ğ®ğ­ğ«ğ¢ğğ§ğ­ğ¬
Colourful food is jam packed with vitamins, minerals and antioxidants. Make sure you're getting enough in your diet ğŸ™

Hit save on this post for your next shopping day ğŸ‘‡

Can't believe it's been a week since our Catch up â¤ğŸ™
.
.
The only con to being an online Coach is not getting to see these incredible ladies in person every day. But some of us finally got to meet up last weekend â¤
.
.
The biggest pro is that I've had groups like this catch up in Ireland and I am working with people in numerous different countries and time zones ğŸ™
.
.
Online coaching has the benefit of:
âœ… Being able to train in your own time
âœ… High level of accountability 
âœ… Nutrition education as opposed to a meal plan
âœ… Like minded community - who catch up weekly on coaching calls, guest speakers, organised online events and in person events ğŸ™ğŸ™Œ
.
.
If this sounds like something you need. Dm me 'Coach' for more details.

ğ‚ğ«ğğšğ­ğ¢ğ§ğ
Creatine is one of the most vastly researched supplements and has been promoted in the fitness industry in the last few years. According to research, supplementation with creatine monohydrate has been shown to increase Skeletal muscle mass, lean body mass and muscle fibre size. Research also suggests past this and it may encourage healthy aging and benefit brain health. 

ğƒğ¨ ğˆ ğ§ğğğ ğ‚ğ«ğğšğ­ğ¢ğ§ğ?
Creatine supplementation can be hugely beneficial for athletic performance and studies have also showed it can have an impact on body composition (prolonged creatine ingestion inducing an increase in fat free mass). 

ğƒğ¨ ğˆ ğ§ğğğ ğ­ğ¨ ğ¥ğ¨ğšğ ğ‚ğ«ğğšğ­ğ¢ğ§ğ?
Nope. 5g daily will suffice. (The idea to saturate the muscle is just to experience benefits sooner).
Increase water consumption when you start taking creatine.

ğ–ğ¡ğğ§ ğ¬ğ¡ğ¨ğ®ğ¥ğ ğˆ ğ­ğšğ¤ğ ğ¢ğ­?
Evidence does suggest post workout is superior to pre workout. 

ğ€ğ«ğ ğ­ğ¡ğğ«ğ ğšğ§ğ² ğ¬ğ¢ğğ ğğŸğŸğğœğ­ğ¬?
- Bloating - This is due to the muscles absorbing the water with the Creatine. Very common and usually subsides when the muscles are saturated.
- Stomach discomfort - May cause stomach sensitivity like bloating.

caption:
It's still possible to progress...

But you may just need some help...

1. One of the most common mistakes I see people make is their lack of structure when it comes to training. Having a 'toned' goal or a strength/performance based goal is very difficult if you're participating in random spin classes or copying what other people do in the gym. If you're looking to change shape or get stronger - follow a progressive plan.

2. Consistency in EVERYTHING is ğŸ”‘ to success. Ask yourself - Can you see yourself doing this in a years time? If the answer is no, chances are you need to change something.

3. Unrealistic goals is a huge problem. Let's give the example of 'Having Abs' for a female. 
Most women have to sacrifice too much to achieve this goal. This leaves them A. Frustrated at not achieving it or B. Achieving it but hating life.
(Notice I said most females - some won't find this difficult at all but they are a minority).

4. Nutrition habits have changed. Again, ask yourself can you see yourself eating this way a year from now - if the answer is no - it's not going to be sustainable.

5. Stress is one of the most overlooked barriers to success. Just like you can't out exercise a bad diet. You can't achieve goals in an utterly stress fried body.

If any of the above sounds like you, I am getting my Strong and Sassy programme ready for the new year ğŸ¥³ DM me 'SAS' if you'd like more information ğŸ‹â€â™€ï¸

caption:
I used to struggle....
.
.
I use struggle with the fact that I don't conform to certain standards and expectations of a woman....
For example:
âœ” I hate cleaning 
âœ” I'm not an exceptional cook
âœ” I don't bake
.
.
âœ” I always wanted to wear comfy sportswear rather than dress up
âœ” I didn't like being told what to do - by anyone ğŸ˜…
.
.
âœ” I prefer going to the gym rather than getting my hair done
âœ” I'd rather a new pair of metcons over an expensive braclet 
âœ” I'd pick a new tatoo over hair extensions
.
.
I struggled with this for years because  this is what I thought women did. I felt I was different. Possibly even there was something wrong with me ğŸ™Š
.
.
Now, I'm happy, confident and comfortable in myself - I realise I am who I am. I won't ever be a typical housewife (and @o_boyce is still with me ğŸ˜…). I'd still rather have calluses than soft hands. And I WILL have a cleaner as I get older ğŸ˜… There is ABSOLUTELY nothing wrong with me. Maybe I am a little different but if we were all the same, the world would be a boring place ğŸ˜…ğŸ™

caption:
Is protein really that important? ğŸ¤”
.
.
1. Amino Acids are proteins building blocks and we NEED these for recovery. Remember recovery is not only essential if you train, our bodies recover every single day.

2. Satiety - every sit down to eat 3 chicken breasts? Doubtful because protein rich foods are so filling. They also help stabilise our blood sugars and reduce cravings. So get your protein in ğŸ‘Š

3. Thermic Effect from Food (TEF) - Did you know that TEF has the same effect on our TDEE as purposeful exercise? ğŸ¤” Did you know protein actually requires more energy to break down than fats or carbohydrates? ğŸ¤” So double whammy here ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Long story short - eat yo protein ğŸ¤¤
.
.
 How much?
ğŸ’« Gold Standard = 2g/kg BW/day 
(But anything between 1.5-2 is very good)
.
.

.
Sport always helped me value my body. But unfortunately as a young girl, sport wasn't enough. I cared deeply about how I looked and I constantly tried to change it. I was always slim but I had such a distorted idea of what I looked like in my head. I always wanted to be leaner. And I was willing to get there in very unhealthy manners.
.
.
Fast forward 10 years ğŸ‘‹
Lifting weights and Crossfit has changed my whole view on my body. I am no longer obsessed with how I look. Like everyone I've days where I feel amazing and days where I feel like a bag of ğŸ’©. But HOW I look doesn't hugely affect me. 
.
.
I am so damn proud of what my body can do. I am so proud that I have been so consistent. I am so proud that I have encouraged so many others to live a similar lifestyle. None of that can be found when fixating on a scale number ğŸ¤”

.
Mindful = Not Mindless
.
.
1. Eat with intent - savour food.

2. Chew your food - did you know you should be chewing your food about 32 times before swallowing? ğŸ™ˆ

3. Eat at a table if possible - avoid eating of your knees in poor posture, avoid standing 

4. Give yourself time - 5 minutes is RARELY enough. Give yourself the time you deserve to take a lunch break

5. Limit distractions - no phones or tvs while eating.
.
.
A lot of the time when we experience stomach discomfort - cramping, bloating etc we put it down to certain foods. Unfortunately our environment and our focus can quite often be a factor and one that is totally overlooked ğŸ¥´
.
.

My hierarchy begins with stress reduction - why?
.
.
Well because stress in all shapes and sizes leads to incredible problems in the body. 
Example: Stress of too little calories - Can lead to hormonal disruptions which can lead to amenorrhoea which can lead to infertility. Too little calories and poor food quality can lead to micronutrient deficiencies and injury.

.

Sleep should be AS IMPORTANT as exercise and nutrition combined - end of storyğŸ˜´

From my experience, people tend to like certain foods. If you stick with the foods you like, you're more likely to stick with it ğŸ™

So my advice:
- Change the vegetables - not just the type but how you cook them - stir fry, boil, steam, roast. 

- Change the carb source - sick of brown rice? Add quinoa or cous cous! Sick of potato, try sweet potato.

caption:
Training with an injury?
.
.
Lets be totally clear on the context. It was training WITH an injury. Not training THROUGH an injury. Very different. 
.
.
However, it is not uncommon to train through an injury either. I want to be clear here. I am NOT telling you to train with an injury. This is very individual dependent and requires advice from a professional I.e Doctor, physio etc.
.
.
âœ…Training with an injury 

ğŸ‘‰ Anyone who knows me, knows how much of an advocate I am of this. When I injure lower body, upper body is still very much manageable, however, I am careful not to put too much pressure on affected area 

ğŸ‘‰ Mental Health - I don't know about the rest of you but mental health is one of my main reasons for training so if I had to sit still I'd cry ğŸ˜© 

ğŸ‘‰ Socialising - It can be a tough time going through an injury. If you are a sports player it can be so isolating ğŸ˜¢ Being able to do something in th gym, in a class or with your team can have a huge impact on your mindframe â¤ 

â¡ï¸ Training through an injury 

ğŸš« Only do under advice from your healthcare professional (But a little bit of important info is there actually is evidence to suggest you can) 

âœ… Nutrition with an injury
â›” Most overlooked aspect of recovery in my opinion 

ğŸ‘‰ Fats are anti inflammatory and a vital part of the healing process 

ğŸ‘‰ Protein as ALWAYS is King ğŸ¤´ 

ğŸ‘‰ Calories will need to be adjusted for activity levels - But do NOT dramatically cut calories. This is where a lot of people go wrong. The body needs food and fuel to repair and recover so while you may not be as active don't underestimate the importance of fuel. 

â¡ï¸Remember Recovery does not just mean 'rest' 

Would love to hear your experiences?

caption:
NOT A TRANSFORMATION POST ğŸ‘†
.
.
Pregnancy was once considered a reason to stop all exercise and eat for two. Which often led to excessive weight gain, gestational diabetes, pre eclampsia, difficult births and difficulty with weight loss post partum. Now, obviously pregnancy is massively different for everyone. Unfortunately there is no one size fits all. But the information I'm giving is general recommendations. If you have any further questions. It is probably worth talking it over with your doctor or other medical professional â˜ºï¸
.
.
Exercise:
-Studies have shown that exercise during pregnancy can actually lead to easier birthing and healthy weight gain during pregnancy.
-It is also thought to be beneficial for post partum weight loss.
-Guidelines for exercise encourage women to stick with similar exercises prior to pregnancy. Light Resistance based training is highly recommended.
- Adaptations may be needed through different trimesters such as: Not lying on your back for too long or overhead extension exercises may need to be removed. This is very dependent on individuals
- Hiit training may not be recommended after trimester 1 - again very dependent on the individual and their training history but it will become a lot harder
- Light exercise like walking can possibly be done the whole way up until due date
- The main take home point from this is: Exercise during pregnancy is encouraged. Everyone's levels, capabilities and pregnancies are different so go with how you're feeling. Don't over exert yourself. And talk with your coach and doctor ğŸ™
.
.
Nutrition
- This idea of eating double for two is non sense ğŸ™ˆ
- Calories shouldn't even be increased in first trimester. Daily calories should be increased by about 300Cals in 2nd trimester and 500Cals in 3rd Trimester.
- There may be food aversions or food cravings during pregnancy - this is totally normal.
- Try to stick with whole nutritious foods
- Supplements include: Folic Acid, Vitamin D, Iron and Omega 3 Fatty acids. But talk to your doctor or health are consultant before taking any of these.
.
.
Something to be very aware of during pregnancy is labelling. Continued belowğŸ‘‡

caption:
ğƒğ¨ğ§'ğ­ ğ§ğğ ğ¥ğğœğ­ ğŸğšğ­ğ¬
.
.
Fat gets a bad rep. 
Sure it is 9Kcal per gram but it is an essential part of a balanced fat. 
.
.
Fats provide us with energy, makes up our cell membranes of our brain and nervous system. Fats are necessary to transport vitamins A,D,E and K and make and balance certain hormones.
.
.
Dietary Fat can be found in 2 forms:
Saturated â€“ mainly found in animal products like meat, dairy, eggs, coconut
Unsaturated â€“ found in marine sources like fish oils, as well as nuts, seeds and vegetable oils
.
. 
For years saturated fat was thought to be associated with higher risk of Cardiovascular Disease and so it was deemed as â€˜unhealthyâ€™ or â€˜bad for youâ€™. The problem with saturated fat was not the actual fat itself but rather the increased consumption of processed food or the large quantities of saturated fat products. Saturated fat helps increase the cholesterol production in the body which is an essential part of metabolism and in the production of steroid hormones. So saturated fat should feature in our diet, just maybe donâ€™t latter every meal in butter.
.
. 
Unsaturated fats are made up of mono and polyunsaturated fats.  These contain our omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids. Omega 3 fatty acids open our airways and blood vessels. They reduce our blood lipids and cholesterol and lower inflammation and pain. Omega 6 fatty acids do the opposite. Both are needed in the body, without both we wouldnâ€™t heal or recover from exercise. The problem with Western diets is that we donâ€™t have the proper ratios. We are at about 10:1 where we should be at 2:1 (omega 6/omega 3).
.
. 
Low fat diets were a fad a few years ago. While people reduced calories, they increased their intake of processed foods. Diets lacked fats and fat soluble vitamins so instead of being healthier people were losing weight but were not healthier.
.
.

caption:
Tomorrow is a luxury we won't always have so please stop wishing your life away ğŸ™
.
.
Life is here and now ğŸ™ Not in the past. Not in the future. Believe me, I'm making all the plans for when Lockdown is over and I'm so excited to do it ğŸ‘Š But I have not wished my life away.
.
.
I've been grateful that it's given me more time with Owen. It's given me time to save some extra money. I will have completed a new course. And I plan on coming out of Lockdown fitter and stronger than I've ever been ğŸ‘Š
.
.
It's not a productivity challenge. I know people are struggling - myself included. I went through my hardest week in Austrailia last week. So I am empathetic ğŸ™ But I truely try to live in the here and now. And allow myself have bad days and bad weeks ğŸ™
.
.
But do yourself a favour and stop telling yourself:
â“ You'll be happier when....
â“ You'll start exercising when...
â“ You'll stop drinking when...
â“ You'll eat healthier when...
.
.
I'm here to say that day may NEVER come. I don't want to be morbid or unsupportive but it's the truth.
.
.
So do yourself a favour. And take this as a sign to start living. Not just for When lockdown is over. Not just for the weekends. For the here and now ğŸ‘ŠğŸ™Œ
.
.

caption:
