ğ‡ğğ«ğ'ğ¬ ğ°ğ¡ğ² ğŸ¤”
.
.
1. Consistency - I make sure every single one of my clients can be consistent with their goals. How? Because each of their programmes and habits are tailored to them.
Eileen mother of 3 barely has enough time to do 2 sessions a week when the kids are off school so why would I give her 5 sessions a week like Mary (a student)? Consistency is key. Each individual is different. Consistency looks different to everyone, but it is the key to every successful fitness journey.
.
.
2. Why? - I told you my why last week. My why is to be a role model. Everyone else has their own why - but unless you know yours and REALLY REALLY care about it, you're probably going no where.
.
.
3. Unrealistic Goals - 
Abs is the perfect example. 
Apart from the tiny minority of genetically gifted people - Abs are not that easy to achieve. Firstly, people don't want to sacrifice what it takes to achieve them. Secondly, being at that low body fat (especially for a woman) is very difficult and unsustainable. So set yourself more realistic, attainable goals.
.
.
4. Impatient - Look I'm impatient too. I get it. But honestly, if you're putting a time frame on your health and fitness journey - you're probably already off to a bad start. You should be looking at the long term - in a few months, a few years etc. It can be good to do a little kick-starter but your fitness journey should never have an end date ğŸ‘Š
.
.
5. You don't have a road map to your goals - This one is easily the most fixable one. Why do you keep trying to do it alone? There are people out there who can help. 

âœ…People like me who have cared about health and fitness their whole lives. 
âœ…People like me who have helped 100s of women already.
âœ… People like me who have the qualifications to back it up.
.
.
If you:
- want to stop using excuses and start seeing results 
- are sick of stopping and starting 
- are serious about changing
.
.

If you haven't already noticed I feel very passionate about helping people. 
.

I too, disliked my body image, under fuelled and exercised to burn calories. I too did endless amounts of cardio and crunches in a bid to find abs. And guess what, nothing changed. How I felt about myself didn't change one single bit. Even when I was a size 6 and probably <18% BF with visible abs, I still wasn't happy. 
.
.
And you won't be either, unless you deal with what's going on in your head and understand the 
Importance of your why. 
.
.
My ğ™¬ğ™ğ™® is to be a role model ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ I want younger girls to look up to me. I want peers to understand the message I am preaching. I want older women to see that fad diets and restriction is NOT the answer. I want Dad's to say 'You should listen to that Mc Loone one' (if you know you know ğŸ˜…).
.
.
My ğ™¬ğ™ğ™® is to help as many women as I can become the best versions of themselves. 
ğŸ’¥I want to educate women that you can still enjoy the food you like and be happy. 
ğŸ’¥I want women to see how empowering it is to become physically stronger. 
ğŸ’¥I want to help women see how incredible they are and stop focusing so much on how they look on the outside and see what they have to offer from the inside. 
ğŸ’¥I want to see confidence radiating from the women I work with. 
.
.
I truely believe I was put on this planet for 3 reasons:
1. To help as many people as physically possible.
2. To become the fittest and healthiest version of myself
3. To have loads of animals 
.
.
If this sounds like you. Reach out and Dm me 'Help'. ğŸ™

ğŸ’¥ If you are a student, unsure of your path. Please talk to a career guidance teacher.
ğŸ’¥ If you are unsure of your career and thinking about changing everything for a different route. Maybe you could see a life coach.
ğŸ’¥ If you are sick. See a doctor.

See the trend???

Once upon a time I thought I was totally independent. I didn't want to ask for help from anyone!!! I got this tattoo just before moving to Austrailia. I certainly would never say I had a bad life - but I wasn't FULLY happy. I had to make changes. 
ğŸ’¥The first and best thing I did was quit football. This is not a stab at anyone playing or all the amazing people I know through GAA. But it was no longer bringing me joy. If anything, it was an added stress to my life. 
ğŸ’¥The second thing I had to do which was a hell of a lot harder was to try and heal a very strained relationship. 
ğŸ’¥And the third choice I made was Austrailia. 
.
.
Let me tell you we all have these tough decisions to make. Yours won't be the same as mine, but honestly if something is not adding to your life and is bringing you so much misery - YOU HAVE THE POWER TO DO SOMETHING ABOUT IT!!!!
.
.
âœ´Maybe it's the job you dread going into every day

.

.

.
I still get a little envious (of a good tan ğŸ˜ğŸ˜ğŸ˜) but I'm pretty darn happy with my body. I no longer compare it to smaller waist sizes. I'm not upset any more that I have a little pouch (that's my happiness pouch).

.

caption:
What you think you want and what you need are not always the same thing ğŸ™€
.
.
I work really hard to give women what they actually need. In reality, this looks like:
ğŸ‘† Nutrition Education - stop with food guilt, stop with binge and restrict cycle, eating foods they actually enjoy

ğŸ‘† Resistance training - women think they need to burn more calories and HIIT style workouts are the only way to do this âœ– Resistance based training changes our body shape and increases our BMR.

ğŸ‘† Accountability - we all need accountability. Myself included. It helps us stay on track but also it gives us a support line. When my clients are struggling is when I tell them to reach out more.

ğŸ‘† Community - I've always worked better as a team. I can train alone easily but know I've people to report back to and a team I don't want to let down, this is very important to me. I'm not just creating an online programme here but a community of women supporting one another â¤ğŸ™Œ
.
.
If any of the above sounds like something you'd like and  you're interested in Online Coaching. Dm me 'Coach'. I've a few spaces opening up in August ğŸ¤—

ğŒğğ§ğ­ğšğ¥ ğ‡ğğšğ¥ğ­ğ¡ ğ¢ğ¬ ğ§ğ¨ğ­ ğ£ğ®ğ¬ğ­ ğšğ§ğ±ğ¢ğğ­ğ² ğšğ§ğ ğğğ©ğ«ğğ¬ğ¬ğ¢ğ¨ğ§ âœ–âœ–âœ–
.
.
Sometimes it doesn't need a name. And what about bipolar and schizophrenia? Mental Health encompasses a huge variety of areas and sometimes it's just not as simple as a diagnosis ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ I am not a mental healthcare provider so I'm not going to go down that route, I just know what I've been through and I'm happy to share ğŸ˜˜
.
.
I wouldn't ever say I was depressed or even suffered with anxiety (this phrase is too commonly misused btw). But that doesn't mean I never suffered. 
.
.
August 2018
This photo was taken during a time in my life when my mental was at it's WORST - you wouldn't think it would you ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ I was having an absolute ball with my friends - drinking way too much to forget the fact that my life was in turmoil. 
.
.
The day after this photo was taken, I woke up to a call from a stranger to say my mother had been taken to hospital (physical injuries as a result of her mental health problems). 
At the time, I was running a gym, commuting, looking after my mother, and playing inter county football. 
.
.
This is not a pity party. It's not to say I've had life tougher than others. 
Thankfully, I'm well on the other side of that period of my life ğŸ™ 
.
.
What I just want to do is raise awareness that it's not always black and white. And sometimes, you have NO CLUE what someone is going through ğŸ™
.
.
So firstly, BE KIND ALWAYS â¤ You literally have NO IDEA how much someone may need it.
Secondly, check in on your strong friends too.
.
.
People in Syndey, these are tough times. But look at our Irish counterparts, look at how they managed â¤ We got this. And never ever be afraid to reach out, even if it's just for a moan down the phone ğŸ™
I'm definitely always here â¤ğŸ™

caption:
Stop comparing foods as like with like ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
âœ…â‚¬30 = $46.17 AUD. But they are 2 totally different currencies.
âœ…1000 Tonnes Feathers = 1000 Tonnes Coal. But they are 2 totally different components. 
.
.
The same goes for food. 
.
.
100 Calories Apple = 100 Calorie Chocolate Bar (as a measure of calories). But you cannot compare them in composition. The lack of micronutrients, the high sugar and fat content in the chocolate bar cannot be easily compared to the vitamins, mineral, water and phytonutrients in the apple ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Since when was Maths ever that simple ğŸ˜… I am not saying Calories in versus calories out is non sense, because it isn't. It makes sense and is very important. All I'm saying is, it's not the ONLY thing that is important. Food quality matters for long term health benefits and body composition ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Questions? ğŸ¤”

You are a sum of the things you do consistently ğŸ‘Š

âœ– Not training regularly? Don't get annoyed with the results you didn't get by the work you didn't put in ğŸš«

âœ– Snoozing your alarm and missing your morning walk - Don't get frustrated when you don't hit your step count ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸

âœ– Weekends throwing you off? ğŸ· You actually can still enjoy yourself but your binge restrict lifestyle is your main problem ğŸ‘Š
.
.
I keep non negotiables that I can stick to EVERY single day. This means Christmas, Holidays, Hangovers etc ğŸ˜… They are nothing crazy. But it works ğŸ‘Š Consistency trumps any and all diets. 
Consistency in training is the only way to progress ğŸ’ª

NOTHING trumps consistency, with regards what you can control - Name one thing - I dare you

I am a strong woman ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Yes in the physical sense. I have worked for years to get stronger and build a body I feel confident in. I have consistently trained for the last 10 years. First at intercounty football which then led to my love of strength and resistance trainingğŸ˜ My body is a reflection of that.
.
.
But I am so much stronger than my physique. My mental strength is something you cannot see, but it's much stronger than any weight I could lift. Or any competition I'll do. 
I have gone through more than most will go through in a lifetime. I have had my own share of mental health issues. But I have come out the other side. A true reflection of my mental strength.
.
.
I have worked damn hard to be in the position I am in right now. I said to a client last year how lucky I am to have got a job during COVID and how amazing my job, clients and boss are. And she said 'Amanda, you are not lucky. You've worked for this.' She was right. This year as proved that ğŸ‘ŠğŸ’ª
.
.
It's an amazing feeling to feel like a strong woman. A strong woman can be intimidating. A strong woman can come off as bossy. A strong woman can get a hostile response especially from the opposite sex. And this is where I acknowledge the strong men in my life. Most notably my Dad was the strongest man I've ever known. Owen has the patience of a saint. And final shout out to the men I've worked with who were not immasculated taking orders from a woman and the bosses I've had who not only considered my opinion but actually valued it. ğŸ™
.
.
I am a strong woman. Are you?

Grace's Experience: 

Thank you so much Amanda for everything I have learned in the past 12 weeks. The knowledge and confidence I now have will last a lifetime.Â 

I was diagnosed with PCOS nearly 4 years ago and the Doctor told me that I will just always struggle with my weight. He gave me no information about it.Â 

Then into a third lockdown, I was feeling unmotivated, lost, and had low self esstem. I turned to Amanda who offered a 12-week program that focused on building habits rather than an all-or-nothing approach. Amanda is so positive, enthusiastic but alsoÂ really understanding that we are all juggling different things while trying to hit our fitness goals. Since joining Amanda I have lost 5 kg which I am so happy with. But I have also learned a lot about having a more positive outlook on life and on myself. Amanda'sÂ habit-building approach really does work without you restricting yourself. I have learned loads about my PCOS which makes me feel more in control. Getting my steps in, drinking 2 liters of water, exercise, 8 hours of sleep, and hitting nutrition goals are partÂ of my day to day now. Amanda has taught me that every day does not have to be perfect, what is important is to try your best and consistency will prevail.

I've always been very open minded.
.
.
I pride myself on it actually. I've alway been a pro choice kinda girl in all aspects of life (not just health and fitness related). You'll never hear me boast about one type of diet or slate any either. You won't hear me downgrade any form of exercise, although I do openly talk about the huge benefits of resistance training ğŸ’ª I'll never tell any of my client's 'You have to do this type of exercise' or 'you cannot eat this for weight loss'. So you see I'm very open minded. If someone who loves yoga comes to me, I'm not going to force them to lift weights. And if someone who is vegan comes to me, I would not force them to eat animal products. My problem with any of these things lies in the misinformation. .
.
.
Did you know that vegan fast food production has sky rocketed in recent years? ğŸ¤” Similarly, a few years ago, gluten free products were a huge trend? And before that, sugar free was the hype? This I have a problem with.
.
.
Veganism is a lifestyle choice. I have huge respect for anyone's lifestyle choices, whether they conform to my own is irrelevant. What actually annoys me is actual vegans are getting a terrible name due to all these people jumping on the bandwagon, thinking veganism is the healthiest lifestyle going. People are going into this lifestyle, uneducated and naive. ğŸ˜’ It was the same a few years ago when gluten free was the buzzword. Did you know you can have a totally adequate, balanced, healthy diet without adding one gluten free product? And thats for ACTUAL coeliacs out there, because they are the ONLY people that need to be eating gluten free toast ğŸ˜‚
.
.
What my very long winded post is trying to say is stop jumping on bandwagons. If you are and always have been vegan, that's fine. Continue with your choices. If you are coeliac, continue with your gluten free bread ğŸ™ˆ 
.
For the rest of you, stop following trends by the latest celebrity diet.
â Stop conforming to social norms âœŠ 
âStop basing your beliefs on a bloody stupid documentary ğŸ˜’ 
âœ…Get some advice from a professional. ğŸ™
âœ… Follow said advice ğŸŒˆ 
âœ… And unfollow anyone giving terrible, uneducated advice 
.
.

caption: Here's what Sinead had to say ğŸ‘‰

Let's clear something up... 
.
.
There is no perfect form of coaching â
Or perfect form of exercise â
.
.
Each style has it's pros and cons ğŸ˜ˆ
.
.
But it is the form that you can consistently work with and that give you long term sustainable results - that works for you. That does not mean it works for everyone ğŸ¤”
.
.
Let me give you some scenarios.
.
.
One of my online clients first approached me for in person PT. She didn't know I lived in Austrailia ğŸ™ˆğŸ¤£ She wasn't interested in online coaching due to wasting money on previous online programmes. This lady works 2 jobs and barely has time for herself let alone fitting into a PT schedule. Online coaching was a great option for her. She lost 18lbs and felt amazing in her wedding dress ğŸ¥³
.
.
I have a friend who tried online coaching...twice. First time went well, second time not as well. Nothing wrong with the programme, she just responds better to in person accountability. She is now doing in person PT and loving it ğŸ¥³
.
.
There's nothing special about Crossfit. It's more the community and the vibe than the exercise prescription people enjoy. 
.
.
Running may be an excellent form of exercise for an introvert but an extrovert might find it very isolating...
.
.
My point?
1. Just because Sharon got results from a PT does not mean that PT has extraordinary powers. This form of coaching got Sharon results because it was something she CONSISTENTLY did and could stick to.
2. There is no right or wrong coaching style - just what works for you. 
3. Please find something you enjoy and can see yourself doing for the next 50 years ğŸ™ As opposed to hating exercise, see it as a blessing ğŸ‘

caption:
I've been there too ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸

I think the impression I portray on social media is of a strong, independent female who has her shit together. Most of the time, this is me. But I haven't always been this way. 

I had issues...
Serious ones...
Ones I struggled with for years...
Ones I didn't even realise I had until I look back... 

ğŸ’¥I was an attention seeker.
I wore skimpy clothes. I was the loudest, most outspoken person in every group. Most people would mistake me for confident.
But I was craving people's attention. I wanted people to like me, wanted people to care because I didn't always get that recognition growing up. 

ğŸ’¥I was a perfectionist.
The control of being the best in every situation. I'm not going to lie this is still one I struggle with to a degree but compared to where I was, they are miles apart ğŸ™ 

ğŸ’¥I drank to forget.
A lot of my late teens, early 20s I would pass out before I could even make it to a club. We all laughed at the time, I was known for 'Never making it out' but honestly this was yet another cry for help. 

Look I'm not going to say I had the worst upbringing in the world because that is just not true. But that doesn't mean that parts of your childhood/life don't form who you become years later. I never had problems with weight or issues with weight loss but that doesn't mean I haven't faced my own demons. 

I deal with women on a daily basis who have terrible relationships with food because of 
1. Their home life (control often leading to eating disorders or disordered eating)
2. Family figures - Parents who excessively dieted or commented on appearance regularly
3. Fad diets - I actually had a woman just this morning who I'm trying to convince there is no such thing as a 'bad' food but her years of WW has told her to stay away from fats ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ 

I'm not a psychologist. I don't try to be. I am aÂ  nutritionist so I don't veer outside the scope of my practice but I do want to help. I want to help women heal their relationship with food. I want to help them realise their worth is not based on a number or a figure. I want them to see food as fuel and not be afraid of it. 

If any of the above sounds like you DM me â¤

My clients know why I recommend up to 2g Protein/KG BW/day ğŸ™Œ Why? Because I educate them why ğŸ‘Š

.
2. Satiety - Protein is super filling. It's difficult to eat large quantities without feeling full. This is a good complaint ğŸ˜œ
.
3. Recovery - Protein is required for so many processes in our body. Regardless of your goals - weight loss, weight gain, performance - everyone will benefit from a high protein diet.

.

caption:
ğŸ¯ Nutrition - Hierarchy of Importance ğŸ¯
.
.
Here's is my nutrition triangle. This is not a standard pyramid, it's mostly just my opinion ğŸ˜
.
.
Diet is defined as the kinds of food a person habitually eats. No diet will ever be successful if someone cannot successfully stick to it and be consistent with it. And for this reason, it is my bread and butter. It is the most important element when it comes to nutrition.
.
.
I am a nutritionist so Food Quality is my next most important element. I know in terms of energy balance it is as simple as calories in versus calories out but I just cannot educate people and say that
Food quality doesn't matter. If I didn't care about my clients and I just cared about transformation photos I could give someone a calorie calculator and say 'Here once it's within your calories it doesn't matter what the meals include'. Maybe not for body composition (questionable) but certainly for long term health ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Then, I put calories. Calories do matter but to me food quality matters more. As I've said, this is opinion. At the end of the day, it is an energy balance equation so I can't disregard them but just be aware of how inaccurate logging and tracking can be. Just be informed ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Technically that should be macronutrients but I'm putting protein as the king ğŸ¤´ Although I do feel very strongly about good balance so please don't disregard carbs and fats ğŸ˜¬
.
.
Lastly, comes supplements. Supplements should always be an addition.
.
.
Did I miss anything ğŸ¤”
.
.
Interested in opinions too ğŸ˜‡

.

The fitness industry is becoming saturated. There is so much conflicting information it's overwhelming to even know where to start. I want to stand out and not fade into the same mould.
.
.
I'm pretty safe though because:

â I won't be that 'hot' fitness model - although leave some ğŸ”¥ if you love the posts of my sweaty red head
â I won't be posing in lingerie to get thousands followers - although I do look good in Lingerie ğŸ˜œ

.

I actually struggle to find time to put up content these days because I am so busy with my clients. All my time, effort and education goes into helping everyone of them. They have invested their time and money in me and I'm so proud of the work we do together â¤
.
.
Anyway, I'm going to be different to a lot of other fitness accounts - I'm not going to say its just as simple as 'Eat Less, Move MoreâœŒ'. 
Sorry unfortunately I just don't think it is.
.
.
My hierarchy begins with stress reduction - why?
.
.
Well because stress in all shapes and sizes leads to incredible problems in the body. 
Example: Stress of too little calories - Can lead to hormonal disruptions which can lead to amenorrhoea which can lead to infertility. Too little calories and poor food quality can lead to micronutrient deficiencies and injury. 
Stress can be as simple as drinking too much caffeine or as severe as overwhelm. Add up all the daily stresses in your life and see how many there areğŸ˜±
.
.
Sleep should be AS IMPORTANT as exercise and nutrition combined - end of storyğŸ˜´
.
.
Nutrition and food quality come next.ğŸ¥¦
.
.
Exercise in general should technically come next but this is my pyramid so I'm going to do what I believe is most important - irrespective of goals! ğŸ‹â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Lastly, individual variance. Have a condition or a goal? Follow all the below first and foremost and the individuality should come last 
.
.

caption:
Health and Fitness goals in a nutshell ğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘Š
.
.
âœ… Training average twice a week for 52 weeks is better than 7 days a week for 4 weeks (every time you 'restart' your fitness journey)
âœ… Drinking 1.5L water daily is better than yoyo extremes of 3L and 500ml
âœ… Eating Whole Nutritious food 50% of the time 52 weeks a year is better than your 'starting Monday' almost every week
.
.
Remember, you and your body is a representation of what you do most of the time, not some of the time. 
ğŸ¯If you are going over your calorie deficit 4 days a week - you're not in a calorie deficit anymore.
ğŸ¯ If you're making more time for socialising than you are for the gym, expect your results to reflect that
ğŸ¯If you have more alcohol units a week than Green vegetables - don't be annoyed when you're not where you want to be ğŸ‘Š
.
.
Now how are you going to spend your time? ğŸ¤”

Cauliflower Rice vs Brown Rice
.
.
Which is best?
.
.
Answer is.
.
.
Neither are better, neither are worse.
.
.
I eat both. But why you are eating it depends on your goals ğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘Š
.
.
âœ… Weight loss a goal? Cauliflower rice is low in calories and high in volume so may be a great option
âœ…Alternatively, portion control of brown rice can also work.
âœ… Performance a goal? You will not get the same complex carbs from caulifower rice as you will from brown rice. 
âœ… Both have different nutritional compositions when it comes to vitamins and minerals.
âœ… Taste? Force feeding yourself cauliflower rice because your favourite fitness influencer recommended it? YOU ARE JUST BEING STUPID!!!! 
.
.
There is no right or wrong answer to comparing these. As always, it is dependent on your individual goals and anyone that gives you a clear defined answer is a fruad ğŸ˜…ğŸš«

caption:
Some of my favourite things about Austrailia:

âœ…Early Mornings - I've always been an early riser (like my Dad). But in Ireland it's not normal, I love that I'm the majority here when my alarm goes off for 5am 

âœ… Breakfast - Any day but especially the weekends. Saturday mornings are made for the CrossFit followed by Breakfast. Honestly, it's one of my absolute favourite things to do down by the beach ğŸ¥° 

âœ… Health and Fitness are a priority- do we have a recurring theme here ğŸ¤£ If I stay in my Grannys house in Donegal, there isn't a gym within a 30 mile radius ğŸ™ˆ Over here almost every second building is a gym 

âœ… Weekends are for Fun - whether you want to include alcohol or not, every weekend there is something new to do and in the 60 weeks I've been here I've done something new almost every weekend. Apart from CrossFit and Breakfast - that's a constant. 

âœ… Tan - I haven't wore fake tan since September ğŸ¥° Dont worry I wear SPF everyday 

âœ… Friends are like Family - I saved the best for last. Friendships are intensified by the fact that we're so far away from home together. I love this though, I've made friends for life in such a short period of time â¤ğŸ™

#happinessis

â€¼ï¸I'm looking for 5 ladies who want to become strong and confident while eating the foods they enjoy. I'm launching my 90 Day Strong and Sassy Programme again.â€¼ï¸
.
.
Feel like you've tried everything and still see no results? Here's 3 reasons my coaching programme could work for you: 

1. I educate women on nutrition. I don't give meal plans but actually teach you the importance of nutrient dense food. I help you calculate calories and understand the foods you need to fuel your body. I'm also a big advocate of including foods you actually enjoy! 

2. Want to be able to lift your suitcase with ease when lockdown finishes? Want to perform a push up? Want to become a strong, independent female?
I focus on resistance training and encourage women to become the strongest they can be. 

3. I help women become the best versions of themselves. Confidence comes from the inside out and I help women find that sassy female that's hiding inside. 

These are just a few of the amazing elements to my Strong and Sassy programme, not to mention the incredible community that comes with it. 

If you're ready to become the strongest, most confident version of yourself - Comment below ğŸ”¥

caption: I know what I'm choosing ğŸ¯

I remember 7 years ago when I started strength training. 

I remember saying I wish I'd started sooner... 

7 years on and other people now say that same thing to me. 

It's never too late to start. I know people who start it in their teens and I also know people who start it in their 40s. 

Never use it's too late as an excuse. The time passes anyway.

It is never too late to make an improvement to your health. 

Stop waiting. There will never be a good time. Just do it! 

Not sure what to do? Why not use the next 90 days to make that long awaited start? ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸

I hope each and everyone of you leave some time for you every day. I don't mean hours, it can be minutes. But every day you need to find some 'you time'. 
.
.
Everyone has something different. Meditate, read a book, listen to a podcast, drink a cup of tea - just find what works for you. And do it daily. 
.
.
Now, find something you need to do for yourself every so often. For me up until recently It was go on 2 big holidays a year and a couple of weekend breaks. I understand that is not something everyone can do at the moment but why not make a plan for when it is? Or save or invest in something for you - it may be a new car, a new couch, some home gym equipment? 
.
.
In recent years I've realised the importance of self care. I invest in holidays and my health. 
.
.
ğŸ¯It never ceases to amaze me how people can spend $100's on handbags but a physio appointment is too expensive? ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
ğŸ¯ I still can't comprehend how a facial or a massage is seen as a luxury but 3 uber eats a week is normal?
ğŸ¯ Coaching is a waste of money but alcohol and drugs are 'worth it' 

I know it all comes down to priorities, I understand that. Not everyone sees the benefit of investing in your physical and mental health right now. I get that. But don't think these things are 'expensive' or a 'luxury' if you are literally throwing away your money ğŸ™ˆâ
.

caption:
Stop comparing foods as like with like ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
âœ…â‚¬30 = $46.17 AUD. But they are 2 totally different currencies.
âœ…1000 Tonnes Feathers = 1000 Tonnes Coal. But they are 2 totally different components. 
.
.
The same goes for food. 
.
.
100 Calories Apple = 100 Calorie Chocolate Bar (as a measure of calories). But you cannot compare them in composition. The lack of micronutrients, the high sugar and fat content in the chocolate bar cannot be easily compared to the vitamins, mineral, water and phytonutrients in the apple ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Since when was Maths ever that simple ğŸ˜… I am not saying Calories in versus calories out is non sense, because it isn't. It makes sense and is very important. All I'm saying is, it's not the ONLY thing that is important. Food quality matters for long term health benefits and body composition ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Questions? ğŸ¤”

caption:
ğ•€ ğ•™ğ•’ğ•• ğ•’ ğ•¤ğ•”ğ•’ğ•£ğ•– ğ••ğ•¦ğ•£ğ•šğ•Ÿğ•˜ ğ•¥ğ•™ğ•– ğ•¨ğ•–ğ•–ğ•œ 
.
.
My period was 14 days late. 
.
.
It wasn't a fear of pregnancy. Quite the opposite actually. Don't forget our menstrual cycle is a sign of health ğŸ™ 
.
.
10 years ago if you had said to me, give me a once off tablet to never have my period again, I would have taken it. Why? Because I considered it 'disgusting' or 'an inconvenience'. I was so uneducated. But being totally honest I just didn't care about my health enough either ğŸ˜¬
.
.
I have been so in tune with my body the last 5 months that it honestly came as a huge shock to me to have such an irregular cycle ğŸ˜¢ I harp on to all my clients about it's importance and here I was with a 42 day cycle. 
.
.
The thing about the menstrual cycle is, it's sensitive. It can't deal with too much stress. But remember stress looks different on everyone ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ For me last month I travelled time zones (this ALWAYS puts my cycle off) and I had my 30th Birthday weekend (the most alcohol I've drank in months - another stress). 
.
.
One long cycle like that due to stress is ok. But if it's a continuing problem, it is really worth seeking medical advice or help from a professional.
.
.
You may not be thinking about it now. But amenorrhoea or irregular menstrual cycles can have a profound effect on your future health.
.
.
My advice:
âœ…Start tracking 
âœ… Understand the different phases in your cycle
âœ… Monitor symptoms, emotions, feelings, productivity, energy.
.
.
Work with your body, not against ğŸ™â¤

caption:
Fitness to me shows consistency, hard work and determination âœŒ
.
.
I will never tire of people calling me fit. I loved when people didn't want to mark me. I am so proud anytime someone calls me a 'tank' or a 'machine' ğŸ˜… 

.
Why?
Because of where I started and where I came from â¤
.
.
I was not always fit. I was definitely not skilful. But my God find someone who was a harder worker than me.
.
.
Hard Work 
âœ…I went from the girl who had to give her football boots to another player to making the county team.
âœ…I went from the scrawny midfielder to the strong full back. 
âœ…I made the bloody Connacht panel. And rest assured I was not the most talented defender in the province.
âœ… Weddings, 21st Birthdays, social occassions, holidays, j1s - all missed
.
.
Consistency
âœ… I was back on the pitch with Roscommon 8 months after my ACL reconstruction
âœ… I was in the gym 2 days after surgery on my wrist
âœ… 8 weeks after dislocating my knee I took part in a Crossfit Competition and achieved my top 10 goal.
.
.
Determination
âœ… After being told I'd never be the same footballer after my ACL injury - I came back stronger and fitter than ever. Ill never forget winning my first sprint the day I went back to full training or scoring the winning point the day of my return to play
âœ… I won a CrossFit competition on a Saturday, played in a county semi final on a Wednesday - did great in both
âœ… At 28 with Achilles Tendonopathy, I played 2 games - 1 county, 1 club - I actually HIGHLY do not recommend this ğŸ˜¬ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
This is not intended to be a boast post ğŸ˜… Although I'm pretty bloody proud of all of the above - apart from the 2 games in 1 day, that was pure stupidity â 
.
.
This is almost 20 years of time and effort. 20 years of commitment. 20 years of sacrifice. (I've sacrificed a lot less in recent times, priorities shifted).
So before you think about quitting because you haven't seen results in 6 weeks. Think about the commitment you're giving. Think about the sacrifice you're making. 
.
.
Think about where you can be in 20 years time ğŸ‘Š

#heresto20more

Happy International Women's Day â¤
.
.
I am so blessed to have so many incredible women in my life - my friends, my family & my clients ğŸ™
.
.
We deserve a day to be celebrated and each and every one of us should take this day to be thankful and grateful for all our achievements ğŸŒŸ

ğ”¹ğ•¦ğ•¥ ğ•¨ğ•™ğ•’ğ•¥ ğ•’ğ•“ğ• ğ•¦ğ•¥ ğ•¤ğ•–ğ•ğ•— ğ•ğ• ğ•§ğ•–?
.
.
Yesterday in Austrailia we celebrated Mardi Gras. I am, have been and always will be a 'love is love' advocate â¤ğŸ™
.
.
I do however, see a little problem within our society ğŸ˜¢ We focus so much on finding love with another person that we forget to love ourselves ğŸ˜”
.
.
A few years ago I would have found this talk 'absolutely ridiculous' ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ The same person would self sabotage with alcohol ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ It's a very individual belief and idea. It doesn't look the same on everyone so here's my two cents.
.
.
What self love means to me:
â Not seeking other people's approval - doing things for myself, not others
â Not being jealous - it's a terrible trait to compare yourself, your possessions or your life to others. Find happiness within what you have or within what you do - if you're not happy, change it. This was a MAJOR turning point for me
âœ” Be content with the person you are - your traits, your characteristics - what makes you you â¤ And again, if there is something you are not happy with - remember you have the power to change it.
âœ” Be happy in your own company - another game changer. I am beyond blessed with Owen, the very large group of friends I have, the work I do and the training I do. I am a social butterfly and I love that. But I am very comfortable being in my own company and alone also.
.
.
I was so lucky to have found Owen at a period in my life where I really didn't love myself and I needed his attention so much. That puts pressure on a relationship. Insecurity is difficult. But in the time we've been together he's seen a change to me, a welcome change. (He actually said to me just last night how proud he is of me ğŸ¥°ğŸ˜­)
.
.
I am so happy within myself. I'm confident in my work. I love my body - not for how it looks but for what it can do. I love my soul - I am a good person and the friends I have are proof of that. 
.
.
It's MORE than ok to give yourself a pat on the back. Its more than ok to say how proud you are of yourself.
.

Stress is not just 'feeling stressed'. I always ask my clients about stress levels. Most people respond with either 'yes I'm stressed or no I'm not stressed'. Stress is a lot more complex than 'feeling stressed'.
.
.
Stress can present itself from so many things,some which I'm sure you're aware of, some which you won't realise ğŸ™ˆ (the above is just a handful)
.

When you're stressed body switches on fight or flight mode - releases Adrenaline, Nora adrenaline, Cortisol.
.
ğŸ¯Adrenaline increases heart rate, breath faster and tenses muscles.
ğŸ¯Noradrenaline diverts blood from (unessential areas during fight or flight) reproductive system, digestive and skin.
ğŸ¯Cortisol raises blood pressure and blood sugar levels.
.
We need stress hormones in our body, but the problem arises when they are imbalanced.
.

caption:
ğŸ¯ Values and Goals ğŸ¯
.
.
People set their goals too high - it's a natural thing.
.
.
From an aesthetic perspective, we have all been raised with unrealistic expectations of what the 'perfect body' is. So of course people set their limits towards that. In most cases:
1. The person we want to look like doesn't actually look like their photoshopped photo
2. The measures they went to, to look like that are unhealthy and unattainable
.
.
From a fitness perspective, we go in all guns blazing expecting to train every day. Expecting an RPE of 8-10 on every session. Expecting to hit pbs everyday. Expecting training sessions to be fun and exciting and different and enjoyable.
1. If you are a person who doesn't exercise, commit to NO MORE than 3 sessions a week - 40 mins. Anything extra should be a bonus.
2. If body composition change is a goal, lift bloody weights - I'm sick of explaining all the reasons why.
3. Boring can be progressed. Progression = improvement. Stop trying to make it fancy.
.
.
From a nutrition perspective, we want to change our whole diet in a week which leads to.... Falling off the wagon altogether, saying fuck it  and starting that cycle 7 million times. What you should do:
1. Start small. Build habits. Imagine 1 habit a week over 12 weeks. No crazy changes just small incremental changes.
2. Instead of eliminating foods - add foods. Add colour, add protein, add water. 
3. 80/20 rule is and will always be my go to. 80% of the food your body needs, 20% of the food your body wants.
.
.
Support - Stop trying to do this all unassisted. If you're like me and love the support from your girls â¤ Find a gym buddy. If you need help with your goals invest in a coach ğŸ™

I used to hate my small boobies....
I used to hate my teeth...
I used to hate my curly hair...
I always wanted to be smaller...
I wanted to be prettier...
I wanted to be smarter...
I wanted to be fitter...
I wanted to be lighter..
I wanted abs... 

I always wanted something more. I was never happy. But the problem wasn't in my appearance. The problem lay deep inside. I wasn't happy within myself. I didn't love myself or my body ğŸ˜¢ And this is something I see in 90% of women, a feeling of self loathing ğŸ˜­ 

I made changes. I changed how I viewed myself and my body. It took time. A long time. But finally I am at a place in my life that my exterior does not define me. I am living in a country where aesthetics is priority and most people have injected at least 1 part of their body ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜… And here I am - delighted with my frizzy hair, my crooked teeth and my muscular legs ğŸ‘Š 

This is something I work on my clients with constantly. Stop trying to look for happiness in a clothes size, the bottom of a make up bottle, or the newest beauty trend. I can promise you no amount of beauty products fitness regimes or shopping can make you feel like self confidence feels ğŸ™ 

P.s Who knew having no boobies at 30 would be the absolute dream ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸

caption:
Why Protein? 
.
.
Quite often I hear people recommending high protein diets without having a clue why they are recommending it ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
My clients know why I recommend up to 2g Protein/KG BW/day ğŸ™Œ Why? Because I educate them why ğŸ‘Š
.
.
1. TEF - Our total daily energy expenditure (TDEE) is made up for 4 components - BMR, NEAT, Purposeful Activity and TEF. It accounts for up to 10% of our TDEE. Protein rich foods have a higher thermic effect from food than any other macro nutrient.
.
2. Satiety - Protein is super filling. It's difficult to eat large quantities without feeling full. This is a good complaint ğŸ˜œ
.
3. Recovery - Protein is required for so many processes in our body. Regardless of your goals - weight loss, weight gain, performance - everyone will benefit from a high protein diet.
.
.
So now you understand ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†

caption:
Collette's Experience:

I have spent the last few days thinking about how I can put into words what the past 12 weeks have down for me. I started off with a particular goal in mind, it definitely hasn't ended up with that same goal!!! I wanted weight loss along with other things and I have lost very little but amazingly the weight loss is irrelevant to me. I haven't even looked at the scales in past 2 weeks. It's the journey that has happened internally that is my biggest achievement and I can honestly say i have never felt better, as Amanda has said so many times it doesn't matter what you look like on the outside if you're not happy on the inside you'll never be happy with how you look. I have achieved so many small personal goals, swimming in the sea on probably the coldest day of the year without worrying about how I looked to others, walking 10 Kms without even thinking about it and loving every single step. I have a very sedentary job and before I started there was days I didn't even get 2000 steps in, most definitely a thing of the past. But THE most important part of my 12 week journey is the fact that I am off all my medication for my mental health, no more anti depressants or anxiety tablets. ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª This journey has taught me to make time for me, just me and as a result I'm a better mother, partner and work colleague because I am happier in me . My journey has just started and I can't wait to see where the next 12 weeks will bring me. From the bottom of my heart Amanda, Brian and all the girls on the coaching calls thank you for the wonderful support along the way

caption:
Comparison is the thief of joy ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
I see this one a lot.
.
.
You are individual. You are not like anyone else, so why would you compare yourself to anyone else? ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Most of the time the circumstances aren't  even comparable. Let's give you some examples
â Comparing your image to celebrities 
â Comparing your performance to athletes
â Comparing your body to fitness influencers
.
.
If you are not where you want to be, being honest it is probably something you are or are not doing. BUT you are making life a hell of a lot more difficult for yourself by setting unrealistic goals and targets ğŸ¯
.
.
âœ” Start by setting some realistic goals
âœ” Progression over perfection 
âœ” Be consistent - stop giving it a short term tag. Look at the long term. Look at your future self.
âœ” Find something you enjoy - you are more likely to stick to it
.
.
Stop blaming other people and start looking at what you need to do to get where you want to be ğŸ‘Š And remember no number on the scales will make you happy unless you deal with the shit in your head ğŸ§

caption:
Training and Nutrition
Aesthetics vs Performance 
.
.
Some of the differences include:
1. Calorie requirements may be different. 
Performance goals usually require maintenance calories or even a surplus depending on how active you are. Aesthetic goals usually require being in a calorie deficit.
.
.
2. Training looks different. 
Training for aesthetics is usually some bodybuilding format with some form of light cardio. Training for performance is usually sport specific like pitch training, strength sessions or even high volume sessions like CrossFit.
.
.
3. Nutrient profiles may be different.
Firstly, weight loss requires you to be in a calorific deficit. Technically, you could eat 1 Mars bar a day and lose weight. I wouldn't recommend it, but you'd achieve your goals. Where as if you tried to perform at your best for a sport on 1 Mars bar a day, I cannot imagine you'd be performing very well.
Nutrition for aesthetics can be as simple as calories in versus calories out. Nutrition for performance is much more intricate - do you have enough fuel? Are you recovering ok? Do you have a full nutrient profile? Are you consuming good fats for hormonal balance and recovery? 
.
.
These are some of the main differences in nutrition and training when you have different goals. Can you think of more? ğŸ¤”

caption:
The meaning behind my Lotus Flower Tattoo ğŸŒº
.
.
I went through a really hard period of my life after my Dad died. As the oldest of his daughters I felt a responsibility to keep my shit together, look after my mother and sister and keep up appearances. It was a struggle. I tried to do this while managing a gym, commuting, playing with 2 football teams, studying, trying to maintain friendships and a relationship. I felt like I was just surviving as opposed to living ğŸ˜¢
.
.
And then I took control of my life. I started to look after myself first and everybody else's needs and wants came second. 
.
.
The meaning of the tattoo is that even the most beautiful things can come from the ugliest of places. ğŸ™
.
.
I'm not alone. I know we've all had struggles and strifes in our lives. I'm not saying mine has been harder than anyone else's. But I decided to take control of mine. I asked for help. I seeked the help I needed. And I made life changing decisions ğŸ’”â¤
.
.
My first Austrailia day in Sydney â¤ I honestly am so proud of my choices and decisions in the last few years ğŸ™ And I could not have spent it with anyone better @o_boyce â¤â¤â¤

caption:
I am fully aware things are crap in Ireland at the moment ğŸ˜¢ 90% of my clients are in Ireland, my friends are in Ireland, my family are in Ireland â¤ I am genuinely heartbroken for them ğŸ’”
.
.
When lockdown occurred in Austrailia, one of the biggest habits people developed was daily alcohol drinking. And openly admitted when working from home, the time would get earlier and earlier ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I am not anti alcohol. Actually I am the polar opposite. I encourage clients to have a glass of wine at weekends if that is what truely makes them happy. It's important to have balance in your life ğŸ™
.
.
I do believe though that alcohol is a little too readily available and can be 'too easy' to use as an escape. 
.
.
I implore people to find other things to pass their time. Exercise, walk, bake, knit, zoom call, cook, spring clean, learn a new skill ... the list goes on. But please don't let alcohol be the ONLY thing you look forward to daily ğŸ™ğŸ™ğŸ™

caption:
Mindset Matters ğŸ§ 
.
.
Exercise and Nutrition are key to achieving your goals âœ…
.
.
But so is mindset and it is an  element very often overlooked ğŸ¤”
.
.
For some people mindset is engrained. For me it was. I grew up as an athlete so exercise was a ready made component of my life. I didn't 'decide' when to exercise, it was decided for me. If I didn't eat right, I didn't perform well, I didn't make the team - the main goal. I trained with like minded people. So you could say things were easier for me. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Easier than say:
- An overweight lady struggling her whole life to lose weight. Uncomfortable with her body but too uncomfortable to start exercising. Feeling tired and lethargic and her only support network is people in a similar situation who shame her into saying this is ok and normal.

- A skinny man who wants to add some muscle. He drinks a lot and dabbles in drugs. His friends are all the same and think he would be wasting money going to a pt. 
.
.
Without the right mindset and the right support network exercise and nutrition may just be too hard to sustain ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
I work with athletes. But I also work with mothers who have never put themselves first. I work with women who have struggled their whole life with weight. I work with girls who are desperately anxious about how they look. Giving them a nutrition and exercise plan would be USELESS without educating them or helping them with the real WHY!!! 
.
.
I am so overwhelmingly happy to have so many amazing people on board at the moment. People who truely want to change their health for the better â¤
.
.
If you are one of these people DM me interested and we'll organise a call ğŸ˜ŠğŸ™Œ

My clients were back on coaching calls with me on Monday to talk about their plans going into January. They laid down markers over Christmas which makes January a hell of a lot easier and guess what every one of them enjoyed Christmas ğŸŒ²ğŸ·ğŸ…ğŸ¥³
Me too ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸

caption:
I absolutely hate comparisons...they are the absolute thief of joy ğŸ˜

But I always assess my comparison. It's always fitness related ğŸ™ˆ If I see someone fitter or stronger than me, I question how? It's an internal conversation....

caption:
Not drinking IS COOL!!!! ğŸ˜
.
.
So is drinking, if that's what you choose to do ğŸ» (as long as it's not negatively affecting your health)
.
.
I was so disappointed by how many people replied to my story saying they feel pressure to drink ğŸ˜¢
.
.
So what I have to say to this:
.
1. If you decide to not drink, don't mind other people's opinions. It has absolutely NO impact on them if you don't drink but it could negatively impact you (for whatever reason you have decided). 
.
2. Your goals will not always be the same as everyone else's. It's not that those people are trying to be rude, they just don't understand so don't take it too personally.
.
3. If you are one of the people saying 'Ah sure one won't hurt' - just think before you say it. I definitely was one of these in the past. But I've learned that sometimes we don't know or need to know why people chose not to drink.
.
.
Whatever you do just be kind. Be respectful of people's wishes. You have no right to question people on their reasoning - they deserve to have a choice. And same goes for sober Sallys - no judgement as long as people are consuming alcohol in a healthy manner ğŸ™
.
.
Opinions and experiences welcome

caption:
These people are why I love Crossfit â¤
.
.
#crossfitchristmasparty #swipeleftforlevelsofdrunk

Let's clear something up... 
.
.
There is no perfect form of coaching â
Or perfect form of exercise â
.
.
Each style has it's pros and cons ğŸ˜ˆ
.
.
But it is the form that you can consistently work with and that give you long term sustainable results - that works for you. That does not mean it works for everyone ğŸ¤”
.
.
Let me give you some scenarios.
.
.
One of my current online clients first approached me for in person PT. She didn't know I lived in Austrailia ğŸ™ˆğŸ¤£ She wasn't interested in online coaching due to wasting money on previous online programmes. This lady works 2 jobs and barely has time for herself let alone fitting into a PT schedule. Online coaching was a great option for her. She is currently at her goal weight 11 weeks into the programme ğŸ¥³
.
.
I have a friend who tried online coaching...twice. First time went well, second time not as well. Nothing wrong with the programme, she just responds better to in person accountability. She is now doing in person PT and loving it ğŸ¥³
.
.
There's nothing special about Crossfit. It's more the community and the vibe than the exercise prescription people enjoy. 
.
.
Running may be an excellent form of exercise for an introvert but an extrovert might find it very isolating...
.
.
My point?
1. Just because Sharon got results from a PT does not mean that PT has extraordinary powers. This form of coaching got Sharon results because it was something she CONSISTENTLY did and could stick to.
2. There is no right or wrong coaching style - just what works for you. 
3. Please find something you enjoy and can see yourself doing for the next 50 years ğŸ™ As opposed to hating exercise, see it as a blessing ğŸ‘
.
.
I'd love to hear some of your experiences
â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸â¬‡ï¸

caption:
Or 6 months? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Impatience is our biggest nemesis. Not the diet. Not the exercise. 
.
.
Try and stick to something for longer than a week. ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ 
.
.
There is no magic potion. There is no perfect training plan. 
.
.
You can spend all the money and time in the world but unless you are consistent, you're wasting your time ğŸ™Š

Is the environment you are in or the people in your life helping towards your goals? ğŸ¤”
.
.
This is often an element people overlook when it comes to forming habits ğŸ˜¬ğŸ™Š And it can have a huge impact on your results. 
.
.
Here's some examples:
.
ğŸ‘‰ You're trying to reduce your alcohol consumption for your health but all your friends drink every night. They consider it normal and you are ABNORMAL for trying to limit it. YOLO ğŸ˜œ
.
ğŸ‘‰ You're trying to cut down on takeaways in a bid to lose weight but your partner is constantly ordering them. YOLO ğŸ™Š
.
ğŸ‘‰ You're trying to exercise more and have started working with a coach. Your parents call you obsessed ğŸ˜‘
.
ğŸ‘‰ You're trying to reduce sugary snacks but the kids treats are calling to you from the kitchen cupboards ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
.
.
This is where you need to start thinking about YOUR goals. How important they are to YOU. You may even need to have a talk with friends and family about how important this is and that you'd appreciate their support â¤ğŸ™
.
.
I have been very lucky that my environment always suited my goals. My Dad, sister and friends were involved in sport and understood the importance of it to me. They understood social occasions were harder for me and they were supportive of my choices. My friends and family initially found it strange that I brought Tupperware with me everywhere ğŸ˜… But it soon became the new norm ğŸ™ I am a result of my environment. The people I chose to associate with. The actions I choose on a daily basis. I want them to support my lifestyle not take away from it ğŸ‘
.
.
If you feel your environment is not supporting your goals, you need to take action ğŸ’¥ It's hard enough to create new habits without everything working against you ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ˜…

caption:
What is the key to results? 
CONSISTENCY ğŸ”‘
.
.
How do we stay consistent?
Finding something we enjoy and can sustain ğŸ™
.
.
If you don't see yourself doing it a year from now. It's not sustainable or something you enjoy ğŸš«
.
.
If you are someone who hates running but your friend Mary lost 2 stone from pounding the pavements so you plan on starting....
Find something else. Please ğŸ˜‘
.
If you love carbs but everyone tells you keto is the best weight loss diet. Keto may not be the best option for you. ğŸ¥©
.
If you've never cycled over 5km in your life but you 'want to challenge yourself' and sign up to a triathlon without training. You my friend are a lunatic. ğŸš´â€â™€ï¸
.
.
I'm going to give you a success story. Not a client of mine. But my boyfriend. Owen has been training for years and years. He's dipped in and out. Trained hard 5 days a week for weeks, then nothing. He's never been consistent. During lockdown in March, Owen started coaching with @komplexfitness. Owen is now approximately 7-8 months consistently training (he missed 1 session - due to a severe hangover ğŸ˜…).
.
Owen is the strongest he's ever been and he looks great. Why?
- He enjoys his training. 
- He can fit it into his lifestyle. 
- Kevin is obviously an alright coach ğŸ˜œğŸ˜…
.
.
Be like Owen. Find something you like. Something you can sustain. And something that helps get you to your goals ğŸ’ª

caption:

.

People can't believe it when I tell them I've only consistently been doing Crossfit since March.

What they don't see is the 6 years of CONSISTENT strength training. The 18 years of football training. My capacity is big. I've been training for a long time. 
.
.
I wouldn't say I'm a keg now but I've a pretty big glass. The bigger the glass, the easier everything becomes. It's the reason a balanced lifestyle is easier for me than Mary who needs to lose a stone. My glass is bigger. Therefore, my lean muscle mass is bigger. Therefore, this has a positive impact on my BMR. Hence, I can eat chocolate and get away with it while Mary just needs to look at Chocolate and she has gained 2lbs. 
.
.
Work on making the glass bigger. Everything else will come ğŸ™

caption:
If scales is the only measure of progress you're using, you are are going down a slippery slope. â›°
.
.
What happens if you don't lose weight one week? Does it undo all the hard work you've done? All the consistent effort you've made. All the new habits you've built. Or what if your weight plateaus? Does this mean you quit and give up? ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
We are all impatient humans. And we want to be rewarded for our hard work. And that's fair. But success does not happen overnight in any industry so why would weight loss be different. ğŸš«

Start Taking Responsibility for your actions ğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆ
.
.
If you are not where you want to be, it is NO One else's fault but yours.
.
.
ğŸš«Stop blaming friends and family members 
ğŸš«Stop blaming gyms and exercise methods
ğŸš«Stop blaming diet approaches 
ğŸš«Stop blaming coaches
ğŸš«Stop blaming time restrictions
ğŸš«Stop blaming money limitations
.
.
You are ultimately the problem. You HAVE to take part in your own rescue ğŸ›¶
.
.
ğŸ”ŠBefore trying yet another diet or another exercise method or another trainer. Why not stick with something? Not for 6 weeks or 6 months. Why not try 6 years?
.
.
ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
I am not where I want to be. But I am a hell of a lot closer than I was 2 years ago. If you want to compare yourself to me, why not compare these stats:
ğŸ‘‰ I have been playing intercounty football for over 10 years
ğŸ‘‰ I have on average been in the gym 4 days a week for over 6 years. That is 1300 gym sessions. 
ğŸ‘‰ I have drank 2L water at least 95% of the time for the last 10 years.
ğŸ‘‰ I have a healthy balanced diet - no extremes of diet and binge - for about 6 years (not including the picky years ğŸ˜…)
ğŸ‘‰ Up until this year, I have drank very IRREGULARLY.
ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
.
.
So unless thats comparable to you. Stop comparing yourself. I was considered a semi professional athlete. I made HUGE sacrifice to get to the fitness level I am at right now (and I still want to be a hell of a lot fitter).
.
.
Comparison is the thief of joy. Stay in your own lane. Be patient. And bloody stick to something long term ğŸ˜…ğŸ™ˆ

caption:
ğŸŒŸLet's talk periods and training ğŸŒŸ
.
.
Firstly, I am so happy with how normal it now is to talk about periods ğŸ™ Secondly, having a period is such a good thing and I think until you've lost it, you'll never realise how good it is to have it. (P.s I've never lost mine. Just through client's experiences)
.
.
I'm going to start off with the fact that until this week I have never ever followed the information I'm about to give you. But after my nightmare training week last week, I promise my body I will now train WITH my cycle and not against ğŸ™Œ I'm pretty happy I have an excuse as to why my performance was so poor last week ğŸ˜…ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
So here are just some of the things going on within your body:

Follicular Phase

â— Increase in estrogen = increase in strength
â— Increase in pain threshold
â— Increase in insulin sensitivity = increased efficiency in burning carbs
â— Muscle recovers well = get training

Ovulation Phase

â— Increase in all hormones including testosterone
â— Up to 11% increase in strength
â— Increase in estrogen
â— Increase in metabolism = increase in appetite 
â— Water retention & bloating can occur

Luteal Phase

â— Decrease in estrogen & progesterone
â— Decrease in serotonin = PMS starts to kick in
â— Increase in water retention
â— Increase in body temperature
â— Decreased quality in sleep
â— Craving sugar
â— Not a good time to do measurements
â— Best to avoid max training / PBâ€™S

Menstrual Phase

â— PMS starts to subside
â— Experience cramping
â— Reduction in body temperature
â— Increase in energy
â— Insulin sensitivity starts to increase
.
.
Taper your training to your cycle. It doesn't mean you have to lie in bed for 2 out of 4 weeks. Sometimes it's hard to talk to a coach or trainer about these things but you HAVE to listen to your body.
.
.
I have tried for too long to think I am invincible. That I can train hard 365 days a years. It's BS. And at almost 30 I am finally starting to realise I need to listen to my body and my cycle. Thankfully I copped on before losing it ğŸ™â¤
.
.
#trainingaroundyourcycle

caption:
ğŸ’¥ Name Change ğŸ’¥
.
.
Old news I know ğŸ¤£
.
.
I got so many people asking why? 
.
.
So here it is. 
.
.
When I started in the fitness industry, I was a footballer. I actually wanted it to be cleanandleangaagirl but a friend veered me away from it saying it'd narrow my audience. 7 years ago I ate super clean. I still believe in natural wholefoods, I am still a huge advocate but I don't eat clean full time ğŸ¤£ I'm much more about that balanced lifestyle. Finally, being lean is NOT important to me anymore. It's not a goal, it's not something I work towards and it's not a word I want associated with me.
.
.
Where do I see myself now?
I see myself as a coach. I truely believe I have helped a lot of people over the last 7 years. I've helped people in A LOT of ways. I don't call myself a pt or a nutritionist but a combo of both. I've changed people's lifestyles which to me is a lot more important than any meal plan or training programme I can prescribe. I absolutely love my job. I love helping people and I'm so happy to call this my job. 
.
.
In short, I no longer play sport, I don't eat clean 100% of the time and I'm not worried about being lean ğŸ¤£ I am however a coach. A good one at that, and thats what I want to be recognised as ğŸ˜
.
.
#thanksforthesupport

caption:
Building Habits ğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘Š

.

.

This approach has been game changer with my clients. It's slower but so much more sustainable.

.

.

I do it in relation to nutrition,training and mindset.

.

.

Without a doubt, its impact on nutrition is invaluable. It teaches people to slow down when it comes to nutrition. Making them realise its not all about 0 to 100. There are ALOT of numbers in between there ğŸ˜… It's simple and relatively easy. 

.

.

Examples include: Drinking 2L water consistently EVERY DAY. Eating vegetables with lunch. Treat every second day. 

.

.

It also works for movement. 10,000 steps daily is a habit. I have clients who nail this daily. And clients who STRUGGLE!!! But having that target helps them move more than without a target. Quite often if I have someone hitting 1000 Steps a day, I won't throw an unrealistic target of 10,000 on their back. Ill start with 2-3k. Hit that for a week great. Increase to 4,000. Hit that EVERY day. Great. Increase again. And so on. NEW HABIT BUILT! You need wins along the way. Otherwise you will quit. Make things achievable.

.

.

Same goes for mindset. Journaling, meditation and reading Are all great habits to work on with clients. 

.

.

Here are some of my habits I'm planning over the next 6 weeks. I've  already nailed the basics so that's why I'm jumping. Please don't jump until youve the basics nailed ğŸ˜…

.

.

Week 1 - No alcohol âœ…

Week 2 - Intermittent Fasting 

Week 3 - Fruit or veggies at every meal

Week 4 -No bread or chocolate

Week 5 - Fizzy drinks only at weekends

Week 6 - Full clean week - No processed food

.
.

caption: Opinions? ğŸ¤”

Sometimes the world scares me ğŸ˜”
.
.
Nothing to do with this pandemic. But just our day to day lives ğŸ˜”
.
.
On Saturday I got Owen to take a picture of me with a white light on me just to look better ğŸ˜¢ Turned out I actually looked even nicer with no bright light (the above photo). This is common for people, I know. But not for me. I pride myself on NOT being like that. I believe in loving yourself warts and all. I've never used editing apps (I can barely use a filter ğŸ˜…). But I did this. Why? To get a few extra likes? Maybe a few extra followers? 
THAT IS NOT ME ğŸ˜­
.
.
Also on Saturday, someone tried to sabotage an event @acountydownunder was organising. Let me explain the nature of the event.
Bringing people together in Sydney from all parts of the world, to be united during these tough times. Can you believe someone could do that? I was appauledğŸ˜¢
.
.
Finally, on Saturday. I met the most incredible bunch of ladies who I would have never met, if it weren't for Facebook and Instagram ğŸ™
.
.
The point to this post... ?
A lot happened on Saturday ğŸ˜…
.
.
No.
.
.
Social media and the world today can be an amazing platform for meeting new people, sharing likeminded opinions and general positive messages.
.
.
But there is a nasty side. One that is jealous of other people's success. One that changes you to be someone you are not ğŸ˜¢
.
.
You do have a choice.
.
.
If social media is negatively impacting you. Delete it. If you follow someone who impacts how you feel about yourself, unfollow them.
.
.
I plan on reducing my screen time as I think it's negatively impacting me a little. It doesn't mean I'm leaving - far from it. I just plan on occupying my time with things I've been neglecting like Mobility, Podcasts and reading ğŸ™
.
.
Use social media for good â¤
.
.
What is your opinion?

.

Sexiness and body confidence is not:

âœ– A number on a scales

âœ– A dress size

âœ– A certain body fat percentage

âœ– Free from cellulite or stretch marks

âœ– Filters

âœ– Super fit or unfit

âœ–The loudest or quietest person in the room

âœ–With make up or without

.

.

Confidence is how you perceive yourself. It's a smile. It's being happy in the clothes your wearing. Happy in the company of others.Â Comfortable in your relationship. It's being happy in your own skin with and without beauty products. It's exercising and eating well because you want to not becauae you have to.

.

caption: Walk slowly but never backward ğŸ™

Cauliflower Rice vs Brown Rice
.
.
Which is best?
.
.
Answer is.
.
.
Neither are better, neither are worse.
.
.
I eat both. But why you are eating it depends on your goals ğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘ŠğŸ‘Š
.
.
âœ… Weight loss a goal? Cauliflower rice is low in calories and high in volume so may be a great option
âœ…Alternatively, portion control of brown rice can also work.
âœ… Performance a goal? You will not get the same complex carbs from caulifower rice as you will from brown rice. 
âœ… Both have different nutritional compositions when it comes to vitamins and minerals.
âœ… Taste? Force feeding yourself cauliflower rice because your favourite fitness influencer recommended it? YOU ARE JUST BEING STUPID!!!! 
.
.
There is no right or wrong answer to comparing these. As always, it is dependent on your individual goals and anyone that gives you a clear defined answer is a fruad ğŸ˜…ğŸš«
.
.

caption:
Training with an injury?
.
.
I had a poll on this a few weeks ago and a majority of people voted they agree with it.
.
.
Lets be totally clear on the context. It was training WITH an injury. Not training THROUGH an injury. Very different. 
.
.
However, it is not uncommon to train through an injury either. I want to be clear here. I am NOT telling you to train with an injury. This is very individual dependent and requires advice from a professional I.e Doctor, physio etc.
.
.
âœ…Training with an injury

ğŸ‘‰ Anyone who knows me, knows how much of an advocate I am of this. When I injure lower body, upper body is still very much manageable, however, I am careful not to put too much pressure on affected area

ğŸ‘‰ Mental Health - I don't know about the rest of you but mental health is one of my main reasons for training so if I had to sit still I'd cry ğŸ˜©

ğŸ‘‰ Socialising - It can be a tough time going through an injury. If you are a sports player it can be so isolating ğŸ˜¢ Being able to do something in th gym, in a class or with your team can have a huge impact on your mindframe â¤

â¡ï¸ Training through an injury

ğŸš« Only do under advice from your healthcare professional (But a little bit of important info is there actually is evidence to suggest you can)

My non negotiables the day after drinking:
.
ğŸ‘Š 10,000 Steps. You don't need to make a workout. You don't have to move fast. Just move.
ğŸ‘Š 2L water - minimum 
ğŸ‘Š No sugar filled drinks - if I want something fizzy I go for a sugar free alternative
ğŸ‘Š Don't eat like an asshole. You don't NEED 10,000 calories the next day. Try get back to a normal routine. It doesn't have to be kale smoothies but get your  normal rotuine back. Decent breakfast, protein in every meal and lots of micros.
.
.
The day after drinking doesn't have to be perfect. But just stay consistent. A lot of my clients love to socialise and want to be able to incorporate it into their lifestyle. caption:

.

Mindset is more than half the battle when it comes to our goals. Ever hear the saying 'the body achieves what the mind believes '.

.

.

I firmly believe a positive attitude helps the body and mind in more ways than you can even imagine ğŸ™

.

.

Begin each day with something positive. This sets your body and mind up for the whole day

.

.

My morning Ritual:

ğŸ’¥ NOT snoozing my alarm - when my phone buzzes at 5am. I am up with bells on. (Yes I am an annoying morning person)

ğŸ’¥I have myÂ  bag packed and breakfast made from the night before - so I am organised and not rushing and racing

ğŸ’¥My morning coffee - unfortunately I dont get the time to sit on social media and reflect on my morning coffee thoughts ğŸ˜… (but i still have them)

ğŸ’¥Morning bootcamps or client coaching calls start my day the right way

.

I find things i am grateful for EVERY SINGLE DAY. I may not jot them down but I have them. (If it's not already obvious this man is certainly one of them ğŸ’•)

.

.

Something I get my clients to do is physically write them down. 3 a day. It can be something as simple as morning coffee to being proud you've overcome cancer. Its relative to you. No one else.

.

.

If you are not willing to work on your mind, good luck working on your overall health ğŸš«

caption:

.

.

So one of the things I harp on about constantly as a nutritionist is trying to get more vegetables in my client's diet ğŸ¥¦ğŸ¥’ğŸ„

.

.

But did you know how you cook your veggies can have an impact on it's nutritional status? For example: when boiling vegetables you may lose a lot of the vitamins in the water. Roasting vegetables can actually change the glycaemic index of a food. And any cooking methodÂ  can cause loss of fibre from the vegetables.

. 

.

What does this mean?

Get a variety of vegetables in your diet. And a variety of different cooking methods 

E.g A salad for lunch and roast veggies for dinner

Or Raw Spinach for breakfast and a stirfy for lunch

caption:
ğŸ’£The gym shark controversy validated what I have been saying for the last few years.
.
.
ğŸ’¥Fitness is no longer about being fit but rather 'looking fit'ğŸ’¥
.
.
ğŸ’¯When I became a trainer, I too was obsessed with the quest for the perfect body. Small waist, big bum, abs..
.
.
ğŸ’¢Not necessarily because I actually wanted these things but because thats what i thought being 'fit' was. I associated fitness with aesthetics and beauty. And let's call a spade a spade, most fitness influencers look flawless at all times. 
I could have easily ended up going down this route. On the constant search for beauty and perfection.
.
.
ğŸ’¢But I enjoyed 'being fit' too much. Being fit includes: inappropriate sweat patches, a red face and HARD WORK!!! While others focused on their booty poses and dieted until they see 'perfect abs' , I got fitter. And Fitter. And now, im the fittest Ive ever been (injury and all)
.
.
ğŸš«Im very disappointed at how 'fitness' has turned into a beauty contest because that is NOT what it is. Fitness comes in all shapes and sizes with varying different levels. 
.
.
âš ï¸I remember a time when I was a teenager where fitness was just associated with how aerobically fit you were? How strong you were? How fast you were? How much you've progressed and improved?
I'd like to go back to this.âš ï¸
.
.
Can we please make fitness normal againâ“â“â“

caption:
#balance
'ğ“ğ¨ ğ ğ¢ğ¯ğ ğ¬ğğ¯ğğ«ğšğ¥ ğ­ğ¡ğ¢ğ§ğ ğ¬ ğğªğ®ğšğ¥ ğšğ¦ğ¨ğ®ğ§ğ­ğ¬ ğ¨ğŸ ğ¢ğ¦ğ©ğ¨ğ«ğ­ğšğ§ğœğ, ğ­ğ¢ğ¦ğ ğ¨ğ« ğ¦ğ¨ğ§ğğ² ğ’ğ¨ ğ­ğ¡ğšğ­ ğš ğ¬ğ¢ğ­ğ®ğšğ­ğ¢ğ¨ğ§ ğ¢ğ¬ ğ¬ğ®ğœğœğğ¬ğ¬ğŸğ®ğ¥'
.
.
Balance isn't always about an 80/20 rule. Balance isn't the same for every one. 
.
.
Sometimes balance is bloody hard. It took me years to find balance. And now I still question if I have it. Instead of being too strict, am I now being to lenient?

.
.
Balance can cause anxiety for people. 
.
.
How are some people able to eat pizza and still remain lean? I eat 100% clean and still can't see changes? ğŸ˜¢ Do I have enough protein in my diet? Do I drink too much? Is low calorie Ice cream or no ice cream the best option? How many steps should I be taking? What exercise is best? Is rest important?
.
.
My opinion: If it works towards your goals, do it. If not, don't!!!
.
.
There is no right or wrong. Just what's right for you ğŸ‘†

caption:
And in the red corner... Weighing in at 71kg... Amanda Mc Loone ğŸ¥ŠğŸ¥ŠğŸ¥Š
.
.
Currently sitting at my heaviest EVER weight. I don't actually normally weigh myself but I had to get it done for something.
.
.
If I used scale weight to objectify my progress I think it's safe to say I'd be pretty darn disappointed ğŸ˜‚ But I don't.
.
.
A scale weight does not determine my worth. It doesn't signify how fit I am. It doesn't show how strong I am (it does however make it harder to do pull ups ğŸ™ˆ). It doesn't have any relevance to how hard I work or my job. So why would I let one number determine my happiness?
.
.
Those extra few kilos are the memories I've made. Those extra few kilos are the weekends that I've enjoyed more than ever before. Those extra few kilos are able to lift some extra weight.
.
.
So please, before you let a scale number determine your happiness, think about what that number actually means. To me, it means freedom. ğŸ™Œ

.
.

.
.

.
My mood may improve tomorrow. It may take until Monday. But it will improve. And I will get back to normality. 
.
.
We all have bad weeks. We all struggle. None of us are perfect.
.
.

.
.

.
.

caption:
I am a strong woman ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™†â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Yes in the physical sense. I have worked for years to get stronger and build a body I feel confident in. I have consistently trained for the last 10 years. First at intercounty football which then led to my love of strength and resistance trainingğŸ˜ My body is a reflection of that.
.
.
But I am so much stronger than my physique. My mental strength is something you cannot see, but it's much stronger than any weight I could lift. Or any competition I'll do. 
I have gone through more than most will go through in a lifetime. I have had my own share of mental health issues. But I have come out the other side. A true reflection of my mental strength.
.
.
I have worked damn hard to be in the position I am in right now. I said to a client yesterday how lucky I am to have got a job during COVID and how amazing my job, clients and boss are. And she said 'Amanda, you are not lucky. You've worked for this.' She was right. 
.
.
It's an amazing feeling to feel like a strong woman. A strong woman can be intimidating. A strong woman can come off as bossy. A strong woman can get a hostile response especially from the opposite sex. And this is where I acknowledge the strong men in my life. Most notably my Dad was the strongest man I've ever known. Owen has the patience of a saint. And final shout out to the men I've worked with who were not immasculated taking orders from a woman and the bosses I've had who not only considered my opinion but actually valued it. ğŸ™
.
.
I am a strong woman. Are you?

caption:
It took my Dad dying 5 years ago for me to finally find true happiness...
.
.
Not that I wasn't happy before that. But his death made me question everything. I really went on a journey of self discovery ğŸ™
.
.
Just because you are living doesn't mean you're truely alive â¤
.
.
So what changed when my Dad died:
1. I appreciated life so much more â¤ Life is precious and a gift.
. 
2. I discovered travel - I always thought I didn't want to travel. I believed I was a home bird and I didn't need it. My trip to Thailand with the girls was a game changer. I cannot thank my friends enough for helping me find travel.
.
3. Fell in love with myself - I was ridiculously self conscious. I don't have good skin so I always covered it up. I don't like my teeth so I wouldn't smile properly in pictures. I stopped focusing on all the negative aspects of my appearance.
.
4. I stopped caring about what people think of me. I remember years ago saying to my sister: how will you cover up those tattoos on your wedding day? And she replied: She loved them and she'll want them to be seen. I had this perception in my head that tattoos were 'unattractive' and should be covered up. I now see them as self expression and see my body as a canvas ğŸ™
.
5. I stopped working towards what I considered success to be. I remember after college I was so embarrassed that I worked in a restaurant. I was a fully qualified nutritionist working in a restaurant. I believed I was too good to work in that restaurant. Why? Because my peers and societal norms led me to believe I was better than that. I worked so hard for a good Leaving Cert to be top 10 in my school. Why? Because that's what everyone else did. The last few years I have been so content in my work, not because of how much money I earn but because I truely love my job. I don't put pressure on myself to be something I'm not.
.
6. I quit looking for a perfect body - When I was a teenager, I thought skinny was the perfect body type. My early 20s - lean was 'IN'. I now realise there is no such thing as a perfect body. But I'm happy in the one I'm in.
.
7. I stopped comparing myself to people - comparison truely is the thief of joy.
.
Continued in comments

caption:
The body is much more complex than comparing it to a bloody scales or seesaw ğŸ™„ğŸ˜‘
.
.
This one does really grind my gears. 
'Oh well you're just not in a calorie deficit'
Well you know Sharon it's not always that simple ğŸ¤¨
.
.
What can also have an impact on total daily energy expenditure:
ğŸ’¥ The type of food you eat - the thermic effect of food has an impact on our TDEE
ğŸ’¥ Endocrine System - hormones and hormonal imbalances can have a huge impact on our TDEE
ğŸ’¥ Chronic Inflammation - due to a number of different things: stress, illness,  poor diet etc
ğŸ’¥ Lack of sleep - Sleep is as important for weight loss as exercise and nutrition - look up the scientific literature
.
.
This does NOT mean calories don't matter. They do. But they're not the only things that matter. This post is to inform you that your body is complex. Much more complex than we think. That's why as a nutritionist my LAST question is actually about nutrition and food. I get a full insight into people's whole lives. It's not always as simple as a calculation unfortunately.
.
.
â›” This post does not give your lazy ass a license to use hormones or 'adrenal fatigue' as an excuse. â›”

#butitcouldbe
