caption:
Priorities
.
.
What are yours?
Â 
- Karen wants to be super lean <20% BF. But Karen enjoys socialising at the weekend and religiously has a takeawayÂ to cure herself Sunday. Karen doesn't want to put in the commitment to get to her goal. And that's ok, because it's not 'easy' to get visible abs. It requires sacrifice. It requires hard work. And not everyoneÂ is willing to do that.Â 

- John wants to become a 6 figure coach. John works 9-5 Monday to Friday. John trains himself twice a day. John competes in bodybuilding competitions (he's in GREAT SHAPE). But he won't sacrifice his training for his client's timetables. John is not making sacrifices. John is unlikely to become a 6 figure coach with his current attitude.

When I played football....

I lived, slept and breathed football.

My whole life revolved around football - social occassions, relationships, friendships, family events, work. I honestly mean MY WHOLE LIFE. Some would have called me obsessed. But I truely believe this is the level you need to prioritise Inter County football. I was never the best player in the world but findÂ someone who worked harder than me, not just on the pitch but in every element of my life. I am an athlete.Â I still consider myself an athlete but myÂ prioritiesÂ have definitely shifted.Â 

Instead of Sunday morning matches, I have swapped it for Sunday morning breakfast. Instead of Friday night training, I'm enjoying Friday morning training in the gym. Instead of a very lean physique, it's obvious I train but enjoy chocolate too ;)Â 

Priorities change and that's ok.Â 

If you are someone who's willing to put in minimal effort but expecting huge results, it's not going to happen (unless you are genetically gifted). If you are someone that enjoys socialising every weekend, you're probably not going to make an Inter county team.

'But just don't be disappointed in the results you didn't get for the effort you didn't put in.'

caption:
It would be so hard to be a teenager right now ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I thought my teenage years were tough. I can definitely say it was the peak of my self loathing. I hated my body. I drank too much. I self harmed. I worked too hard. I put too much pressure on myself.
.
.
And I didn't have social media or drugs in that era ğŸ¥ºğŸ˜
.
.
1. Social Media
The ideal of perfection is damaging. The 'perfect body'. The 'perfect make up'. The 'perfect picture'. The 'perfect life'. It's ALL FAKE NEWS!!!!!! Please please please stop following people who make you feel inferior. Stop trying to look like influencers. Stop trying to seek a perfection that doesn't exsist ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
2. Drugs
Since when are drugs the norm? ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ Yes I am going to address the elephant in the room ğŸ˜ I actually cannot get my head around this... It's like teenagers are now fully grown adults ğŸ˜” Making choices like this probably won't affect you now. But NO ONE IS THINKING ABOUT THE FUTURE!!! ğŸ˜Ÿ 
.
.
I feel like I am old (maybe not wise) beyond my years. Everyone is looking for the quick fix. The easy option. The momentary high. No one is thinking about the long term. Their health? Long term health ğŸ˜¶ Physical and Mental Health ğŸ˜ğŸ˜£
.
.
Can we please protect this group of young adults? Can we please do our best to be good role models? Can we show them that perfection DOESN'T exsist? Can we encourage them to act their age and stop trying to be and look like adults? 
.
.
Make mistakes. ğŸ”
Take silly photos.ğŸ“¸ 
School is important but so is life.ğŸ“š Travel (when we get out of this). ğŸ–
.
.
Rant over âš ï¸âš ï¸âš ï¸

caption:
SMART GOALS ğŸš€ğŸš€ğŸš€
.
.
DO YOU REALLY NEED THEM? Well if you're looking to make progress, yes!!!
.
.
How long have you been wanting to get a pull up for? How long have you wanted to lose that extra kg? How long have you wanted to improve your speed? 
.
.
Well then you need to make smart goals. You also need to take action  in the steps to achieving these goals. What are SMART GOALS?
.
.
S - Specific - Weight loss is too general. You need a specific target in mind and a path to get you to that goal.
.
M - Mesurable - 60m dash speed is measurable - 'getting faster' Isn't 
.
A - Achievable - this one is a BIG one. Please don't set yourself up for failure. If you have just started resistance training and you want to compete in a bikini competitions in 8 weeks with no coach you are setting yourself up for a fail ğŸ™ˆ
.
R - Realistic - If you are playing high level football and want to sign up for a Crossfit competition just don't ğŸ˜… (unless you are me. I know Pot Kettle Black - I still wouldn't advise it)
.
T - Time Specific - Instead of 'I want to be able to do 10 Chin ups (btw this is a very hard goal) - why not say ' I want to be able to do 1 chin up in 8 weeks and maybe 5 Chin ups in 6 months'
.
.
Now you have your goals decided make a plan to make it to your destination. If your goal is to master chin ups and your constantly doing hiit classes (unless the classes have this in it) you're probably never going to achieve that goal. If your goal is weight loss but you're not interested in changing your diet, you're probably never going to achieve that goal. Be SMART about your planning too ğŸ™ƒ 
.
.
Some of my goals to share with you:
ğŸ’« I want to be able to do All Rx exercises by the end of 2020
ğŸ’« I want top 100 in Ireland in 2021 Open
ğŸ’« I want a 50kg Snatch by September 
ğŸ’« I want an 80kg C&J by the end of 2020

caption:
My own journey ğŸ‘¸ğŸ‘¸ğŸ‘¸
.

I truely believe people think. Ah ya, she's always been fit it's easy for her. Sure what would I know I've never had to lose weight ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Not every battle can be seen ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
I struggled with my image from a young age. People will think I was always confident, always the life and soul of the party. But it wasn't until I seen a counsellor that I realised I was masking my unhappiness. I had issues I didn't even know exsisted. When I was in school I was so self conscious. I had mental health problems I didn't know exsisted. These continued on into my early 20s. I was obsessed with my body image. EVERY single time I walked past a mirror I checked for abs. I took photos of myself every single day on the quest for a 6 pack ğŸ˜” My relationship with food and exercise was poor ğŸ˜° I honestly thought I was not lean in the first photo ğŸ˜¬
.
.
Fast forward to being 29 ğŸ¥° I cannot believe the journey I've been on to get here but I am in love with the process ğŸ¤© I am so proud of what my body can do. I fuel it right. I'm good to it (most of the time, unless I do too much ğŸ¤ªğŸ˜¶). It's not all about the physical. Physically I'm probably the fittest I've ever been but MENTALLY I'm 100% the best I've ever been ğŸ’˜ 
.
.
So please don't think I don't know what it's like. That because my journey is not weight loss, that it doesn't matter or count. EVERY journey to better health matters. EVERY conscious effort to improve mental and physical health matters. You matter ğŸ˜˜

caption:
Back to the gym this week or in the coming weeks? ğŸ¤”
.
.
LEAVE YOUR EGO AT THE DOOR. ğŸ¦§
.
.
Similar to the football post I put up a couple of weeks ago. There are a lot of considerations when going back to exercise in a gym setting ğŸ™ƒ
.
.
As per usual, this is very individual based but I'll try make this advice as generic as possible ğŸ˜Š
.
.
1. Don't expect to lift what you lifted pre Covid (unless you've had a home gym setting and have been training consistently during isolation)
2. Ease yourself in. 3 days of training will be MORE than enough. You WILL be sore. You don't need to make up for lost time. You don't need to punish yourself for the extra half stone you gained. Just ease yourself back in.
3. Get back into a routine. Sleep, hydration and training. Make these a priority.
4. Recovery is KEY!!!!! Nutrition will be more important than ever. Protein is our principal recovery food. Eat it in abundance. Carbs are our main energy source. Don't neglect them. Essentials fats have anti inflammatory properties. Eat them ğŸ¥‘ And let's make sure our immune system is in tip top shape. Keep lots of colour and fibre in there too ğŸ†ğŸğŸŒğŸ¥’ğŸ„
.
.
It's pretty simple really
.
.
If you want to avoid monstrous doms and increasing risk of injury. Take this advice.

caption:
Lets talk fruit ğŸ‘ğŸŠğŸŒğŸğŸ“ğŸğŸ¥ğŸ‡
.
.
I 'prescribed' a client to eat more fruit during the week. And she questioned the idea 'does too much fruit not store as fat?'. Too much anything will result in excess calories which will result in weight gain. Too much Fruit will not solely 'turn to fat'. .
.
The difficult thing with nutrition and understanding nutrition is there is so much crap on the internet. And then even the science changes regularly so it really is a minefield ğŸ¤¯ğŸ¤¯ğŸ¤¯
.
.
This guide is great to show that you can get a lot more bang for your buck with fruits like berries and watermelon. More quantity leaves a greater satiety which avoids over eating. As opposed to a simple banana that is convenient.
.
.
I have had people over consume fruit. It's not totally false. And if you are bodybuilding or prepping fpr something that requires a very low body fat, you may need to be careful with fruit. Fruits are simple sugars and are classified as carbohydrates. But they are full of vitamins, minerals, water and fibre. And believe me, with majority of population, fruit is the least of your worries ğŸ™ƒğŸ˜‰ #fruitforthewin #deliciousandnutritious

Want a strong core? ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™‚ï¸
.
.
As most of you already know I was allergic to core work ğŸ˜… I did it through my strength training and that was it. I have no desire to have a 6 pack so it just seemed irrelevant to do isolation exercises ğŸ˜…ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
Since starting my Crossfit Programme my core strength has been seriously tested. I thought (and still believe) I don't have a weak core. But there are so many levels our core strength can get to. Gymnastics is a new ball game to me and my God has my core has been tested ğŸ¤ªğŸ˜¬ I'm now very happy I've been doing this extra core work because it's helped a lot.
.
.
1. Toes to Bar
2. L Sit
3. Hollow Rocks
4. Half Get Up
5. Palloff Press with Squat
6. Side Plank rotations
.
.
These are just some of the exercises I'm doing regularly. Again, they are a little more advanced. And don't expect miracles when it comes to training your core. I'm not promising a six pack but I certainly believe I'm getting stronger doing it ğŸ’ª

.

.

.
.
A little information about me:
ğŸ‘† I am HIGHLY self motivated. I work outrageously hard at what I do in all areas of my life. Not everyone is. That's fine (And also where investing in a coach is a very good idea). ğŸ‘† I am really positive. Not always but I try to keep a good outlook on life. I have not had an easy ride. I have probably been through more in a couple of years than most go through in their lifetime. But I don't let it define me and I don't whinge and complain about it (all the time anyway ğŸ™ˆ).
ğŸ‘† I know what I'm good at but I also know where my weak points are. I'm constantly learning and I believe that we can all benefit from other knowledge and expertise.
ğŸ‘† I belive in giving compliments. People should know what a good job they are doing. Jealousy is natural but is usually a reflection of you and not the person or thing you are jealous of. Jealousy can actually have a postive effect on us if treated right, it can motivate us to get to where we WANT to be ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Long winded point of this post. Are you doing what you need to do, to get where you want to be?
ğŸ’¥For me, I'm working when other people are drinking. I'm awake when others are asleep. I'm training in the rain when other people are making excuses. ğŸ’¥
.
.

caption:
Let's talk sports injuries ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
You know what I'm talking about here. That person who constantly has 'tight hamstrings'. Or the full forward who repeatedly strains their calves. What about the goalie with the shoulder impingement?  Or the corner back who has tore their quad on more than one occasion ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I've had my fair share of serious injuries. I've had my ACL reconstructed. Broke the 2 bones in my wrist and had wires inserted. Dislocated fingers badly ğŸ™ˆI Attribute it to the fact that I put my body on the line and never pulled out of a tackle. My years and years of running the pitch ragged caught up on me when I developed tendonopathy in my Achilles but I've never had a muscular injury ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
Why? Especially after ACL reconstruction. People normally have issues. Why didn't I?
ğŸ’¥Firstly, I am not a physio or a doctor. What I'm about to say is my opinionğŸ’¥
.
ğŸŒŸ Consistency - This is a major problem in the world of GAA. Players spend a month or 2 in pre season and that's their gym work for the year done âŒâŒâŒ Strength based training should be done year long for athletes. A good coach will periodise it and tailor it to the individual and their workload. But it should not be neglected mid season
.
. ğŸŒŸKnowledge - It's not enough to be doing a few Squats and Pull ups. If you are 'doing your own thing' or 'copying other people' it won't suffice. Pitch athletes require good exercise prescription, relevant to them and their sport. Basic, generic plans could lead to injury.
.
.
ğŸŒŸNutrition - High protein diet with carbohydrates for fuel, good fats for recovery and micro nutrients for immune function. Again, not just in season but off season too. Please do not under estimate the importance of good nutrition year round â¤ï¸ğŸ™Œ
.
.
I was lucky enough to have a solid career on the pitch. Even when I had serious injuries I bounced back from them. I wasn't the player constantly on the side line with recurring injuries ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸And that wasn't down to luck. That was down to looking after myself.
.
.
Continued in comments

caption:
It can be this simple ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
.
.
1. Fill up your plate with nutrient dense, low calorie vegetables.
2. Add a decent protein source - opt for oily fish regularly 3-4 times a week. White meat/fish is lower calorie if weight loss is the goal. 
3. You don't need to eliminate carbohydrates. Our body wants them. Our brain needs them. Just reduce your portion size and choose the right type of carbs.
4. P. S Fats are also vitally important but I've used this as a typical 'Irish dinner' (meat, veg and spuds typeğŸ‡®ğŸ‡ª) .
.

.

caption:
Let's make salad tasty and enjoyable ğŸ˜
Rather than using the term 'rabbit food' ğŸ°
.
.
ğŸ’¥5 Steps to a tasty, nutritious SaladğŸ’¥
. 
1. Choose your base - I usually go spinach, you could go iceberg lettuce, kale, whatever you fancy
.
.
2. Add in some extra colour - I usually go beetroot, maybe carrot or peppers - I know tomatoes are a staple or maybe you'd like to add some olives ğŸ¸
.
.
3. Add in some fats and/or Carbs - I tend to add a cheese - Feta, Goats, Halloumi. I sometimes add carbs to my salads but I rather fats. You could add cous cous or quinoa.
.
.
4. Add dressing - this is my go to. Low cÃ¡l and the tastiest there is. The odd time I might use pesto but I never waste my calories on dressings ğŸ·
.
.
5. Add a protein and I like to add some fruit to colour â¤ï¸ğŸ’œğŸ’™ I tend to be a salmon, chicken or turkey burger gal ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Don't think for a single second just because you eat salads you'll lose weight ğŸ™„ Salads have the potential to have higher calories than you think. Overdoing it on fat based foods like cheese or nuts or calorie laden dressings are the 2 main culprits ğŸ˜ There's also the fact that because they don't 'fill you' you may over eat after it ğŸ˜•
.
.
Salads are amazing and should be a staple in most people's diets but don't think eating them automatically means you Lose weight ğŸ˜…ğŸ‘† #deliciousandnutritious

A complex is any series of movements performed back-to-back with the same piece of equipment in which the set number of reps is completed for each movement before moving on to the next. It is also nice to create a flow for the exercises. You can do this with a Barbell, Kettlebell, Dumbells, a Sandbag or a Deadball. It is a another great way to increase difficulty of exercises with limited equipment during quarantine. ğŸ™Œ
.
.
My Complex This morning was 20 sets of:
- 1 Deadlift
- 1 Hang Clean
- 1 Split Jerk
(The ideal weight should be determined by the most difficult exercise. So for example this deadlift was relatively easy for me but the split Jerk was harder.)
.
.
An idea of a double DB Complex Could be:
- 10 Renegade Row
- 10 RDL
- 10 Cleans
- 10 Front Squat
- 10 Push Press
.
.
These are a great way to get more bang for your buck with very little equipment ğŸ™Œ

ğŸ‘‰For years we were told you NEED to eat Breakfast...
ğŸ‘‰Then we were told to fast...
.
.
So what's the deal? Is breakfast really the most important meal of the day? ğŸ¤”
.
.
So I'm not going talk from a scientific perspective right now. Even though a lot of the science that is thrown around this topic is all horse crap anyway ğŸ™ˆ From a personal perspective.
.
.
ğŸ‘‰ If you absolutely detest eating a breakfast. I say don't eat a breakfast. I'm not going to force feed someone a breakfast 'so they don't go into starvation mode' ğŸ™ˆ. But if they're general wake up call is a cigarette and a coffee, I'd recommend something a little more substantial of course. But forcing and scare mongoring is not something I recommend.
ğŸ‘‰On the opposite scale of things, fasting is not for everyone. It is not some miracle weight loss programme. It is simply, consuming fewer calories in a smaller space of time. It works for some people it doesn't for others. I personally like to push my breakfast out to 9 or 10am because my days are long. If I start eating when I get up, I'd eat too much calories, simply because I'm eating too many times ğŸ˜‚
.
.
We over complicate everything ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜‚ Please don't listen to celebrities or unqualified people about these topicsğŸ¤”
.
.
It's (for the most part - not all cases I.e someone who's diabetic etc) this simple. If you want to eat breakfast eat it. If you don't, don't.
ğŸ’¥Fasted cardio is useless unless you are in a calorie deficit.
ğŸ’¥Your body will not 'eat itself' if you skip breakfast.

T. U. T (Time under Tension) or Tempo ğŸ’¥
.
.
This is not something I discuss regularly because this is normally an advance on normal gym training. I tend to keep things simple for people because people over complicate everything ğŸ™„ Basics first always ğŸ˜‚
.
.
But as most people are probably struggling with equipment this may be a handy tool ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
TUT or Tempo refers to how long or how much time a muscle is under strain. The longer time your muscle is under stress the greater muscle fiber recruitment it will have. You will usually load the muscle in the eccentric phase (downward portion of the exercise). So as you are lowering yourself in a Squat or lowering yourself down from a pull up. In the videos, I am slowly controlling my movements. The weight is light but because I am using TUT and adding more reps I am getting more bang for my buck ğŸ’¶ğŸ’¶ğŸ’¶
.
.

Let's talk labelling âœ¨âœ¨âœ¨ .
.
I'm a big fan of this type of labelling in Australia ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘Œ
.
.
In Ireland, we have a traffic light system which in my opinion is very flawed. Foods receive green, amber and red lights. It is based solely on calories. Fats contain 9kcal per gram. So technically they are high in calories. But certain foods like nuts, nut butters and avocados while high in calories are full of other nutrients. But fats themselves are essential for fat soluble vitamin absorption, reducing inflammation and it's also an energy source. So should these high calorie foods receive a red light? ğŸ¤” Foods are not just calories. âŒâŒâŒ
.
.
This labelling gives a foodstuff a health indicator rather than a colour. I think it's a much more accurate and truer representation of the food rather than just based on calories alone ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
This being said calories are important and you can't just disregard them. Just be mindful and reduce portion size ğŸ¤—
.
.

Plant Based is defined as a diet consisting mostly of foods derived from plants, including vegetables, grains, nuts, seeds, legumes and fruits. ğŸ¤”
.
.
I base most if not all of my meals around plant based foods so... ğŸ¤” So yes I would consider my diet plant based ğŸ¥¬ğŸ¥‘ And I am in no way vegan. .
.
Veganism is a way of life. I have the height of respect of anyone choosing to do something for health purposes, whether I believe in it or not is irrelevant. But I don't agree with people changing their views or opinions after watching a TV show. I also don't believe anybody should scare monger anyone else into their choices ğŸ˜”And this goes for anything. Not just food choices. But please don't think by choosing a diet (any diet not just plant based) that automatically makes you exempt from disease. I genuinely know people who take drugs but they adhere to a vegan diet so ya know.... Health ğŸ˜
.
.
Anyway the basis of this post is education. Plant based diets don't have to be meat free diets. Natural whole foods like mentioned above should make up a large part of your diet, if health is a priority.  A herbivore is plant based. An omnivore can also be plant based. ğŸŒ±

Pregnancy was once considered a reason to stop all exercise and eat for two. Which often led to excessive weight gain, gestational diabetes, pre eclampsia, difficult births and difficulty with weight loss post partum. Now, obviously pregnancy is massively different for everyone. Unfortunately there is no one size fits all. But the information I'm giving is general recommendations. If you have any further questions. It is probably worth talking it over with your doctor or other medical professional â˜ºï¸
.
.
Exercise:
-Studies have shown that exercise during pregnancy can actually lead to easier birthing and healthy weight gain during pregnancy.
-It is also thought to be beneficial for post partum weight loss.
-Guidelines for exercise encourage women to stick with similar exercises prior to pregnancy. Light Resistance based training is highly recommended.
- Adaptations may be needed through different trimesters such as: Not lying on your back for too long or overhead extension exercises may need to be removed. This is very dependent on individuals
- Hiit training may not be recommended after trimester 1 - again very dependent on the individual and their training history but it will become a lot harder
- Light exercise like walking can possibly be done the whole way up until due date
- The main take home point from this is: Exercise during pregnancy is encouraged. Everyone's levels, capabilities and pregnancies are different so go with how you're feeling. Don't over exert yourself. And talk with your coach and doctor ğŸ™
.
.
Nutrition
- This idea of eating double for two is non sense ğŸ™ˆ
- Calories shouldn't even be increased in first trimester. Daily calories should be increased by about 300Cals in 2nd trimester and 500Cals in 3rd Trimester.
- There may be food aversions or food cravings during pregnancy - this is totally normal.
- Try to stick with whole nutritious foods
- Supplements include: Folic Acid, Vitamin D, Iron and Omega 3 Fatty acids. But talk to your doctor or health are consultant before taking any of these
.
.
Something to be very aware of during pregnancy is labelling. Some food labels distinctly say 'not suitable for pregnancy' so just be aware ğŸ’¯

ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥Fun fact ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
.
.
I didn't eat fruit or vegetables until I went to college (studying to be a nutritionistğŸ™ˆ). And at that it was VERY limited. Maybe the odd orange and carrots with dinner. ğŸ™ˆ @len_tils was my saviour when I moved to Sheffield with her. She had me eating food I would never ever eat ğŸ˜‚Even if I did make her chop vegetables into the tiniest pieces ğŸ˜‚ My point is I changed a habit. Not only did I change it, I absolutely did a 360 ğŸ¤— (I don't do things by halves ğŸ˜)
.
.
When people come to me with: I don't eat this or I don't like that or I don't eat any vegetables etc. I see that as a choice. Its absolutely fine if you are one of these people and choose to 'be picky'. No one is expected to like everything ğŸ˜‚ I still cannot eat Cauliflower and I'm not a fan of asparagus but I am much more open to trying new things. And not once, because that is not enough. They say if you still cannot stand something after the 3rd try, there's a good chance you like it. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥Another fun fact ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥ğŸ’¥
I only started eating salads about 4 years ago. After years of telling myself I don't like iceberg lettuce and tomatoes (still don't) I realised that's not the only salad that exists ğŸ˜‘ğŸ˜³ If you think you don't like salad, don't make it with items you don't like ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜œ I base most of mine on rocket or spinach, add as much colour Usually Beetroot, carrot, Cucumber, sun-dried tomato, a cheese and finish it with fruit ğŸ˜ I love fruit in salad. And salads shouldn't just be a summer thingğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«Add a warm meat, fish or meat alternative, add a warm grain like cous cous, quinoa or pasta and voila â˜‘ï¸â˜‘ï¸â˜‘ï¸
.
.
Stop holding yourself back from the healthiest version of you ğŸ¤—

#fitfood #nutriton #nutritionist #fitlifestyle #fitliving #fitfam #fitaustralia #irishfitfam

What defines health? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Let me tell you what I think it is...
.
.
âŒHealth is not a low body fat
âŒHealth is not training excessively
âŒHealth is not clean eating
âŒHealth is not being mindful
âŒHealth is not sleeping 8 hours a day
âŒHealth is not 1 thing
.
.
Health is different to everyone. Health has a physical aspect but it has a huge mental aspect too. Obsessing about calories is not healthy, YOLOing isn't either. A measure on a scales is certainly not a definition of health. Eating whole nutritious foods is amazing but if you are constantly thinking about all the foods 'you can't have', that's not healthy. Sleeping 8 hours a day but stressing for the other 16 is not healthy. And training is important but if it's consuming you, affecting relationships, affecting your physical or mental health that obviously is not healthy.
.
.
I want to help people. I want to help them develop a healthy relationship with food and exercise. I want to help them stop being so hard on themselves and celebrate little victories. I want to cut this idea that exercise is just a way to burn calories. I want people to stop obsessing over calories. I want to help â¤ï¸ if you want my help. Pm me.

#happiness #goodrelationships #healthyrelationships #behappy #behealthy #fitlifestyle #fitliving #fitaustralia

What is my main aim of coaching clients? ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
âŒ It's not weight loss âŒ It's not getting stronger
âŒ It's not getting fitter
âŒ It's not even improving your body shape.
.
.
â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸â¬†ï¸
All of the above are by products.
My main aim is to find a lifestyle that is healthy and sustainable. Healthy doesn't always mean 'eating healthy foods' sometimes showing people they can have 'treats' actually makes people healthier. I deal with all my clients individually and help them create a healthy relationship with food and exercise.
.
.
I would say at least 90% of my clients have disordered eating in some form. Some know it, some don't. I have had it. And I've found a light at the end of a tunnel. So this is my main aim. Yes, I give nutrition plans. Yes, I provide training plans. But my programmes are more than that.
.
.

caption:
I am so excited to finally become an actual Crossfit member in Australia ğŸ™ˆ

I started Crossfit about a year ago but due to Inter County football I could never give it full commitment. In season (January - October) I was probably only doing it once or twice a week. As soon as Championship started I actually had to give it up as training intensity was just too high and I'm no spring chicken anymoreğŸ˜‚
In season I competed in 2 competitions, which I took podium at bothğŸ¥‡ğŸ¥‰
As soon as football was finished I had time to give it my full commitment. I did my first Open which was the biggest learning experienceğŸ™ And I did my first competition with trainingğŸ†

Why Crossfit?
I have been training consistently at a high level for at least 14 years. I have played Intercounty football since I was 12 and anyone that knows me as a player, knows my (probably only) strength is my engine. So I have a very good capacity. I have also been consistently weight training for 5 years so my strength is decent too. I have a huge competitive nature so pushing myself outside my comfort zone is something that I thoroughly enjoy. Crossfit seemed like a perfect match and so far it's ticking all the right boxesâ˜‘ï¸â˜‘ï¸â˜‘ï¸ I also absolutely love the incredible sense of achievement and community spirit within it ğŸ˜Š

Do I recommend Crossfit to everyone?
Like with any high intensity sport, injuries happen. Up until now, I have trained for Crossfit alone. Something I would not recommend to people. I am a fully Qualified trainer (not crossfit coach) but I'm competent in in my exercise execution. If you are a beginner, I would recommend getting a baseline before starting crossfit. And get a good trainer. Unfortunately, Crossfit gets a bad rap for under Qualified coaches but this is actually minimal. I have yet to come across a bad one, but they exist (and not just in Crossfit may I add, i have seen worse in the GAA). To answer the above question, no I do not Recommend RX Crossfit to everyone. But that doesn't mean that everyone cannot enjoy it to a certain level. Most gyms do some sort of cross trainingğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ I do not endorse Crossfit. I do not recommend it for everyone. But right now, I'm loving it â¤ï¸ğŸ™

caption:
Tips on travelling and how to maintain a  good lifestyle while away:
.
.
1. Don't drink your calories.
 If you are going to go on the lash every day chances are you will gain weight ğŸ˜’ Also, if you're adding a lot of extra calories through drinks (even healthy ones) you may put on weight. Let's take a smoothie for breakfast with breakfast, a milkshake with lunch, sipping on Fanta throughout the day and 2 cocktails at night. That will probably clock up an extra 500-1000 cals a day. ğŸ™Š Stick to water. Or a coke zero is an absolute life saver if you're craving a little sweetness ğŸ™
.
.
2. You don't need to be in the gym to stay active.
 Did you know your NEAT contributes more to your metabolic rate than Purposeful exercise? I may not be training much but I'm getting between 15-30k steps every day. So get swimming, walking, hiking or kayaking. If you want to laze by the pool, that's fine but don't be suprised if your body feels tired and sluggish ğŸ˜¬
.
.
3. Get at least one decent meal in.
 I try to opt for eggs and fruit for breakfast. This way I can leave a little lenancy for dinner ğŸ˜œ You should enjoy yourself at the end of the day but you want to feel good at the same time. Try opt to snack on fruit and nuts instead of ice cream and crisps the whole time ğŸ™Š
.
.
4. I'm weird about salads in developing countries. The water is so dirty over here so if that's what they use to clean it, I try to veer away. I do get veggies cooked, normally in a curry or stir fry ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
5. That leads me onto my next point. Be weary of meat. I tend to go pescatarian when away as the meat quality just isn't  the same ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
6. A few things to have handy: Bug Spray, tissues, plasters, iodine, after sun, antibacterial gel, wipes and a fan ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚
.
.
7. Invest in a Go Pro. They are worth it.
.
.
Travel is amazing and should be enjoyed but if you want to stay comfortable and not self conscious maybe points 1-3 may help. 4 to 7 are just some of my tips and to be honest I probably have a million more I've forgotten ğŸ™Š
.
.

New year, New me ğŸ™Œ
.
.
Each year since my Dad died I have vowed to put myself first. I'm not great at it tbh. I let work come first, football, looking after others and my needs and wants came after all those things ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
If my friends or family, hear the word organised they will probably think of me. I organise my organisation ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚ So when I decided to leave my job and head to the other side of the world at (almost) 29, I'd say people couldn't believe it ğŸ™ˆ But it's something I had to do. â¤ï¸
.
.
I genuinely thought I'd be married and have a child before 30. I thought I'd have my career sorted. But dya know what... I couldn't be happier. I am currently travelling with the love of my life @o_boyce and with no job organised we hope to start up a new adventure in Sydney.
.
.
It's OK to be almost 30 and not have a certain plan. It's OK to not have a mortgage. It's OK to be single. It's OK to not have a career. .
.
Life is what you make it. You are a product of your environment. I believe good things are coming my way so here's to a positive outlook on 2020â¤ï¸ğŸ™Œ I hope you all have the same YOLO attitude ğŸ™‹
.
.

caption:
As you can see from my feed I have began to love Crossfit ğŸ’‹
.
.
I didn't always love it and actually I was a huge skeptic. My friends know this as some of them have questioned me on it ğŸ¤” But my views and opinions on so many things over the years have changed. I also believed that a restrictive 'clean' diet was the healthiest diet there could be, forgetting the impact that restriction has on your mental health ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
I have made so many mistakes over the years I've been in the health and fitness industry. I've called foods 'good' and 'bad', and I've shunned certain exercise routines. But from experience comes knowledge and wisdom. ğŸ™ And I am a lot more open minded to things now ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
I don't think Crossfit is for everyone. It's a seriously stringent training regime which requires a huge level of mobility, strength and conditioning. Even at a regressed level, it can be overwhelming and injury levels can be high due to poor training technique or poor coaching (this is obviously not all coaches). But I also don't think everyone should be running. Poor running technique can contribute to any number of problems with joints, ligaments, tendons or muscle strains.
.
.
I am a firm believer in anyone starting out on a fitness journey, to look around. Find what works for you. There's not a one size fits all. I would normally say to get a coach to steer you in the right direction and then you'll find a lifestyle you can enjoy â¤ï¸ Because exercise should not be a punishment ğŸ™

I actually love Cardio ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸(except rowingit's the devil's exercise ğŸ˜‚) .
.
Coming from a football background, cardio was my first love fitness wise ğŸ‘ŒI'm not gonna lie, I love that breathlessness feeling. I feel it always shows me I've pushed myself ğŸ˜‰ And being honest, running is the highest my heart rate goes to (even when I don't think it and some of the other sessions I do feel way worse ğŸ™ˆ)
And I'm one of the very few Assault Bike fans.
. .
But let me tell you something, if you think you're going to change your body shape by doing cardio alone. You're so wrong ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
Sweat should not be a determinant of a 'good session'. Again, I love the feeling of a good sweaty session. But quite often my weights sessions barely work a pore, does this mean they are not as beneficial? ABSOLUTELY NOT!!! Resistance training is and should be priority. No matter what your goals?
ğŸ‘‰ Weight loss, gain or maintenence (along with calorie manipulation)
ğŸ‘‰ Reduce injury risk
ğŸ‘‰ Stronger bones, joints, ligaments, tendons
ğŸ‘‰ General strength and fitness
.
.
If you have not already realised how important resistance training is, make it a goal and priority for 2020 ğŸ’ª

caption:
You're telling me, you can actually enjoy Christmas? ğŸ˜³ğŸ˜³ğŸ˜³
.
.
Every other year I've given tips on 'how to not lose all your hard work over Christmas'. This year I'm taking a different approach.
.
.
I plan to train less over Christmas. Before, I would panic about this. Oh but 'Will I lose all my strength?'. 'What about all the chocolate I've eaten'ğŸ˜­ I now have a good relationship with exercise. I don't plan on sitting on my arse all Christmas but my normal 6 day training week will probably reduce to 3. Why? To facilitate for spending time with friends and family â¤ï¸ This Christmas is even more important than others that I spend valuable time with friends and family as I'm moving in 2.5 weeks ğŸ˜± But training is a part of my lifestyle so I won't be going cold turkey on it (Christmas pun or whatğŸ¤ª)
.
.
As always I will enjoy myself. But as usual, good nutritious food makes me feel best so I will stick mostly to what I know and enjoy the treats too âœŒï¸ I won't take the p#*s. ğŸ·ğŸš«
.
.
Lastly and most importantly, when the 5th of January rocks up and I'm about to get into a bikini I will not be hard on myself. I will cherish the weeks over Christmas. .

caption:
Travelling Workout ğŸ–ï¸ğŸŒ
.
.
A lot of you had asked will I be training on holidays ğŸ¤” The plan is to definitely keep up a minimum level of training while travelling while including a lot of hiking and extra steps ğŸ‘£ğŸ‘£ğŸ‘£
.
.
I'm not gonna lie, a good gym is what motivates me ğŸ’ª I don't have much interest in a Hiit Bodyweight session ğŸ™ˆ But if there is no option for a good gym in some of the places I am here are some of the exercises I will keep up ğŸ¤
.
.
1. Skipping - This is definitely one I will be keeping up. Since I bought my new rope I'm going to use this as an opportunity to improve my DUs
2. Squats - BW air Squats are pretty easy for me so I've progressed them to pulse Squats here
3. Lunges - Again, normal Lunges are pretty regressed for me so I've added an OH Walking Lunge option
4. Push Ups - Still one of the hardest exercises to perfect
5. Core Work - Being honest I probably won't do these as I hate doing isolated core work but I've added it in for any of you thinking about home workouts ğŸ˜œ
.
.
I will probably add Burpees as I love a good Burpee but not everyone can or should do them so I haven't added them. Hope this helps some of you ğŸ˜ I hope to do most of my training in gyms but this is an option for when there are no gyms to avail of ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ #fullbodyworkout #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #exercise #fitfam #irishfitfam

It's easy to assume I've always been confident ğŸ¤”
.
.
I've always been the loudest in the room
.
I've never been afraid to show a little skin
.
Attention seeker was my middle name
.
.
Delve a little deeper and you'd have seen a very vulnerable girl, terrified to show how insecure she truely was ğŸ˜¢
I was the girl who couldn't be seen without make up. The girl who was more than uncomfortable in her own skin ğŸ˜© I conformed to norms & standards that I thought I 'had to'. I was being someone I wasn't. And I'm well aware this is a vast majority of women unfortunately ğŸ˜­
.
.
But I'm at a stage in my life where I am now so happy and confident in myself â¤ï¸
A girl who once thought I had to have life sorted by 30 is off to Austrailia next year.âœˆï¸ A girl who was obsessed with having a 'perfect body' is thriving in her strong body ğŸ’ª Instead of designer handbags and expensive jewellery, I'm more interested in what tattoo I'm going to get next ğŸ˜‚ And did I mention I got a nose piercing at 28 ğŸ˜œ
.
.
So don't make assumptions. Yes I'm at a place in my life where I'm happy, but I haven't always been there. It can take a long time. It takes a lot of self care. But it's worth it. And don't be afraid to be who you are ğŸ’•

#confidence #confident #travel #movingaway #getmesomesun #3weekstoday #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
I've always been very open minded. I pride myself on it actually. I've alway been a pro choice kinda girl in all aspects of life (not just health and fitness related). You'll never hear me boast about one type of diet or slate any either. You won't hear me downgrade any form of exercise, although I do openly talk about the huge benefits of resistance training ğŸ’ª I'll never tell any of my client's 'You have to do this type of exercise' or 'you cannot eat this for weight loss'. So you see I'm very open minded. If someone who loves yoga comes to me, I'm not going to force them to lift weights. And if someone who is vegan comes to me, I would not force them to eat animal products. My problem with any of these things lies in the misinformation. .
.
Did you know that vegan fast food production has sky rocketed in recent years? ğŸ¤” Similarly, a few years ago, gluten free products were a huge trend? And before that, sugar free was the hype? This I have a problem with.
.
.
Veganism is a lifestyle choice. I have huge respect for anyone's lifestyle choices, whether they conform to my own is irrelevant. What actually annoys me is actual vegans are getting a terrible name due to all these people jumping on the bandwagon, thinking veganism is the healthiest lifestyle going. People are going into this lifestyle, uneducated and naive. ğŸ˜’ It was the same a few years ago when gluten free was the buzzword. Did you know you can have a totally adequate, balanced, healthy diet without adding one gluten free product? And thats for ACTUAL coeliacs out there, because they are the ONLY people that need to be eating gluten free toast ğŸ˜‚
.
.
What my very long winded post is trying to say is stop jumping on bandwagons. If you are and always have been vegan, that's fine. Continue with your choices. If you are coeliac, continue with your gluten free bread ğŸ™ˆ For the rest of you, stop following trends by the latest celebrity diet. But let me tell you this. One is much more important than the other. Because without one, we would be seriously limited ğŸ¤”
.
.
Health should be EVERYONES number 1 priority. Health is different to everyone. It's not necessarily eating clean or training. But it involves a physical and mental component. Without good health, we restrict ourselves in so many ways. It should be a priority over every single other goal/task in your life â¤ï¸
.
.
For me prioritising my health involves:
ğŸ™ Eating a diet with wholesome, nutritious food but not depriving myself if I want some chocolate
ğŸ™ Exercising daily - because I love my body, not hate it
ğŸ™ Social interactions - I thrive on talking to people. Always have. My job helps me with this. If I'm not working, I'm meeting friends and family
ğŸ™ Organisation - sounds silly but not being organised would spark anxiety problems. I don't want that therefore, I am highly organised
ğŸ™ Sleep - no explanation needed
ğŸ™ Being selfish from time to time - I've always been selfless. I've always put everyone else first. These days I have a healthy balance â¤ï¸
ğŸ™ Reading - whether it's light reading or learning
.
.
If you are not prioritising your health you need to. You need to start doing things for yourself. You need to start looking after your body because believe me, we won't be here forever ğŸ˜”

caption:
The weekend is almost over... Are you really trying to achieve your goals or are you just kidding yourself ğŸ˜¬ğŸ¤”
.
.
If you are like my clients and making a conscious effort everyday to create new, better habits. Then well done ğŸ‘ğŸ‘ğŸ‘
.
.
It's not about perfection. It's about consistency. It's about 'trying'. If a client says to me, 'Amanda I had a meal out for my sister' s birthday, I stuck to a decent dinner but I did have dessert'ğŸ˜¬. I count this as a win. Before, this client would have a starter, main and dessert without even a thought about the nutrition content of the food. Now, they are making a conscious decision to have a healthier dinner but still enjoy dessert. They didn't overdo it by having 3 courses. It's about progress, not perfection ğŸ‘ğŸ‘ğŸ‘
.
.
On the other hand, if someone told me, they went out of their way to order a takeaway 'because they had a bad week at work'. I'd be a little less impressed ğŸ¤ I try to help my clients with emotional eating. And not using food as a coping mechanism. Again, it's about progress. If this happened once, mistakes happen. If it was a continuous cycle, I would express my disappointment. ğŸ˜
.
.
I said last week I was going to try and 'treat myself' less frequently. Which to be fair, I actually did. But then I visited family over the weekend and they were all about treating me ğŸ˜‚ I enjoyed myself but I didn't take the absolute piss either ğŸ˜’ My goals are not aesthetic based and are more based on energy and performance levels so I want to keep my diet as nutritious as possible as that's the food that makes me feel the best ğŸ’ª
.
.
If you want to change, I mean really WANT to change, make small changes. If you don't, that's fine too, but stop wasting your time, your money and your energy ğŸ™„
.
.

â“â“â“Did you know that Whey is a by product of cheese production? Yes you heard right. Its a simple dairy bi product that is dried and may have lactose or fats removed during production ğŸ™ˆâ“â“â“
.
.
So if you are on the bandwagon of thinking whey protein has some sort of steroid included or has some sort of extra powers, I'm afraid your both wrong.
.
.
It's not needed in everyone's diets. But if you are someone who:
ğŸ‘‰ Does not get enough protein in their diet its a good source of protein and is convenient and easily absorbed.
ğŸ‘‰ Trains a lot and finds it hard to get in the amount of protein you need. It's a great addition. Remember it is a supplement do that's exactly what it should do. Supplement the diet.
.
.
ğŸš« It will not make you bulky
ğŸš« It is not only for athletes
ğŸš« It is not only required after the gym
.
.
I'm not going to compare it nutritionally to milk. But if you're a person who would drink a glass of milk, but wouldn't drink a protein shake, maybe think twice ğŸ¤”

I actually understand how hard it is to reduce or eliminate foods we all enjoy like chocolate ğŸ¤¤ Or Crisps, maybe even Bread or Takeaways. These foods usually require a lot of make you full (satiation). But there does come a point where you will feel full. Liquid calories however will never leave you feeling sated. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
1. Liquid calories include juices we consider 'just a drink', they may be a healthier option but they contain calories too. This is a very easy way to cut calories by eliminating these juices and replacing with water.
.
.
2. Fizzy drinks. This one still baffles me. I'm not a fizzy drink fan but the odd time I get a little craving ğŸ˜œ But there are 'zero' options in EVERY drink these days ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸Why would you even consider the sugar alternative!? ğŸ˜
.
.
3. Alcohol contains calories. Quite often a lot of them. Drinking is fine. But be aware it doesn't go unaccounted for. But 'banking calories' for drinking can have dangerous consequences. Firstly, drunkoxeria is a very real thing. People starving themselves the day of a drinking binge 'to save calories'. Can we please stop saying things are 'bad' and 'good'. Go out every so often. Drink a sensible amount. Be aware it's not calorie free. The end.
.
.
4. Hot drinks. Tis the season and all thatğŸ¥¶ Hot chocolates and festive coffees are a sure way to boost your daily calorie consumption without a second thought. And I can tell you those 400 cals will not leave you as full as a nice chicken salad would ğŸ¥—ğŸ˜ We all love a good hazelnut latte but let's just keep it as a treat, not a daily lunchtime special ğŸ˜œ You'll save yourself some cash too for Christmas ğŸ˜
.
.

So as we know we are made up of bone, ligaments, tendons, organs, muscle and fat. ğŸ™ˆ Yes we all have it. And we all need a certain amount, especially women.
.
Our optimal body composition is to have a lower body fat mass (in healthy proroption s 18 - 28% woman and 8 - 18% man) and a higher lean muscle mass. We also would like a good bone density with strong joints. Strong, healthy, functioning organs would really top it off ğŸ‘Œ
.

What if I told you with a good, balanced diet and some consistency you could achieve this ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜®

Let's talk portion size ğŸ½ï¸
.

Firstly, this is just a generic reference. It doesn't take into account body weight or goals but it's a good guide all the same ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Protein - palm size portion with every meal. Meat, fish, eggs, Yogurt, cottage cheese
.
Vegetables (not fruit, fruit is a cÃ¡rb) - fistful with every meal.
.
Carbs - cupped handful with most meals. Grains, peas, fruit, rice, pasta, bread etc
.
Fats - thumbful with most meals. Opt for healthy options like avocado, oils, nuts, nut butter
.
.
Portion size is often a problem.
Other ways to avoid over eating:
ğŸ½ï¸ Try reducing plate size.
ğŸ Avoid trigger foods. Contrary to popular belief bread does NOT make you fat. However, if you are having 6 slices of bread a day and you over eat it causing you to be in a calorie surplus you will gain weight ğŸ˜‘ If you feel there are foods like this in your diet that you cannot stop eating, I do recommend eliminating. At least for awhile until you can gain control back on them. It does tend to be carbohydrate dense foods like bread, and pasta. Personally, I keep these as a 'treat' rather than a dietary staple ğŸ‘Œ
.
.

Hands up if you love burpeesğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸
.

I often get asked some of the following:
âš¡ How many days a week SHOULD you train?
Answer: How many time a week CAN you train? There is absolutely no point committing to a 5 day programme if all you can fit in is 3/4. You're already setting yourself up for a fail. There is no Right amount of days to train but there is what's right for you
.
âš¡ Is rest not important?
Answer: Recovery is vital. Recovery is done through nutrition, hydration, sleep and reducing intensity/volume. Recovery does not necessarily mean sitting on your arse for the day ğŸ¤” I prefer an active recovery with some light movement. You don't need to be totally sedentary.
.
âš¡ Is Crossfit not dangerous?
Answer: If you have the capacity, you can increase the load. I'm a huge advocate of the sport but as with ALL sports of course there is a level of risk involved. The problem often lies in the person or trainer rather than the exercise prescription. If you have never done an Olympic lift before and try Snatch 50kg of course it's dangerous ğŸ™„ But I put the problem down to you more than the sport. It may be benificial for any newbies to either start off with some level if weight training or invest in a really good coach âœŒï¸
.
âš¡What exercise is Best?
Answer: The one you enjoy and can adhere to âœŒï¸ But if you want the most bang for your buck and are willing to try anything, it doesn't get more beneficial than resistance training ğŸ’ª
. âš¡How do you keep motivated all the time? You never stop!
Answer: This one is simple. I love itâ¤ï¸ I love training. I love fuelling my body right. I love that my body is capable of training so hard. We should be so grateful for all we CAN do ğŸ˜
.

caption:
Let me blow your mind ğŸ¤¯ğŸ¤¯ğŸ¤¯
.
.
Purposeful exercise is NOT enough. ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
What makes up the body's need for energy? (Aproximations) âš¡ 60% BMR - this rate is affected by genetics, environment, food consumption, overall activity etc
âš¡ 10% TEF - this is the energy we need to breakdown and absorb food. Certain foods like protein rich foods have a high thermic effect, therefore eating more of them results in higher TEF.
âš¡20% NEAT - This is the exercise we do involuntarily like walking, housework, gardening or playing with kids.
âš¡10% Purposeful Exercise
.
.
Let's say Sarah is trying to lose X kg. Sarah  is 87kg and has been highly inactive her whole life. Her diet is and always has been highly processed. She works a desk job and her family have 'always carried a few pounds'. So Sarah starts resistance training 4 times a week. But she is still sedentary outside of those 4 sessions. And she hasn't cleaned up her diet....what do you think will happen? Sarah will seriously struggle to lose weight ğŸ˜”
.
Eileen on the other hand is 67kg and back to the gym twice a week after having a baby. She trained 4 times a week up until having Thomas. She has always had a healthy lifestyle which she maintained while pregnant and breastfeeding. Her diet is protein rich with lots of fruit and vegetables and the odd treat ğŸ˜œ She plays with Thomas daily...
Will it be easier for Eileen even though she has less weight to lose?
Absolutely ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Purposeful exercise is great and should be part of a weekly routine. But it is only a very small piece of the puzzle. Don't forget what we put in our mouths has a huge impact on our BMR and burns energy through TEF. NEAT is often over looked and has more impact on TDEE than Purposeful exercise. It's a much larger picture than 'just going to the gym'. #tdee #neatup #tef #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #healthylifestyle #healthiswealth #irishfitfam

caption:
People often ask me what exercise is 'best for your bum', 'how do I get rid of love handles', or 'can you target my bingo wings'. Unfortunately, we cannot spot reduceğŸ™ˆ If it were that easy we'd all be walking around with 'perfect' bodies ğŸ˜œ
.
.
But if there was one exercise I would recommend it would be the Deadlift ğŸ™‚ It is a compound movement that really hits many muscle groups ğŸ’ª Unfortunately, it is often executed incorrectly and is almost always recommended by health professionals to 'stay away from' if they have injuries. Which is such a pity because if executed properly it can actually help strengthen muscle groups and reduce the incidence of injury ğŸ˜”
.
.
I have demonstrated 4 different types of Deadlifts. There are more. Some may have to adjust for lever length or injury etc. But the main take home points of a Deadlift.
â¡ï¸ Hip hinge. If you can master this movement. You have mastered a lot of the exercise and many other exercises. I recommend practising with a dowel until fully comfortable with this position.
â¡ï¸ 3 points of contact. If you were to put a dowl on your back it should touch your head, in between shoulder blades and glutes. If one is not in position, your position is not correct.
â¡ï¸ Slow and controlled movement. Make sure not to Jerk the weight.
Point to note. Remember, we have muscles in our lower back so if you have a little bit of pain following Deadlifts it may often be DOMS. Don't automatically think the worst. caption:
Let's talk disordered eating âš ï¸âš ï¸âš ï¸
.
.
I've always said I've never had an eating disorder e.g anoxeria, bulimia. But that doesn't mean I've never had disordered eating. An eating disorder sometimes doesn't capture the full range of complexity of people's eating experiences ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
Unfortunately, most people in their lifetime will have some sort of disordered eating. Even those that think they don't ğŸ˜” With the society we live in these days, this has become even more prevalent. The strive for perfection in everything we do has become extreme. The pressure to look a certain way. It's no wonder everyone has a form of disordered eating ğŸ˜”
.
.
So what kind of behaviours fall into the Disordered Eating (DE) category:
ğŸ‘‰ Restriction and tight control of food
ğŸ‘‰ Routines and rules are food (certain foods are 'BAD' or when someone should eat)
ğŸ‘‰ Bingeing
ğŸ‘‰ Compensation for binging - purging, over exercise, fasting
ğŸ‘‰Anxiety and Avoidance - eating out, social events etc
ğŸ‘‰ Orthorexia - obsession with healthy eating
ğŸ‘‰ Body Dysmorphia - distorted body image
.
.
Sadly, I can safely say in my lifetime I have experienced ALL of the aboveğŸ˜” And I'm sure I'm not alone.
.
.
I will not say I'm 110% body confident or happy all the time but thankfully I am rid of my disordered eating. It's not easy. It takes a lot of self acceptance. It takes talking - be that to a friend, family member, counsellor. It takes accepting there is an underlying issue and this behaviour is as a result of that. Its not easy but it can be done ğŸ’•
.
.
Let's try and be kind to ourselves, each other and our bodies ğŸ™

#disorderedeating #talktosomeone #itsoknottobeok #loveyourself #loveyourbody #healthiswealth #health #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

I gave up a life long hobby a couple of years ago which was main source of excerise. I have hated any other excerise since then. I hate the gym and i was  dragged by my sister to engage in any type of activity over the  last few months . Since the programme, i'm loving excerise.  I look forward to going for my run in the fresh air and love the home work outs. My energy levels have increased two fold and im ready and waiting for  my sister to come get me now . My last goal was to lose weight as im  getting married next year. In the 8 weeks i have lost over a stone and have really noticed it my clothes.

Protein is a vital part of every diet no matter what your goals. ğŸ’¯

I am a huge fan of plant based diets. I am not vegetarian but I try to get a large amount of plants into my diet. It was often thought that vegetarians don't get enough protein in their diet. Vegetarians can get a sufficient amount of protein in their diet with good meal planning and preparation. But eliminating any part of your diet can come with trade offs so it is important there is a conscious effort to add protein to all meals. There is also risk of deficiencies such as iron and Vitamin B12 so air on the side of cautionâš ï¸âš ï¸âš ï¸
.

Sometimes I think people (myself included) give all this 'great' information on macronutrients and some people don't even know what a 'carb' source is ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
This is a great diagram to show what foods contain what. Some foods are primarily single nutrient based while others contain more than one.
.
.
I use this a lot when I talk about carb or calorie cycling. I also use it in relation to trying to keep treat meals within your goals.
E.G If going out for a meal but weight loss is a goal and you don't want to absolutely ruin all progress. I would recommend to a client stick to either a protein/fat OR protein/cÃ¡rb meal. Yes, it comes down to overall calories but it's much easier to overeat on a protein/fat/carb meal like a lasagne and chips than a steak and veg or a stir fry with rice ğŸ¤”
.
.
Hope this helps clear up some things for people ğŸ˜ƒ
.

caption:
I had a little giggle with one of my friends the other day about how different my page has become since we first met which was about 5 years ago (when I first started this) She had actually been following me and we ended up working together and it blossomed after that. Cute I know â¤ï¸
.
.
I have learned so much in that 5 years. I have educated myself so much more. I have made mistakes which I've learned from. I tried some silly things and failed. But also tried some crazy things and succeeded ğŸ™Œ My page is a reflection of what I do, it always has been. It was started to keep me accountable ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜‚ If I didn't have thousands of bloody posts I'd definitely be looking back cringing ğŸ˜‚ğŸ™ˆ As you get older, you do learn, you do get some Sense, you do find yourself. ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
5 years ago the girl writing posts on this page was: Insecure, searching for abs, weaker - physically & mentally and enjoying exercise but also punishing herself for a binge the odd time
.
.
Now, this girl is: Confident, enjoys every time she exercises (no punishment workouts required), body composition is not my goal (although my body is in great shape, it is as a result of training hard, it's not my priority, its as a by product) and I am so proud of what my body is capable of â¤ï¸
.
.
Love your body. Love what your body is capable of. Stop searching for aesthetic goals. Start focusing on performance. Embrace everything your body CAN do. Nourish your body. You're going to be in it your whole life, you might aswell start looking after it ğŸ™ŒğŸ™ŒğŸ™Œ

caption:
Food Prep ğŸ²ğŸ½ï¸
.
.
Fail to prepare, prepare to fail â˜¢ï¸â˜¢ï¸â˜¢ï¸
.
.
We all have the same 24 hours in the day. Yes, it's very easy to be 'too busy' to prepare and cook food. A takeaway or a deli are very appealing after a long day of work. But it comes down to habit. If you form a habit, this becomes a lot easier.
If you keep putting it on the back burner it becomes harder. ğŸ™„
.
.
My top tips to Food Prep:
- Do a weekly food shop - Having good foods in the house make it easier. If you have no food in your fridge it's much easier to pick up convenience crap. Do a full shop at the start of the week and you're off to a great startğŸ˜‰ The above ingredients are the basis of my food shop every week ğŸ“ƒ
.
- Pick a day. Take an hour and get prepping. I do a Sunday evening. I put a batch of chicken, fish and turkey burgers in the oven to last me 3 days. While they are cooking, I boil broccoli and make up a salad. I chop up my fruit and portion out my Greek yogurt. I put my overnight oats in the fridge for the next day. It take me and hour to get the bulk of my food ready for 3 days. I use microwaveable rice to save time too. I save money because I rarely eat out and make all my own lunches. I do the same on a Wednesday evening. Tupperware is your new best friend. .
- Find food you like and stick with it. It's actually very simple. People overcomplicate it. It's unnecessary.
.
- If you do have to eat out or buy lunch there are LOADS of healthy options. Stop saying there's none. Go to Aldi, buy a bag of spinach, hot smoked salmon and a pot of cous cous (portion out). That's 2 lunches. Stop using excuses
.
- Get into a routine. I am in such a routine now that even when I go off course like have a few drinks at the weekend, I am back to Tupperware on Monday. Its ALL ABOUT HABITS ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Let me know some of your food prep ideas ğŸ¤” Mine are pretty monotonous. It's really just about forming a habit and sticking to it ğŸ‘Œ

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #foodprep #fitlifestyle #fitliving #healthylifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Searching for motivation ğŸ”ğŸ”ğŸ”
.
.
Most people think motivation should come naturally and then you'll form a habit. When in fact it's the other way around. Motivation is a result of habits formed. You don't just wake up one day and say that's it, I'm gonna be motivated for good ğŸ˜ It just doesn't happen like that. Your habits create motivation. People always ask me how am I so motivated all the time ğŸ¤”
.
.
Firstly, know that I am not motivated all the time. No one is. But training regularly and eating healthy are both habits to me. I don't go through periods of eating well and exercising. I do it regularly and consistently. How are some people so 'motivated' to go out every weekend? Habit..What about people who play football every weekend? Habit (they also have responsibility to a coach and a team) which brings me onto my next point.
.
.
I advise getting a coach. Someone who holds you accountable. It's not always easy at the start. It can take a long time to form a habit. Having a coach there, helps you from quitting when you want to(and there will be times you want to)
.
.
Stop focusing on the end goal and start enjoying the ride ğŸš² This one I can't emphasise enough. Today was my first day off training in 13 days. I really really wanted to train (I love training) but it was more important to get a day out with my family. It should add to your life, not take away from it. Sometimes it will be priority, sometimes it won't but you need to incorporate it into your lifestyle and make time for it. âœŒï¸
.
.
Remember, you are in control. You decide what you can and can't do. Goals are important. But stop focusing so much on an end point and enjoy the journey ğŸ‘ŒOh and find something you enjoy, that is vital. If you don't enjoy it, you won't sustain it ğŸ˜”ğŸ˜– #motivation #youareincontrol #takecontrol #goals #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitness #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

Other options include: Fruit, Veg with hummus, boiled eggs, protein shakes, protein bars. There is a huge variety. If you like the odd treat opt for crisps or sweets with less than 100 Cals ğŸ˜œ

Weights can make you bulky ğŸ˜¬ğŸ˜¬ğŸ˜¬
.
.
OK, now I've got your attention. Let me explain to you ğŸ˜
.
.
2014 This was me: 9 stone of skin and bone, Active my whole life with a poor diet and a little pot belly ğŸ¤ğŸ˜‚ I had no upper body strength. I could not lift more than a 7kg bar overhead. Please don't use 'not being able to do a pull up' as a measure of upper body strength, they are damn bloody hard ğŸ˜© And A lot of super strong people can't do them.
.
.
Fast forward 5 years later. I am 10.5 stone with a heck of a lot of that muscle and a little chub ğŸ˜‰ğŸ· I eat to fuel my body and I still have my protruding stomach but it's leaner ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‹
.
.
So why do I reckon I gained so much weight?
I genuinely think people look at me and think, ah she looked better before she started weight training. And that's fine. That's people's opinions and they are entitled to that. But I gained muscle. I added about 40kg to my overhead press and my legs and bum make up 3/4 of my weight I reckon ğŸ˜‚ But this doesn't just happen overnight and probably won't happen to many people. I train very regularly and consistently usually 5/6 times a week, sometimes twice a day. That sheer volume will of course increase muscle mass. And I eat to maintain.
.
.
If you train like me, and depending on your size and frame, there is a possibility you will gain weight. Your size 8 pants may jump to a size 10 ğŸ˜³ğŸ˜‚ But chances are you don't train like me and if you did, you wouldn't be caring about a little weight gain ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
. .
I can promise doing 3 45 min weight sessions a week will NOT make you 'bulky'. It will however:
â˜‘ï¸ Help you drop body fat
â˜‘ï¸ Improve your overall body composition, â˜‘ï¸ Make you stronger,
â˜‘ï¸ Improve bone Density
â˜‘ï¸ Strengthen joints, tendons and ligaments
â˜‘ï¸ Make you happier and healthier

This is probably one of my most honest posts I've EVER wrote. And that's saying something ğŸ™ˆBecause I'm pretty much an open book ğŸ“™ Some of you might agree with me. Most of you won't. It's an opinion that is all ğŸ˜‡
.
.
I lost my love of football about 3 years ago ğŸ’”ğŸ’”ğŸ’”
.
.
When I first started, skill was priority. Which I had none of ğŸ˜‚ But I still had the craic. It was so much fun. Even though I never got a game, the sidelines were hopping when I was around ğŸ¶ğŸ¶ğŸ¶
Between the ages of 18 and 25, fitness was priority ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸Finally my lucky break ğŸ™Œ I may not be able to kick a ball, but I was fit ğŸ™‹ğŸ’ª I enjoyed football so much during these years â¤ï¸ And thankfully, they were my best years performance wise and I had a few medals to show for it too ğŸ…ğŸ…ğŸ…
.
.
But the last 3 years the game has changed. Or maybe it was just my mentality. I had sacrificed so much for so long, maybe I was just sick of doing that ğŸ¤” Or maybe I just don't have the same winning mentality others have. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ I cannot do 'whatever it takes' to win. Its just not in me ğŸš« And as for sacrifice. It used to be a 2 week drinking ban which has now turned into: No holidays, no alcohol for months, no social life, strain on relationships/friendships.
.
.
So why do you still do it?
The girls â¤ï¸ The friends you make and the relationships you build make it all worthwhile. That being said I am done at intercounty level. I want to enjoy engagements, weddings, and 30ths. I've had my time. I've lost a lot more than I've won, but I'm happy to call quits on my inter County career now. I don't get the same thrill as I used to. I'm slowing down and I'm enjoying other things more (club and crossfit) ğŸ’ª
.
.
Thanks to all the amazing people I've met along the way. All the people who've injured me. All the people I've injured. All part of the journey. .
.
See ya in the County Final xo

caption:
Is brown or basmati rice better? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Another nutrition answer that people don't like to hear but it depends ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜‚ (Anwser to almost every nutrition related questionğŸ˜‚). Well that's mainly because there are no 'good' or 'bad' foods and that question is too generic.
.
.
Picture 2 gives a nutritional break down of basmati rice while picture 3 is Brown rice's nutrition composition. Calories from basmati rice are slightly higher than brown rice while the protein content is also slightly higher. Brown rice is slightly higher in fat. Both have similar fibre content and both have a medium GI.
.
.
So really as you can see there is no dramatic nutritional difference between both grains. Basmati Rice may be slightly easier to digest than brown rice but that varies from person to person. I personally recommend variety. I also recommend convenience and what fits into your lifestyle (personally boiling brown rice for 30 mins doesn't fit into my lifestyle and a microwave basmati is much more convenient). I wouldn't fret over which one is 'better' but rather have both. Also, if you're picking either over chips you're doing something right ğŸ™ŒğŸ™ #nutrition #nutritionfacts #realnutrition #realfood #alwayslearning #healthyliving #healthylifestyle #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

What is iron and why is it important?
.
. 
Iron is an essential mineral needed by the body. Its primary function is to transport oxygen in the haemoglobin of red blood cells so the cells can produce energy. It also helps to remove carbon dioxide.
. 
How much iron do you need and where do we get it?
.
. 
Infants and toddlers need more iron than adults because their bodies are still growing. Women need more iron than men due to menstruation. Women require about 18mg/day while men need just 8mg/day. Iron is found in foods like: Shellfish, Liver, Red Meat, Spinach, Kale and Fortified Cereals. Haem Iron is the iron we get from animal sources and is most easily absorbed in the body. Non haem iron comes from plant sources and is not as easily absorbed so may require supplementation in vegetarians and vegans. Vitamin C is also essential for Iron absorption. Itâ€™s found in many fruits like Blackcurrants, strawberries, kiwis and oranges. Adding orange juice or fruit to an iron rich meal can help absorption.
.
. 
How do I know if Iâ€™m deficient in Iron?
.
. 
Common symptoms of Iron deficiency anaemia include: Fatigue, Paleness, Difficulty exercising, or have a fast heartbeat. It is important to never self diagnose. Too much iron is toxic and should not be taken unless recommended by a medical professional.
.
. 
Female athletes are at risk of iron deficiency anaemia due to menstruation and high exercise output. Make sure if you are showing any of the symptoms to get it checked out by a doctor and never self diagnose.

Curried Cous Cous ğŸ’‹
.
.
I'm a big fan of variety but a hectic schedule means it's often pretty hard to plan and make all the food I'd like to make ğŸ™ˆ I'm a fan of making my own food and try to avoid convenience options as best as possible, but its sometimes unavoidable ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
Cous cous is cheap and one of the quickest grains to make and can be super tasty if made well. Cous cous is lower in calories than most grains. But also lower in fibre. I have added chickpeas to the cous cous which lowers it's overall GI and increases it's fibre content ğŸ‘Œ I've also added vegetables, well because, health â¤ï¸ğŸ™
.
.
Ingredients:
- 200g Cous cous
- Curry powder
- Vegetable stock
- Paprika
- Chilli Powder
- Garlic
- Peppers
- Onions
-Chickpeas

Make up the cous cous with water (as instructed on pack). Add all spices. Wait 5 mins and add vegetables and chickpeas. *Mixture shouldn't be soggy

Enjoy ğŸ‘Œ

Is Sleep really that important?
Youâ€™ve heard people say itâ€™s important. That you need 8-10 hours per night. That without it you canâ€™t function. But is there any real evidence to support everyoneâ€™s advice.
HELL YES!!!!
1.	Performance:
Weâ€™ve all heard, â€˜Performance will sufferâ€™. Recent studies have suggested that poor sleep is related to slower reaction times, compromised physical performance, increased risk of illness and injury, lower mood and decreased ability to learn and remember new skills. Poor sleep has been reported in elite athletes in numerous sports such as swimming, rugby, cricket, ice hockey and track and field. This is thought to be related to training times, competition stress/anxiety, muscle soreness, caffeine use, technology and travel. We found almost half (47.8 per cent) of GAA players monitored in a current study were poor sleepers, and those who were poor sleepers had significantly lower general health, increased stress and lower mood. 
Recent studies have found that: In a study of sleep interventions on athletes, sleep extension proved most beneficial to athletes. (1) Bonnar et al 2018. Another study claimed that increased sleep time improved sustained contraction time to exhaustions (2) Arnal et al. Meanwhile,  Inadequate sleep impairs maximal muscle strength in compound movements when performed without specific interventions designed to increase motivation. (3) Knowles et al

2.	Weight management
Short sleep duration and other aspects of poor sleep habits are growing in prevalence in modern society in both children and adults. A growing literature has established that short sleep duration and other dimensions of poor sleep are associated with obesity and appear to predict obesity risk and rate of weight gain longitudinally. Small experimental studies suggest poor sleep may impact dietary intake particularly hedonic eating. (4)  Ogilvie et al

3.	General Health 
A recent study showed that insufficient sleep and sleep disorders are highly prevalent and are associated with significant morbidity and mortality. Primary outcomes of insufficient sleep and/or sleep disorders are weight gain and obesity. Continued in comments

Do you really want to be lean? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Body Fat Percentage Norms
>32% Overweight/Obese
25-31% Normal
21-24% Fit
13-20% Athlete
10-12% Essential
.
. 
So apart from those genetically gifted people, being lean/athletic and remaining lean requires effort. Effort that a lot of people aren't willing to give. Time people aren't willing to put into it. And sacrifices people aren't willing to give up ğŸ™ˆ I see it all the time. People with unrealistic goals. ğŸ˜¬
.
.
I (am not this lean right now) and a lot of GAA players are lean year round. Why?
Training 5-6 times a week, healthy eating to fuel our bodies and adequate recovery. We also have to give up on a lot of social occasions and probably drink much less than peers. It's a consistent process and has been for years.
.
.
But what about when people become too obsessed with body fat?
ğŸ˜¬ğŸ˜¬ğŸ˜¬
- If your body fat is > 32% for a female, it is optimal for overall health to try and reduce this. But if your body fat is at 20% unless you are competing or need to make weight for sport, you don't need to be actively seeking to reduce this.
- Remember, females need more essential fat than men at about 12%. This is for our overall reproductive health. With low body fat, there is an increased risk in amenorrhoea (loss of period). This is due to the pituitary gland reducing production of hormones. This can have long term implications and can result in potential loss of reproductive function
- Other problems associated with a very low body fat can include: decreased bone mass density, problems with your heart, shrinkage of your organs, loss of muscle tissue, stomach problems and nervous system damage.
.
.
Please think of the long term implications of actively seeking a very low body fat. It may not affect you now if you are young, but down the road the health implications are daunting. Stop trying to look like people on Instagram (they don't even look like that) ğŸ˜’ğŸ˜’ğŸ˜’ #lowbodyfat #lean #isitworthit #health #healthimplications #healthylifestyle #healthy #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam
