caption:
How do you eat healthy when you are 'on the go' and always busy? ğŸ¤”
.
.
So firstly, this is a cop out for a lot of people. Some people genuinely don't know what busy means and they use this as an excuse ğŸ˜ğŸ˜ğŸ˜ I've seen it all. I've had people tell me they can't eat well because they are 'too busy'. Why I asked? I work 10-5 and don't get a break. OK so what about the hours before 10 and after 5 ğŸ¤”
I have seen the other end of the scale. I work with a lot of nurses who MAKE time. Even after their 12 hour night shifts. Even with children and a husband. So a lot of the time thÃ­s IS a choice. Personally, I have to prepare food and training gear up to 3 days in advance due to long days. .
.
But I have met others who it genuinely isn't. And eating on the road is the only option. If that is the case can you eat healthy?
âœ”ï¸ Of course. The range of food choices has become so much better. There are healthy options available most places if you are looking for them.
ğŸ‘‰ A lot of salad bowls are available in fridges. Greek yogurt is a great go to snack. Little pots of berries are often found along side them
ğŸ‘‰ Fruit is never far away in most shops
ğŸ‘‰ If you want something warm why not get soup and add chicken to it?
ğŸ‘‰ Pre packaged foods like rice and lentils are always available if you have a microwave at work
ğŸ‘‰ You can even get healthier options in fast food outlets. Wraps and Healthy Ciabattas are now available in most of them.
.
.
âŒ You don't need to go for that carvery dinner every day. That is a choice.
âŒ You can choose a healthier option in the deli, you just choose not to
âŒ Being busy is NO excuse to have curry chips for lunch
.
.
#healthyalternatives #healthylifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Why should women resistance train? ğŸ¤”
.
.
I asked this question a few weeks back and got a great response so I said I'd do a little post on it. So while yes I agree women can do anything men can do, that's not why I would be recommending to do it (a lot of your responses) ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜‚
.
.
Health benefits to resistance training
â˜‘ï¸ Increases bone density and strengthens joints - This is of particular importance as we get older. There is no age limit on resistance training. We should start young and continue it regularly throughout our lives â˜‘ï¸ Increases lean muscle mass - Optimal body composition. Studies suggest that a combination of resistance and cardiovascular training is more beneficial for weight loss than either in isolation
.
.
Other benefits to resistance training
âœ”ï¸ You get stronger ğŸ’ª
âœ”ï¸ Boosts body confidence ğŸ‘™
âœ”ï¸ Reduce body fat mass and increase muscle mass = Shape the body you want
.
.
Play Sport?
â–¶ï¸ Stronger on the pitch
â–¶ï¸ Reduce risk of injuries
â–¶ï¸ Can improve endurance
.
.
If you're still questioning why you should be doing it? Questions below ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ğŸ‘‡ #resistancetraining #strongwomen #fitliving #fitlifestyle
#strengthtraining #sport #fitfam #irishfitfam

Listen up, this one is important. You don't want to fall down on this one ğŸ˜œğŸ¤£ (I craic myself upğŸ˜†ğŸ™ˆ)
.
.
But honestly, it's the peak of championship, priority to every sports person out there should be performance ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª If your goal is aesthetics, you're in sport for the WRONG reason ğŸ™ˆğŸ¤”
.
.
So what does that all mean?
- Firstly, you need to be eating to fuel your performance. Large calorie deficits should be a thing of pre season, not mid season. (Now a slight calorie deficit may be OK, but I still would not be recommending it for clients). Food is so important. Stocking up on carbs, an abundance of protein and lots of healthy fats ğŸ‘Œ If you are lean this time of year, it should be as a result of lots of training, not lots of dieting.  I personally am sitting at about 22% Body Fat. That's probably more than my regular BF % but I am eating in maintenance and maybe even a little bit of a surplus just to be sure I am getting enough fuel ğŸ‘Œ This weekend I had 2 games. It's not the first time and it won't be the last. I've trained 6 times this week and it's so important to get the most out of your body on game day ğŸ‘Œ - Secondly, it goes back to my burnout post. You need to fuel âœ”ï¸ But you seriously need to recover. I'm starting to take up a pool session a week to aid with my recovery. I am in an ice bath almost every day and I see a chiropractor every  4-6 weeks. Now is not the time of year to be hitting PBs in the gym ğŸ˜¬ The gym shouldnt get shoved out the window but maintenance should be all you should be looking for right now ğŸ‘
.
.
Remember, performance is priority. Do everything you can to improve and progress that. Eat well and recover right ğŸ‘Œ That extra few pounds could be the difference between a good game and a great game ğŸ˜œğŸ’ª #health #aesthetics #performance #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

Exercise on your periodğŸ˜’ğŸ˜’ğŸ˜’
.
. 
People still seem to be afraid to talk about this topic ğŸ™ˆ It's such a natural thing which all us ladies have to deal with so I'm so glad someone asked me to talk on this topic ğŸ˜Š
.
.
Let's be honest none of us WANT to do it, especially if you are crippled with period pains ğŸ˜© And there's a lot of non sense out there telling us we 'shouldn't' do this that and the other ğŸ¤” So what is the truth?
.
.
Well firstly like with most things I talk about it is very individual dependent. If you have a low iron count or anaemia, this time of month is very difficult to exercise. You are an exception to the norm. But for most of us there's no need to cut out exercise. Sometimes we MAY just need to cut down especially if you have a heavy flow and are losing a lot of blood ğŸ˜”
.
.
Why should we exercise during our period?
âœ”ï¸ Decreases PMS symptoms
âœ”ï¸ Endorphins - our feel good factor
âœ”ï¸ Reduces period pains
âœ”ï¸ Enhances your mood ğŸ˜Š
.
.
What type of exercise should we do?
-As I said before, most of the time we can just keep up with our normal exercise routine but yoga and pilates can be quite beneficial.
- Did you know that during your period you're stronger? So low rep strength training can be benificial ğŸ’ª
.
.
Hope this helps ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª #periods #femaletraining #trainingonyourperiod #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Do you suffer from burnout? ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
Every year around this time of year, someone on your team is likely to suffer from burnout ğŸ˜” A recent survey done with intercounty minors showed that 62% of underage players played while carrying injuries and 42% experienced chronic fatigue ğŸ˜³
.
.
The GAA calendar year is long. For some of us it doesn't stop. You need to know how to adapt and tailor training to different cycles during the year. If you're lucky enough to have a great coach, they will be able to do this for you, if not, you need to seek help. The same level of training cannot be continued year long. Everybody needs periods of Deload especially athletes ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
I train year long. I don't take long breaks. And I know my body craves and needs it. I try to Deload but I'm not the best at listening to my own advice. Until this year ğŸ’¡ Other people would think I'm mad taking a rest period before championship starts but thats exactly what my body needed â¤ï¸ I normally train 5/6 times a week but with reducing my training by 1 or 2 days a week for June, my body thanked me and my energy levels are exactly where they need to be this time of year ğŸ˜Š I have also had to step away from my beloved Crossfit the weeks of championship games ğŸ˜­ As football is priority at the moment. But for once I'm listening to my body and performance is the main goal ğŸ‘Œ Maybe you should too? ğŸ‘‚ğŸ‘‚ğŸ‘‚ #champo #championship #burnout #praticewhatyoupreach #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

.

It might even take a few years ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ But you have to stick at it. And not just for how you look. But for how you feel. â¤ï¸ For your health, your wellbeing, your life ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†

Do We Need Breakfast?
.
. 
Well firstly itâ€™s a myth that anyone â€˜needsâ€™ breakfast. 
But we were always told that breakfast is the most important meal of the day?
If you questioned why. You were probably told because your metabolism starts when you eat breakfast. If you have breakfast, your metabolism starts earlier. And probably that you burn more calories if you eat breakfast or â€˜youâ€™ll lose weightâ€™ eating breakfast. Well according to Betts et al 2014 [1] Daily Breakfast consumption has no effect on resting metabolism. For those of you who hate breakfast or those of you who like to fast, there is hope ğŸ˜ Does that mean donâ€™t eat breakfast? Absolutely not. Iâ€™m a regular breakfast eater. I could not go without it. But I deal with clients daily who â€˜Donâ€™t have timeâ€™ or â€˜canâ€™t stomach itâ€™ so I wonâ€™t force them to consume it. The answer really is do you want breakfast, if no, donâ€™t eat it, if yes, enjoy ğŸ˜Š  You may have also been told the more meals you have in a day equates to burning more calories and boosts your metabolism more. 
This is also a myth. The thermic effect of food is the same if you have 6 meals or 2 meals. Sometimes having small frequent meals can actually prove a hindrance as you may overconsume on calories. Dashti et al. 2017 [2]. Your metabolism or metabolic rate is highly influenced by your overall calorie consumption, your food choices, your NEAT and your purposeful exercise. It is overall daily calorie intake that is what matters, not necessarily how you distribute it. Unless in certain circumstances like athletic performance or muscle retention, where it may be important. 
So finally, it really comes down to personal preference. Do what suits you and your lifestyle. Remember, when it comes to metabolic rate, overall calories are important. What is not important is meal timing or meal frequency. ğŸ˜Š

1.	 The causal role of breakfast in energy balance and health: a randomized controlled trial in lean adults. Betts et al. 
Am J Clin Nutr. 2014 
2.	Recommending Small, Frequent Meals in the Clinical Care of Adults: A Review of the Evidence and Important Considerations. Dashti et al
Nutr Clin Pract 2017

Just to clarify...
.
.
âœ”ï¸Its OK to go on a holiday.

Even if it is in the middle of championship ğŸğŸğŸ
.
.
I feel like sometimes people forget this is a hobby. You're not paid. You don't get that much recognition. And yet you're expected to act like an elite athlete.
.
.
For me:
Holidays are a necessity. I work my normal 40 hours. I have my online clients which probably bring my working week up to 60 hours. I drive 1.5-3hrs daily. I rise at 5am at least 3 times a week and am in bed every night at 11 because of either work or training. I do something every weekend because I like to keep busy. And that's before training. I train 4 times a week with football and 1/2 of my own sessions. âœ”ï¸That's who I am and I like being super busy.
.
. 
Holidays give me time to relax and unwind and without them I would never do that.
I used to be that person who sacrificed everything to play football. I still sacrifice a lot, you have to. But I was sacrificing my happiness and probably a little bit of my health.
.
.

Amanda is amazing!! My weight would have always been up and down but I had really fell into a rut in the last 12months. 
I am beginning to see the changes already after only 8 weeks with Amanda! She is knowledgeable, supportive, she will push you!!... but she is also down to earth and that is what I needed. 
If I had an occasion etc that was okay, Amanda would motivate you to just get back at it the next day! Not to give up like I would have before!
I have really enjoyed the 8 weeks but as Amanda said herself â€˜this is a lifestyle, not just 8 weeksâ€™ I am looking forward to continuing in my new routine and canâ€™t thank Amanda enough for her support and help in getting me back on track, and feeling positive again!!! â¤â¤

Fat gets a bad rep. Sure it is 9Kcal per gram but it is an essential part of a balanced fat. Fats provide us with energy, makes up our cell membranes as well as our brain and nervous system. Fats are necessary to transport vitamins A,D,E and K and make and balance certain hormones. Fat can be found in 2 forms:
Saturated â€“ mainly found in animal products like meat, dairy, eggs, coconut
Unsaturated â€“ found in marine sources like fish oils, as well as nuts, seeds and vegetable oils
.
. 
For years saturated fat was thought to be associated with higher risk of Cardiovascular Disease and so it was deemed as â€˜unhealthyâ€™ or â€˜bad for youâ€™. The problem with saturated fat was not the actual fat itself but rather the increased consumption of processed food or the large quantities of saturated fat products. Saturated fat helps increase the cholesterol production in the body which is an essential part of metabolism and in the production of steroid hormones. So saturated fat should feature in our diet, just maybe donâ€™t latter every meal in butter.
.
. 
Unsaturated fats are made up of mono and polyunsaturated fats.  These contain our omega 3 and omega 6 fatty acids. Omega 3 fatty acids open our airways and blood vessels. They reduce our blood lipids and cholesterol and lower inflammation and pain. Omega 6 fatty acids do the opposite. Both are needed in the body, without both we wouldnâ€™t heal or recover from exercise. The problem with Western diets is that we donâ€™t have the proper ratios. We are at about 10:1 where we should be at 2:1 (omega 6/omega 3).
.
. 
Low fat diets were a fad a few years ago. While people reduced calories, they increased their intake of processed foods. Diets lacked fats and fat soluble vitamins so instead of being healthier people were losing weight but were not healthier.
.
. 
Fats are an essential part of any healthy diet. Be aware that they are very calorie dense so be sure not to overconsume and donâ€™t opt for processed versions. Enjoy them as part of a balanced lifestyle.

.
.
When my Dad died, my whole outlook on life changed. Health became a priority to me and abs no longer seemed so important. As soon as I started caring more about my health, I started to enjoy my training a lot more ğŸ˜ I was still eating very well but I wasn't obsessing about 'bad food'.
.
.
Fast forward 3 years later and I am so incredibly proud of my body. Not for what it looks like but for what it can do â¤ï¸ And the irony of it is, I'm probably in the best shape of my life as result.

caption:
How to get a bikini body.
Step 1. Put on a bikini. ğŸ‘™
.
. 
While I wish it were that simple for everyone to be that confident. Not everyone is. Truth is every single woman out there has insecurities ğŸ˜­ Myself included. I'd be pretty comfortable in a bikini year round but there are tips I recommend to make you feel good whilst on holidays â˜€ï¸
.
.
Like most I enjoy myself on holidays. I drink, I eat rich food and I exercise less. All these differences to my lifestyle and add in the fact that I have a sensitive stomach can cause a lot of bloating and water retention. ğŸ‹ I try to keep this at bay as best as possible so I feel confident in my bikini ğŸ‘Œ
.
. 
1. Drink as much water as possible. Alcohol plus salty food can equal a lot of fluid retention so it's important to get guzzling that water. Not to mention the other side effects of dehydration like headaches and vomiting. Nobody wants that on holidays. I also bring electrolytes and dandelion Root with me.
.
.
2. Do a little exercise. While I take a break from my heavy 5-6 day routine I like to get a session in every 2-3 days. If you're not interested in the gym when away nÃ³ problem. Why not go for a run or cycle? And walk EVERYWHERE ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
3. Don't take the piss. If you want to eat like an absolute fool, do, but don't complain about the stomach cramps or diarrhoea. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ If I'm going to Indulge in a heavy meal for dinner, I'll have a decent breakfast or vice versa. Keep protein with every meal and reduce snacking if it's leading to a massive consumption in calories. .
.
4. Don't drink all your calories. Cocktails are great ğŸ¹ But don't forget they contain calories too, so does the 3 fantas a day and your baileys coffee after dinner ğŸ™Š Again, I suffer if I eat a lot of sugar so I know not to over consume on these, but some of you might need some reminding ğŸ¤£ğŸ˜µ
.
.
It's not all doom and gloom. You won't ruin all your progress if you do decide to go all out. I just know some of you suffer with the same symptoms as me and hopefully this might help you ğŸ˜Š
.
.
Enjoy holidays â˜€ï¸ #holidaytips, #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #bikinibody #confidence #fitfam #irishfitfam

I am not an s&c coach so I won't be giving advice on the different phases and cycles you should have in the gym. Although I have a very good idea it's not my area of expertise so I'll leave that to the experts ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘Œ
.
.
What I do know?
- Resistance training is essential to reduce injury risk. Doing it pre season is not enough. You need to dedicate at least one day a week to it. The game speed and strength has dramatically increased. So too has the injury count. We need to keep on top of our games.
.
.
But what if I'm sore for training/match?
- Doms predominantly occur from:
1. A break from training and rÃ© introduction of weights. Best way to avoid this, don't take a week off and definitely don't take more than that ğŸ˜•
2. A new stimulus - maybe a new programme with the introduction of new exercises. Don't start this the day before a game ğŸ˜‘
3. Under recovery - Not getting in sufficient food and water post exercise
.
.
What should I be doing then?
Again, this won't be too highly detailed. Not my area of expertise ğŸ‘†
- Volume shouldn't be crazy high - Rep ranges should probably be lower with higher weights. There's no need for a 12 exercise, hypertrophic leg day in the middle of championship ğŸ˜©ğŸ˜©
- Exercises that transfer over onto the pitch - Strength, Power and plyomteric exercises. NOT bicep curls ğŸ˜‚ğŸ’ª LADS that one is aimed at ye ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
- If you're recovering from an injury, you need to keep up with individual rehab as well as what everyone else is doing ğŸ‘Œ

caption:
Sweet potato versus white potatoğŸ¥”ğŸ 
.
. 
The humble spud got a very bad rep in the last couple of years and the reign of the sweet potato took over. All potato recipes were substituted with sweet potato and sweet potato fries were on every menu. What is the difference between the two tubers?
.
. 
When you compare 100g of each baked, there is very little difference calorie wise. Carbohydrate and fibre wise they are practically identical. The main nutritional difference would be the significantly higher vitamin A content in Sweet potato and the white potato contains more potassium. Both have a High GI when cooked. .
. 
So, if you are thinking youâ€™re â€˜healthierâ€™ eating Sweet potato, remember there is place for both types of potato in your diet and both should be enjoyed as part of a balanced diet ğŸ˜Š

#sweetpotato #whitepotato

I put up a poll yesterday to see are people being led by marketing. While I was delighted to see most people don't think dairy free, gluten free or vegan = healthy. Over 40 of you answered yes. ğŸ¤”
.
.
Companies have become really smart recently with their marketing strategies and are constantly using buzz words like gluten free or high protein. These buzz words do not automatically make a food healthy. The only person that NEEDS to eat gluten free is a coeliac. Now that being said a gluten free diet can simply be an elimination of processed wheat, barley, and rye based products. But there is no need to opt for gluten free products because you think they are healthier. They are often heavily processed and again are not necessary unless you are coeliac. Same goes for dairy free ğŸ™„ As for Vegan, this is a new buzzword. Plant based should be a large part of every diet for all the micronutrients, water and phytonutrients it gives us ğŸ˜ But getting a 'vegan sausage roll' will not make you a health queen ğŸ˜‚ Remember, if weight loss is a goal, calories are king. So if you are choosing between a raw cacao, nut butter, hazelnut infused brownie (400 cals) and an Eton mess (200cals), the Eton mess is probably the better option for your dietary goals. It may not be refined Sugar free but it's lower in calories (not based on actual calories). Finally, my favourite, high protein label. Everything has protein in it now: bars, bread, even water ğŸ˜‚
.
.
Just keep it simple. Plant based fruit and vegetables with each meal and snack. If you eat meat, buy from a butchers or reliable source. Natural protein sources include a lot of dairy based products, meat, fish, eggs, and legumes. Natural wholegrains, and tubers for our carbohydrate sources. Natural oils rather than man-made products. It's not rocket science. Don't give into marketing strategies, a lot of the time it's ğŸƒğŸ’© #labelling #marketing #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #eatforgoals #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
What is Fibre and why is it important? ğŸ¤” - Fibre comes in 2 different forms:soluble and insoluble. We can't digest these, but they have very important roles in the body especially within our gut.
.
.
Soluble fibre is found in fruit, oats, dried beans and peas, nuts, barley and chia.
.
.
Insoluble fibre is found vegetables, fruit and vegetable skins, seeds and nuts
.
.
â˜‘ï¸Fibre helps us feel fuller for longer
â˜‘ï¸Lowers our risk of Colon cancer
â˜‘ï¸ Speeds up digestion through our GI tract
â˜‘ï¸ Bulks up our stools
â˜‘ï¸ Lowers our blood lipids and Cholesterol
â˜‘ï¸Boost overall gut health

We need approximately 25-35g per day. In Ireland, we tend to not eat enough fibre and thus we can have issues with our gut health. Too much can cause digestive stress so it's important to get just the right amountğŸ‘Œ

#fibre #itsimportant #healthyalternatives

Football has been a huge part of my life from an early age ğŸ’• I've talked about how terrible I was as an underage player on more than one occasion ğŸ¤£ I was lucky that fitness became a focus of the game, because that I could do ğŸ’ªğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ I've talked about my struggles after my Dad died and how hard football became for me. Most games now my boyfriend is my sole supporter â™¥ï¸ (And he's too nice for the post match analysis ğŸ˜‚â¤ï¸)
.
.
Football has developed me as a person. It has developed traits in me that I've carried into my life, my job, and my relationships â™¥ï¸ For awhile, football was my life. While I love it, and I mostly have positive things to say about it. Never EVER forget it is only a hobby. I give out about it a lot ğŸ˜‚ But I still enjoy it. And if I ever don't enjoy it, it wont be a part of my life. To play at the top level, you need to make sacrifices. That is a given. And if you're not willing to, you shouldn't be playing. These sacrifices will include social occasions. Again, expect that. If it starts affecting other elements of your life, your job, relationships or your health, that's where you draw a line. Coming back to the fact that any sport is a hobby. Gaa is not paid, and the sacrifices do mimic a professional sport. So enjoy the sport. Remember that's why you are doing it. ğŸ¤” Don't let it dictate your life. And if you feel it is, there are loads of other hobbies out there ğŸ‘ŒğŸ˜‰ #gaagirls #gaelicgirls #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

Friday reminder that nobody is perfect and we all have struggles ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯
.
.
Some days I love having muscle. Some days I hate that I can't fit into 'normal' clothes. Some days I love being strong. Other days I hate how many fouls I give away on the pitch because of it. Most days I love a healthy salad. Some days I just need chocolate for my soul (this weekend ğŸ˜). Some days I have so much energy I can't sleep at night. Other days I barely have the energy to brush my hair ğŸ˜‚ Some days I am super motivated. Other days a walk is a struggle (Monday ğŸ™Š).
.
.
Nobody is happy 24/7. Even the most confident people struggle. Don't ever forget that. The most important thing is to be at peace with yourself and your body. It is your most valuable asset and you need to treat it well ğŸ’• If you don't, it's never too late to change it ğŸ’¯

caption:
What are the components to fitness and how do I get fitter? This can be a very scientific topic so I'm going to put it in as simple terms as possible ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Firstly, you need to push outside a comfort zone or a tolerance limit. Most people will stay in that. And while staying in that zone will keep you at the same fitness levels, its pushing outside it that will ultimately improve your fitness. Let's be brutally honest, we've all seen it, the fittest players getting fitter while the unfit players pull out of sessions. This may not actually be their fault either. With team sports, there are all fitness levels. While you try to push the fittest on the team, sometimes it's too much on the unfit players which leads to dropout. If playing team sports, runs/sprints should be staggered (fitter players have more to do). Bench players should also have extra to do so they don't fall behind starting players. There is no one size fits all and that's hard to do with team sports. (This is purely opinion)
.
.
You need to train in the right energy systems. You don't see a Sprinter constantly doing 5ks (which is an aerobic system), no you see them work in an anaerobic system. If they are sprinting, they are working their creatine phosphate system, if they are in the gym, they are using the same energy system. If you are a field sport player, you need a bit of both. You need to be able to access your anaerobic system for short sprints and your aerobic system for recovery. That's why your trainer should have you doing both fast, speed work and endurance work. If you are poor in either of those areas, you need to work on them ğŸ˜
.
.
Hydration and Nutrition. Never ever underestimate these powerful tools. We only train about 10% of our time. The other 90% is sleep, recovery and nutrition. What you put into your body has a huge impact on your fitness levels. I talked about food and the importance of it not just for fuel but for other essential bodily functions ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Recovery. In the form of food, hydration, sleep, and physical rest. Our bodies are smart. If you Constantly 'grinding', our bodies don't have time to adapt. They are in overdrive.
Continued in comments

caption:
People over complicate everything ğŸ™€ğŸ™€
.
.
Nutrition is relatively simple. Not necessarily easy, but simple. Exercise is the same. Eat better, move more ğŸ˜
.
.
I have people coming to me, sprinting before they have even learned to walk. Yes, I've heard it all. I've had overweight/obese people give out to me about my food choices as they are not organic or may be genetically modifiedğŸ¤” I've had people who lived on takeaways all of a sudden are now vegan. And don't even get me started on going gluten and lactose free ğŸ˜«ğŸ™Š Guys, get your house in order. If you are over weight none of these extremes are necessary. If you cut back a little on treats, controlled portion size and ate more vegetables you could probably sort all your problems out. It may be a slower process but it's a consistent one. I'm not trying to be harsh. I'm actually trying to be nice and say it's more simple than you are making it ğŸ˜«
.
.
As for exercise. Going from nothing to something is always a benefit. But make sure it's not just purposeful exercise. Increasing your steps daily will have a huge benefit on your Basal Metabolic rate. And as for the best exercise, that is the one you enjoy the most and can sustain. I know people that exercise that absolutely hate it and do it for the sake of it ğŸ˜­ Exercise should be something you enjoy, not endure, so find one you likeâ¤ï¸. I would recommend some form of resistance training on top of it, as it's hugely beneficial for bone, ligament and tendon health as well as maintaining lean muscle mass.
.
.
So stop over complicating healthy eating and exercise. You don't need to be a gluten and lactose free vegan to be healthy, nor do you need to be a crossfit athlete. Get moving daily, stop treating yourself so often (you don't need it), reduce your portion size and increase your vegetable consumption. Thats a great start right there ğŸ‘†ğŸ˜ #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #eatwell #stopovercomplicatingthings #healthylifestyle #fitlifestyle #fitliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
I'm not a physio and I won't be giving you a big list of exercises to do for ACL rehab. Also, every injury is so different and every individual is so specialised and specific I won't be giving a one size fits all approach, because there isn't one ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
What I will say is 2 things:
ğŸ‘‰ Firstly, don't underestimate the influence of nutrition on the healing process. What you put in your body is as important as your rehab exercises. Never forget that. ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†
.
.
ğŸ‘‰ Secondly, if and hopefully when you get back on the pitch. Just because you are back from injury does not mean you are healed. If you don't keep on top of your strength and rehab work, your chances of re injury is increasingly higher. Keep on top of your strength work. Not just your quads (most of us footballers are quad dominant which isn't helped by the fact that when we do leg work it's mostly quad dominant work) but hamstrings and glutes need attention. Glute exercises include: Hip Trusters, Hip Bridges and Band Work. Hamstrings need to do 2 things: Knee Flexion (exercises like leg curls, Nordics) and Hip Extension (RDL).
.
.
From my experience, staying on top of my nutrition and strength work has hugely benefited me since I had ACL reconstruction 4.5 years ago ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª #consistency #rehab #strengthtraining #gaagirls #gaelicgirls #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
One of the most common questions I get asked is about a pre match meal. Well let me tell you, pre Match fuel begins long before the pre match meal. ğŸ˜ƒ
.
.
As discussed in previous posts, carbohydrates are the main fuel source involved in GAA. We can store 80-100g in our liver and 300-600g in our muscles as glycogen. But as glucose is constantly being used as a fuel source it is constantly depleting therefore we need to top it up regularly.
.
.
Pre Match nutriton begins the day before a game. So if you play Sunday at 2pm. You should be topping glycogen stores from 2pm Saturday. I recommend a carbohydrate source with each meal like Cous cous for lunch, potatoes for dinner and oats for breakfast the following morning. Closer to game time, fruit is a great source of cÃ¡rbohydrate. Protein is also essential. As athletes we are constantly in recovery mode for our next session so protein needs to be a part of our pre Match routine. Although it won't be used as fuel it is an important element for muscle repair etc.
.
.
Some don'ts the day of a game
âŒâŒâŒ â High fat foods are harder to break down in the body and may cause gastrointestinal upset so best to avoid large quantities of fat. Save them for afterwards when we need to reduce inflammation
â High fibre foods can also cause gastrointestinal issues and while fibre is a vital part of a healthy diet, its best to avoid large quantities before games
â Strong flavoured foods .
.
Some dos
âœ”ï¸âœ”ï¸âœ”ï¸
â˜‘ï¸ Nutrient dense foods with a cÃ¡rbohydrate and protein element
ğŸ‘‰Oats with whey protein, Eggs and Toast, fruit salad with Greek Yogurt, Chicken and pasta, fish and potatoes
â˜‘ï¸ Don't forget about water. Hydration is a key pre Match ritual

Hope this helps ğŸ˜ƒ Never change a routine the day of a game. Slowly make changes in the days leading up to a game ğŸ‘Œ

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #prematch #nutrition #fitliving #fitfam #irishfitfam

Prior to beginning my 8 week program from Amanda I was very active, playing ladies football and training between 3/4 times a week. I felt frustrated as I wasnâ€™t seeing any results so linking up with Amanda was the best decision I ever made. From the detailed diet plan and training program I began to see a big difference on and off the field. I began to lose body fat and gain lean muscle, feeling physically stronger in every aspect. Thanks Amanda ğŸ’ªğŸ» I am fully booked until July with online clients. Listen up, this one is an important one.ğŸ‘‚
.
.
Yes macros are important. Carbohydrate is the main source of energy for most sports. Protein is essential for repair and recovery. Fats are anti inflammatory and necessary for fat soluble vitamin transport. Yes your macronutrients which convert into energy are fuel for the body.
.
.
But what about micronutrients, phytonutrients and zoo chemicals. These don't directly fuel us but they are also vital to the functioning of the human body. They are responsible for vital internal functions and without them our bodies would not be able to asorb nutrients or convert them to energy. They are vital for gut health, immunity, nervous system functioning, nutrient absorbtion, digestion... The list goes on. ğŸ“ƒ As humans, our bodies don't just do one thing at a time (even if we think we are). Just to be alive, all our systems are working internally. Imagine adding eating and drinking to that. Now let's add a job. Let's add a family. Let's add exercise. Our bodies are constantly working, there is no off switch ğŸ“´ Sometimes are bodies are under serious strain. If we are not getting the vital nutrients we need to keep up with this pressure, major problems can occur within the body. ğŸ˜
.
.
I don't give opinions on this very often but I'm going to for this one. If you are constantly worrying/counting macros and not focusing on food quality that's fine, you'll get the fuel you need for your body. But overall, internally, you are not focusing on the other functions in your body. Your body is more than just an engine that you need to fuel. It's complex and deserves to be treated like your most important possession. Because really, that's what it is ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤” #foodisnorethanfuel #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #healthylifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Let's just get one thing straight the optimal body composition for EVERYONE is a high lean muscle mass and a lower body fat mass. That includes having strong bones, joints, ligaments and tendons. This is the composition our body thrives on and is most healthy in. That is the body composition everyone should be aiming for. ğŸ‘Œ Now, that doesn't mean you will get muscular or bulky ğŸ˜‚ I understand that my muscle mass is not for everyone but believe me, most of you will never have to worry about that ğŸ˜‚
.
.
How to gain muscle:
ğŸ‘‰ First thing you need is a lot of patience. Especially if you want to gain muscle and remain relatively lean. The difference between these photos is 4 years and there's still not that much difference ğŸ˜‚
ğŸ‘‰ You need food. Food is fuel. Generally, you need to be in a slight calorie surplus to gain muscle. Protein and carbs are your best friends â¤ï¸
ğŸ‘‰ Resistance training. From my experience, volume and time under tension are 2 of the main aids for gaining muscle. Rep ranges of about 8-12 are working in a hypertrophy range of building muscle. But it's good to mix strength, hypertrophy and endurance.
ğŸ‘‰ Frequency. Don't expect results from training twice a week. It's not necessarily about training 2 hours a day every day but frequency is important. Train smarter not harder.
ğŸ‘‰ Recovery. This relates to food, hydration, sleep and physical rest. Your body needs to repair itself to grow.

And enjoy the process ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ #muscle #girlswithmuscle #bodycomposition #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitlife #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
This is one I get asked on a lot. So here is a very general guide.
.
.
Step 1: Weight in kg x (22-24)
- 22 Low Activity Level daily - 23 Medium Activity Level daily
- 24 High Activity Level daily
.
.
Step 2: Mutiply this number by training frequency level (1.2 - 2.0)
- 1.2 - Little to no training
- 1.4 - Training 1-3 times per week
- 1.6 - Training 3-5 times per week
- 1.8 - Training 6-7 times per week
- 2.0 - Training 6-7 times a week with highly active job or 2+ per day
.
.
Step 3: Adjust for goals
If maintenance is a goal. You have it. If weight loss is a goal minus the percentage body weight you want to lose. If weight gain is a goal add the percentage body weight you want to gain.
.
.
Example: 30 year old woman who works at a desk job wants to lose 6kg. She is currently 66kg and trains about 3 times a week.
66 x 22 = 1452

1452 x 1.4 = 2032

2032 x 90% (wants to loose 10% BW) = 1832 per day (you could go a little lower if you wanted to speed up weight loss, this number is for a slow, sustainable weight loss) .
.
I have no problem with my fitness pal but please stop getting your calorie and macro figures from it. It is not accurate or tailored to you ğŸ˜‘ğŸ˜‘ğŸ˜‘ It is a good tool to track foods but not to get calories and macros on ğŸ˜’

#calories #caloriecounting #fitliving #fitlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #foodisfuel #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Are Macro and Micro Nutrients important for Athletes??? YES!!!!
.
.
Let's delve into what we need each nutrient for and requirement levels.
.
.
Protein ğŸ¥©ğŸ³ğŸ¥“
Every cell in your body needs protein. Protein is absolutely essential for athletes due to the amount of training they are doing. Protein turnover is very high so demands for protein are also very high. We need it for recovery and muscle repair. It is also very important in times of injury. I recommend 2g per Kg of Bodyweight.
Sources include: Meat, Fish, Eggs, Beans, Legumes. Eat protein at every meal.
.
.
Carbohydrates ğŸ¥”ğŸ¥ªğŸš
Carbohydrate is the preferred fuel for GAA. It gives us energy in the form of glucose or stored glycogen. There are 2 types of carbohydrates:Complex carbohydrates and simple sugars. Complex carbohydrates are the ones we want most of in our diet. They not only provide fuel but also fibre which is essential for gut health. I recommend about 3g per Kg Bodyweight. This can increase days of games/trainings or day before to almost 6g per Kg Bodyweight. Sources include: Rice, Oats, Fruit, Potatoes, Sweet Potato.
.
.
Fats ğŸ¥‘ğŸŒ°ğŸ§€
Fats are often neglected and are a very important part of an athletes diet. Fats reduce inflammation (caused by exercise or injury), they are part of our cell membranes and they transport vitamins A, D, Ã‰ & K. I recommend about 1-1.5g per Kg BW. This can increase or decrease based on carbohydrate consumption. Sources include: Avocado, nuts, seeds, dark chocolate, oily fish
.
.
Micronutrients ğŸ‰ğŸ¥¦ğŸ¥’
These are often overlooked. Although they are required in small quantities, lack of consumption can lead to serious deficiencies. Not only is immune function lowered increasing risk of catching colds and illnesses which can increase absenteeism from training. Cognitive function can be impaired (not ideal on a pitch). Micronutrient deficiencies in some cases can cause fatigue like a lack of Iron or B Group Vitamins. Water would also be considered a micronutrient
. .
 It is important to look at the big picture. It's not just macros that are important to athletes. We need micronutrients for our overall recovery and health ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ğŸ‹ï¸â€â™€ï¸

caption:
Let's talk ConfidenceğŸ™ŠğŸ™ŠğŸ™Š
.
.
People assume I've always been confident. This is so far from the case. Confidence is not something you are born with. It's something you choose to become, in my opinion ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
I'll tell you my struggles with confidence we've all had them.
.
.
When I was a teenager I struggled with my appearance. I would wear make up every single day. I would never be seen without make up. I was so afraid what people would think of my bare face ğŸ˜© Would Boys still like meğŸ˜© I struggled with body image (as most teenagers do). I was tiny. But I always thought I could be thinner. My distorted image of exercise was for weight loss only. It just helped that I actually liked football. ğŸ˜”
.
.

Food. Nutrition. Weight Loss. Weight Gain. Performance. Sleep. The list goes on....
.
.
First thing is first, you need to figure out is your goal. If its weight loss. Calories are king. Not low cÃ¡rb or high cÃ¡rb or keto or Atkins. Calories. Being in a caloric deficit. Please don't use myfitnesspal calories as they cut you down to insanely low daily intake ğŸ˜± Which will have an impact on your BMR and is not healthy long term. Get a professional to help you and THEN you can log them into my fitness pal (if you have the patience, I personally don't). Sometimes healthy options are higher in calories than processed counterparts. So yes you CAN overconsume healthy food and sometimes the lower calorie option is better for your goals.
.
.
If health is the goal. We're mainly talking whole nutritious foods. We're talking very little processed food. We're thinking about our insides not just our outside ğŸ™ It's probably more a long term goal.
.
.
If performance is the goal our macro and micro nutrients become far more important. Are we getting enough protein for recovery? Do we have a good cÃ¡rb fuel store? Are we using fats as an anti inflammatory? Are we eating enough fruit and veggies for our immune system?
.
.
Figure out your goal. Seek help from someone qualified. Get a coach. It's not as simple as it seems sometimes ğŸ™ŠğŸ˜ #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitness #fitgirls #fitfam #irishfitfam

After years of doing my own thing in the gym with little or no results I decided to undertake Amanda's 8 week challenge. For me my aim at the end of this challenge was far more about mobility and strength rather then aesthetics. I had experienced so much difficulty from a cartilage issue in my knee that I felt I was so limited in what I could do. In general I'm quiet petite and have never had any issue with my weight however I wanted to see if I could tone up and get stronger while working through the problem with my knee. The program that amanda gave me was absolutely unbelievable.she knew exactly what I was looking for and tailored my plan to include strength exercises that would build up all the muscles around my knee allowing me to lift heavier weights and incorporate more cardio into my routine, something that I had been so afraid of in case I damaged my knee more. The 8 weeks with Amanda is worth so much more then any amount of sessions with a physio. I can now walk around pain free and have mobility back in my knee. My whole body has toned up and I am so much stronger. This program has made me enjoy the gym again and amanda herself is worth her weight in gold both professionally and as a personal friend. I would recommend this program to anyone who wants to change things up a bit or try something different you will not regret it.

caption:
If you're like me and calorie counting is not your thing. All is not lost. Yes calories matter but so does your life and if you absolutely hate the thought of entering everything you eat into my fitness pal, as a trainer I would never force you ğŸ˜‰Most if not all of my clients have achieved their incredible results from never having entered a calorie or macro into myfitnesspal ğŸ‘ğŸ‘ğŸ‘
.
.
I am not slating it. It obviously works for people. And whoever uses it and enjoys tracking, go you ğŸ‘ There are some reasons why the calories on our food labels don't actually correlate to real life though ğŸ™ˆSo it's not a 100% fool proof method.
ğŸ‘‰ Fibre and resistant starches are often overestimated
ğŸ‘‰ Some of the data is outdated or the analysis of it was imprecises
ğŸ‘‰ Only one product is tested so it doesn't take into account product variety
ğŸ‘‰ Soil composition and animals diets are not taken into account
ğŸ‘‰ Ripeness at time of harvest. Ever taste in season Irish strawberries vs imported out of seasonğŸ˜
ğŸ‘‰ Storage, preparation and cooking of food can change nutritional composition of food
.
.
Some of my top tips if you're not interested in tracking:
ğŸ’¥ Protein at each meal (approx 2g per Kg BW)
ğŸ’¥ Load up on veggies (full of micros and volume, low in calories)
ğŸ’¥ Portion size (use a smaller plate and watch those cÃ¡rb and fat portions)
ğŸ’¥ Fibre rich foods (fruit, veggies, legumes, some complex carbs)
ğŸ’¥ Drink plenty of water. A lot of the time we're actually thirsty not hungry
.
.
And just keep active. Technically, you don't have to if you're nutrition is on point. But come on, we are so lucky to be able to exercise. Enjoy it ğŸ˜

caption:
A little bit of info on calories and how sometimes less is not always bestğŸ˜‘
***Disclaimer: This will not be relevant to a lot of people. Take into account my training schedule etc.***
.
.
Last week for possibly the first time ever I tracked calories ğŸ™ˆ And I was shocked to see how much lower my calories were than they should be for maintenance. I kinda knew I was in a deficit but thought ah sure losing a little body fat would do no harm ğŸ˜œğŸ™ˆ
.
.
You see when you drop your calories and your exercise activity is still high, your Resting Metabolic Rate (RMR) drops. Because you are eating less your Thermic Effect from food(TEF) drops. Being in a deficit also means energy can suffer. ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ .
.
So I decided to up my cals and carbs. And I've never felt so good or more lean ğŸ‘ŒğŸ˜ I trained 6 times this week and still had energy for a game today. My sleep has been great. My mood is incredible ğŸ˜
.
.
This mostly relates to athletes especially women. Less is not always best. You need to fuel your body. You need to recover well. You need your hormones, enzymes and antibodies to function properly. If you need help or advice seek it ğŸ‘Œ

caption:
Walk before you can run ğŸƒğŸƒğŸƒ
.
.
So the reason most people fail at their health and fitness routine is because they go from zero to 100 in a week ğŸ˜” It's a  sure recipe for successğŸ˜
.
.
You need to make much smaller steps. And make a new one weekly. All these small steps will make your fitness journey so much easier ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Let's take a breakfast for an example. If you're used to a big breakfast roll with a bottle of coke on your way to work, chances are you're not going to get up at 6am before work to make some 'Smashed avocado on sourdough topped with poached eggs' ğŸ˜‚ğŸ¥‘ Why not pick up a breakfast wrap minus the butter and ketchup and a coke zero. Maybe after a couple of weeks you might bring some Overnight oats with you ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
If you've never exercised before in your life, 5 days of Hiit is never going to be sustainableğŸ™ˆ Why not do 3 days of resistance training with 2 long walks?
.
.
If your regular water consumption is less than 500ml, forcing 2L down your throat is torture.
.
. 
I think you get the picture. Stop trying to be perfect. Perfection doesn't exist. Don't try a lifestyle overhaul. Make small changes. Be more conscious when shopping. This is something I try to instill in all my clients. It should work into your lifestyleğŸ‘ And some of you may never ever have salmon for breakfast ğŸ˜‚

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #progressnotperfection #fitlife #fitliving #fitchick #fitfam #irishfitfam

Why are we always so negative and pessimistic? ğŸ˜©ğŸ˜©ğŸ˜©
.
.
Most common things I hear working in a gym:
-I can't
- I won't be able
- I'm too unfit
- I'm too heavy
- I'm not strong enough
- I'd never be able to do that
- I'll fail
ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
Well you'll never know unless you try ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯ No one Jumps out of the womb super fit. Everybody struggles with nutrition to a degree. Everyone is on their own journeyğŸ‘ŒğŸ’ª
.
.
Firstly, stop doubting yourself and start trying. I can assure you, you definitely will fail if you don't try. When starting to learn to drive and it's hard do you suddenly give up? No, because driving a car is important. We'll guess what your health is even more important â¤ï¸ğŸ’¯ Secondly, stop bloody comparing yourself. Comparison is the thief of joy. You are never going to be somebody else, so stop trying to be. Instead focus on being a better version of you â¤ï¸ I used to do this all the time, I'd watch other girls on Instagram lifting heavier weights than me and I'd be so jealousğŸ˜’ Now, I focus on my own goals because I'm happy with where I'm at â¤ï¸
.
.
This weekend I had clients say to me they were happy and proud of themselves. This was absolute music to my earsğŸ¼ğŸ¶Finally, a bit of self assurance and confidence ğŸ‘Œ We could all do with more of it. â¤ï¸ #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #balance #stopbeingsonegative #stopbeingsohardonyourself  #fitfam #irishfitfam

Did you know that nothing changes, if nothing changes??? ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
If you're still stuck in the same routine, doing the same thing, you'll get the same results you always got. ğŸ™„ğŸ™„ğŸ™„
.
.
Unless you make a change, you won't see a changeğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆ
.
.
Start off small. Remove one 'chocolate bar' a day. Or save money and cut out the 3 daily mochas. What about trying to have protein with every meal? Get 10,000 steps a day. Start resistance training.
.
.
Be smart invest in a coach and/or a nutritionist. If you think you can do it alone and have been trying for the past 3 years, it's definitely worth the money. caption:
Should you go all out when out for a meal or drinks??? ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
I made a confession last night that I'm an all out kinda gal when it comes to meals out, drinks too ğŸ¤¤ The way I see it. I go out for dinner on average once a month. That is one meal out of approx 30 days, approx 150 meals. Its one 'bad' one. I also only drink on holidays. Its a very rare occasion. And super infrequent. Now my goals are not aesthetic. I could certainly be leaner, but my body doesn't function well on super lean. My body functions best at my current shape and performance is my goal ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ŒTherefore I'm at calorie maintenence so I don't need to overly worry about that one meal or that very infrequent drink ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸
.
.
But if your goals change this can change. Also if the frequency changes this can change. What about the other meals are they mainly healthy? You have to realise not all goals are the same. Just because I do it doesn't mean you have to ğŸ¤£And it may be affecting your goals?
.
.
It's what you do 'consistently' that matters not what you do once every so often. Achieving goals is all about Consistency and patience ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ #canigobacktovegas #slushiesandjellyshots #consistency #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitliving #balance #fitfam #irishfitfam

This week was all about recovery for me âœŒï¸
.
.
Since I came home from holidays at start of January I have been training really hard. First for a competition and then for football. I was doing a seriously demanding strength programme with 1/2 wods a week plus pitch sessionsğŸ™ˆ
. .
So this week, I pulled it all back. No hard training. 2 strength sessions (maintenance is now my goal though rather than increasing weights every week), 1 WOD (not a hard one this week) and 1 ball skills session.
.
.
I also had a chiropractor session and a great recovery package @acepandr. Today is Foam rolling and stretching âœŒï¸
.
.
Remember, you don't have to be constantly 'grinding'. It's OK to reduce volume, take a Deload week, take a week off etc. Your body NEEDS rest and recovery. Since my recovery session in ACE my sleep has been incredible ğŸ˜ And the cold I had at start of the week is more or less gone ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
P. S First Ice Bath in months ğŸ¤£Hence my facial experssions

caption:
Know your treats ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰ğŸ‘‰
.
.
So as I've said before here I'm a big fan of treats. I think we all deserve them (maybe not daily) but I think it's an important part of our enjoyment of food ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘Œ
.
.
When it comes to macro nutrients these 2 products are not comparable. The protein bar is way higher in protein and the milkybar contains a lot of sugar. But both still contain calories. I'm not telling you to eat either or both. I just want you to understand that just because it's labeled as 'healthier' does not mean it doesn't contain calories ğŸ™ˆ People could have 2 or 3 of these bars a day on top of their meals. So while you think you're eating well (and you probably are) you could be over consuming calories due to the nature of the foods your eating. This is obviously depending on goals. If goals are weight loss, calories are king. If goals are performance based, content of product becomes more important ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
Take home point. Just because it's labelled as 'healthier' version doesn't mean it doesn't contain calories. Healthy foods contain calories too and we can over consume ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤” Goals are too important. If you are an athlete looking to get the best from your body and looking to fuel yourself for your sport, it's different to you're average person just looking to lose afew pounds. Know your goalsğŸ‰ğŸ‰ğŸ‰ #healthyfoodcontainscaloriestoo

caption:
Calling all weights newbies or people dying to try it but too scared ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†ğŸ‘†
.
.
 I was once where you are too. Actually so was everyone. Nobody is born with weights in their hands ğŸ¤£ And nobody is born super strong. Strength comes from effort day in, day out. Any fitness for that matter comes from the sum of all your daily efforts, week in week out. It's about consistency ğŸ‘ŒğŸ‘Œ
.
.
I always hated when people said to me 'you're naturally fit'. Eh sorry Susan, I didn't see you up doing extra sprints on Christmas day. My whole life I've worked super hard to be fit. When I was younger it was aerobically fit. I ran so much (now I can't even do a 5k ğŸ¤£). Now I focus on strength and conditioning ğŸ’ªğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ And no I have not always been strong. When I trained in @elitefpa I was weak as p*#s. I used a 7kg bar for overhead press. 4.5 years later I'm in a competition where 25kg is easy ğŸ™‹â€â™€ï¸ğŸ‘† But again consistency. Last year I trained 50 out of 52 weeks (average 4/5 times a week). I took a week off the week after Connacht final and a week at Christmas. So no I am not naturally strong, I'm not naturally fit. It's not 'easier' for me. I'm an athlete. I train hard and reap the rewards â˜ï¸â˜ï¸
.
.
Side note: I do have muscle but I don't look this pumped all the time ğŸ˜‚ ğŸ’ª

caption:
Healthier, Happier and Fitter than I've ever been ğŸ’•ğŸ’•ğŸ’•
.
.
Things I would have told me 18 year old self:
1. Health is so much more important than weight (2 stone difference between pics)
2. Stop trying to be perfect. Perfection doesn't exsist
3. Relax a little. Don't stress so much. Good things come to people who work but remember there's a thing called life that needs to be enjoyed
4. Problems aren't solved at the bottom of a vodka bottle (only have learned this one in recent years ğŸ˜£)
5. Fitness is NOT about being skinny. I would tell my 18 year old self to start lifting weights â¤ï¸
6. Eat your bloody vegetables and stop being so damn picky. It feels so much better on your body and you'd have so much more energy
7. Make up isn't life. You are beautiful, stop hiding yourself with layers of foundation and baggy hoodies.
8. Appreciate everyone in your life. You think they will always be around. Unfortunately that's not the case ğŸ’”

So much has changed, yet so much has stayed the same. ğŸ’•ğŸ’•ğŸ’• #10yearchallenge #mentalnotphysical

Pre season NutritionğŸğŸ A question I get asked quite often is should nutrition be different pre-season and during season. The answer is yes. You should not be consuming the same calories in pre-season as you do during championship.
.
. 
Think about it though. Preseason is usually gym based with maybe one pitch session so activity levels are not as high. Compare that to full on championship mode, you may be on the pitch 3 times a week with one gym session. And this only takes one sport into consideration. You may have multiple sports.
If activity levels increase so too should calories and vice versa. If we are in a period of lowered activity, calories should therefore be lower. Overall calories are determined by gender, weight, activity level and goals.
.
. 
Macronutrient requirements will also be different. Protein requirements will be high in both cases as the need for recovery will be high i.e post gym session or post-match both require high protein. Protein targets are usually 1.8-2.2g per kg BW.
.
. 
Fats are also important for recovery and to reduce inflammation. These should be approximately 20% of our overall calorie intake.
.
. 
Carbohydrate is our main energy source during sport. Pre season however, requires less carbohydrate intake. We are focused on more short bursts of energy like Gym work or sprints which use a different energy system to matches. We donâ€™t need to consume carbohydrate with every meal during pre-season and while our calorie requirements are also lower here might be a good place to start. We could substitute our complex carbohydrate rice with a lower calorie cauliflower rice or breakfast could focus more on a larger omelette with extra veggies rather than 2 slices of bread? These are just options of how to reduce calories but keep bulk and not feel like you are depriving yourself. .
. 
It is important to understand that these are two different periods of an athleteâ€™s schedule. Just like we cycle training, we should also cycle our nutrition ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
This is what my pre season looked like thanks to @keelafarnon & @komplexfitness for pushing me to my limits the last few months training for this comp. Bring on Saturday ğŸ’ªğŸ’ªğŸ’ª

caption:
My 2019 'Resolutions' ğŸ’•ğŸ’•ğŸ’•
.
.
2018 was my most mentally challenging year. From January until mid October I suffered with problem after problem. They accumulated. Stress accumulated. My mental health deteriorated. Excess stress lead to niggly injuries. I wouldn't rest or couldn't recover because I was putting myself under too much pressure. My football performance suffered. My work suffered. With the help of @womensgpa I decided to seek counselling services and it was the best decision I've ever made. I'm not quiet about problems and issues. I've always talked about them. But sometimes you need more than just the ear of a sibling, partner or friends. Sometimes you need to seek professional help â¤ï¸
.
.
So therefore, 2019 is for me. For the first time in my life I'm putting 'my' needs and wants first. Not those of others. It's for prioritising myself.
.
.
'How can you help others if you are not looking after yourself? ' ğŸ’•

caption:
Christmas Drinks ğŸ»ğŸ·ğŸ¹
.
.
If you're like me, you don't drink very often and enjoy a tipple over the festive season. Remember you didn't get it all in a few days, so you won't lose it in a few days. Alcohol will however, cause water retention, possible bloating depending on drinks and probably cravings the following day ğŸ™ˆ 90% of the time, I don't give into these and go back to normal eating habits. And that's probably why I can drink as part of a balanced lifestyle ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
If you've been drinking since 1st December and use the whole of December as 'Christmas' things are gonna be a little harder for you ğŸ™ˆBut here's some of my tips:
1. Try a lower calorie option. Select from the above and try to stick with that. Pints and festive cocktails are laden with calories so beware.
2. Drink water between alcoholic drinks. You'll thank me the next morning ğŸ‘Œ
3. Drink more water in general over the festive period. It will help flush you outğŸ’¦
4. Eat a decent protein rich meal before heading out. And have a homemade snack ready when you get home to avoid chipper afterwards ğŸ™ˆOnce in a blue moon is OK but if you're out 4 times a week, it's a little excessive don't you think? My personal fav is toast with real butterğŸ¤¤
5. Don't give into cravings the next day. Your body is dehydrated, tired and sore. It doesn't need more crap it needs nourishment. Again as I said, once in a blue moon is fine but if you are eating more 'hungover food' than normal food, then we have a problem ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I will be enjoying my Gin and Slim tomorrow. Its my first of the holiday season and it won't be my last. But be mindful. Enjoy yourself but don't take the p*#s ğŸ˜Š

caption:
Let's talk stress ğŸ™ˆ The whole world is taking about calorie deficits and training hard, did you know that maybe you're 'grinding' too much ğŸ¤”
.
.
What do I mean?
ğŸ‘‰ We're always told, be in a calorie deficit to lose weight and exercise more? Right. But what if you're body is under chronic stress and you are not sleeping right? Will this affect you? Yes!!! Chronic and acute stress release hormones and neuro transmitters that tell our body to go into 'fight or flight' mode. These hormones and neurotransmitters especially norepinephrine switch off digestion and the GI tract making it very difficult to absorb nutrients ğŸš«ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
My own experience with stress. And how I learned to copeğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
I have been a worry wart from day dot. And a control freak. I used to stress out so badly. I remember the tell tale signs would be on my skin if I was going through a really bad period of stress ğŸ˜© During my leaving cert I lost loads of weight and my hair started falling out due to stress ğŸ˜”Before my Dad died, he asked me to try and relax and something triggered in me. I knew I needed to put things in place or I would end up running myself into the ground. And I had improved so much until this yearğŸ™„ This year tested me. A roller-coaster doesn't do it justice, so I realised I needed help. I started seeing a  counsellor and I have been seeing her for the past month ğŸ˜Š (My issues are not as simple as I'm stressed they go way back so that's what I needed help with).
.
.
What can you do?
So while you may not need to go to the extreme I did. You need to manage your stress levels. The body does NOT want to be in fight or flight mode. It wants to be in 'rest and digest' mode. So you need to sort your stress out acute or chronic ğŸš«ğŸš«
.
.
Self care is vitally important. I have only really started learning that since my Dad died. This year with the help of my counsellor I've realised that who's going to look after me if I'm trying to look after everyone elseğŸ¤” It's absolutely necessary to put yourself first sometimes. Don't ever forget that â¤ï¸ #stress #hormonemonstress #fightorflight #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #balance #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitchick #irishfitfam

caption:
ğŸ…How to stay on track over Christmas ğŸ…
.
.
Firstly, let me start by saying I'm not a grinch ğŸ˜‚ I love Christmas as much as the next person and I enjoy myself too ğŸ‘Œ But I don't take the absolute p*#s either ğŸ˜™ Here's my top tips on how to not ruin your progress over the holidays ğŸ„
.
.
1. Relax. It's not Christmas yet. I'm all for YOLO and all that but there's no need for the celebrations to be out on 1st December ğŸ™„ If you take the whole month of December to celebrate one day, you WILL ruin your progress ğŸ˜¬
.
.
2. Keep active ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ğŸƒâ€â™‚ï¸Get out in the fresh air, bring the dog for a walk, take part in a charity swim, go for a cycle or even a home workout ğŸ‘ Being 100% sedentary will do you no favours ğŸ™
.
.
3. Stay hydrated ğŸ’§ğŸ’§ğŸ’§ Simple tip but one of the most important ğŸ‘Œ
.
.
4. Try stick to one 'bad meal' a day. If you want a fry in the morning, stick with a healthy lunch and a wholesome dinner. If you are going out for dinner, opt for a protein rich breakfast and maybe a salad for lunch.
Top tips for eating out:
- Stick with 2 courses or a main meal with a couple of drinks
- For a main meal, try a high protein/high cÃ¡rb/low fat option or high protein/high fat/low cÃ¡rb
.
.
5. Be cautious of drinking your calories. Check out my last post on how calorific festive hot drinks are ğŸ™ˆ With Alcohol, stick to clear drinks with a diet mixer or water. Steer away from creamy cocktails or baileys ğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸
.
.
6. The most important part is ENJOY yourself. It's a time of year to spend with family and friends and appreciate what you have â¤ï¸ You don't need to be the prude sitting in the corner with fish and greens but you also don't need to do a 10,000 calorie challenge every day ğŸ˜‚ Find a balance that means you'll enjoy yourself but you'll also keep an eye on your goals ğŸ˜Š
.
.
P. S if you decide to eat like an asshole. Own it and don't come whinging in January. ğŸ™„ğŸ™ˆ Nobody wants to hear it ğŸ˜…

.

.
.

.

caption:
One of the biggest problems with our society is we wait until we are broken before we fix ourselvesğŸ˜¢

.
This goes for everything. We let our mental health deteriorate before we decide to do anything about it. We only work on our stress levels when we've had a breakdown. We only start looking after our diet when we've been diagnosed with an illness. We don't exercise until we have weight to lose. We don't sort injuries until they stop us from working. We take shortcuts, tablets, pills, shakes all to avoid  reality, which is actually so much easier. .
.
Move a little everyday. Nourish your body. Sleep. And stress less â¤ï¸ #fitliving #fitlife #balancedlifestyle #eatforhealth #eatforperformance #fitgirls #fitfam #irishfitfam

.

 I put up a poll the other day and was disappointed to see over 30% of people found it restrictive. I didn't ask reasons why but here's my thoughts on the whole matter. ğŸ’­ğŸ’­ğŸ’­

ğŸ‘‰ Food that nourishes your body

.
.
I believe healthy eating is eating 80% of the food that the body needs and 20% of the food the body wants ğŸ˜‰â¤ï¸
.

That being said there are healthier versions of everything these days. As above ğŸ˜ğŸ‘†ğŸ¤¤
.
.
â˜‘ï¸And I also think as you get older you realise health is important.

.
.

Strength was my other reason for getting involved in fitness. I was tiny and so weak. I initially did it to get stronger for football. .
.
Secondly, how I look should never come into it. If I was overweight would you say 'you're not a good role model'. It doesn't matter what size or shape you are. .
.

caption:
How to get back on track after weekend of bad food and alcohol??? ğŸ˜¥ğŸ˜¥ğŸ˜¥
.
.
Remember it is what you do MOST of the time that will be a reflection of your health and body composition. ğŸ™Œ NOT what you do SOME of the time.
.
.
So if this weekend was the first weekend in weeks/months that you went out then chances are you won't do huge damage to progress. But if it's a regular occurrence and you're complaining that you're not seeing results. Remember the weekend is 35% of your week, so if it's consistently a problem this will have an impact on results ğŸ™ˆğŸ™ˆğŸ™ˆ
.
.
What to do?
ğŸ‘‰ A wise woman once said to me, when you make a mistake think of the 3 f's. Forget about it. F*#k it. You didn't kill anyone did you ğŸ™ˆ And fix it. The way you fix it is not by overdoing the cardio or living on fish and leaves for the week. Instead go back to normal eating habits
ğŸ‘‰ Drink plenty of water.
ğŸ‘‰ Catch up on sleep. Sleep is one that is undermined.
ğŸ‘‰ Get back to exercise. Even if you need to wean your way in with a walk or something light. You'll always feel better afterwards

caption:
â‰ï¸Did you know that we have 11 systems in our body?? ğŸ¤”
.
.
â‰ï¸Did you know that they work in conjunction with one another?? ğŸ¤”
.
.
â›” If you have an issue with one system you could be putting other systems at risk.
.
.
â¡ï¸ Take your digestive system for example. If you are not absorbing nutrients properly it can have an impact on your skeletal system (in the case of calcium)
â¡ï¸ If your stress hormones are imbalanced it can have an impact on your integumentary system (hair loss)
â¡ï¸ When your nervous system is out of whack, you may have a weakened immune system

The list goes on. The point is. Look after all parts of your body. No part is more important than the other. Looking healthy externally means nothing if you aren't healthy on the inside ğŸ‘Œ This doesnt just mean exercise and nutrition. It goes for every part of your health â¤ï¸ And don't forget to enjoy life while you live your healthiest life ğŸ’‹

Priorities ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”
.
.
I always talk about goals and how important they are. Well priorities link in with your goals. There is no right or wrong answer to this. We all have priorities. Some of us have them without even realising. ğŸ™„
.
.
What do I mean?
ğŸ‘‰ I prioritise my health. Therefore, I eat well. I exercise. And I try my very best to reduce my stress levels and sleep well ğŸ‘‰ I prioritise holidays. Therefore, I don't go out very often so I can save money to go on holidays. ğŸ‘‰ I prioritise my family, friends and boyfriend. Even with a very busy schedule. I make time to see them. It may not be very often but I still make them a priority. ğŸ‘‰ I prioritise my job. The hours I work are often very unsocial but I make it work, because its a priority.
.
.
I often hear people say they 'care' about their health but are not willing to pay for healthy food. ğŸ™„Others who 'care' about their friends but never see themğŸ˜µ. Those who want to build businesses but are only willing to work 9-5ğŸ™ˆğŸ¤” People wanting to save for a house but are out every weekend ğŸ˜”Then, there's the ones who want to lose weightğŸ¤¯. They may care. But caring and prioritising are 2 very different things. Again, I am not giving out. Nobody needs to have the same priorities as me. But remember, for you to achieve your goals in life, no matter what they may be you need to prioritise. âœ‹âœ‹âœ‹ #priorities #ineverythingyoudo #healthyliving #healthylifestyle #healthyalternative #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

Buzzword = Protein ğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆğŸ‘ˆ
.

Wrong ğŸ˜±ğŸ˜±ğŸ˜±
.
.
Are you buying protein bars because they are the 'healthier' option? What is the context? Why are they healthier? Because they contain protein? Because they have 'less sugar? Or maybe you are eating them to hit your protein target? Do you understand the term food quality? Anyway you should really understand 'why' you are eating what you are eating and if it will help towards your goals? .
.
I haven't tried them because
1. They are a rip off
2. I like the original
3. Protein bars don't agree with me
.
.
If it were me and I wanted a boost bar. I'd buy the bar (as long as I could stop at 1 bar and it's not a multipack). I would have it as a treat.
.
.
If you are eating protein bars as your treat, just understand why? P. S I am NOT anti protein bars but I am anti miseducation.

caption:
Last week was a bad week and came with it poor choices and what I consider poor health. ğŸ˜”
.
.
ğŸ‘‰Monday - Normal Diet and Gym session
ğŸ‘‰Tuesday - Starting to feel tired and sick but still normal diet
ğŸ‘‰Wednesday - Head cold, ate twice, stress levels sky high
ğŸ‘‰Thursday - Still dosed, very high stress levels, ate twice
ğŸ‘‰Friday - Terrible sleep, stress levels through the roof, forced myself to eat, ate rubbish
ğŸ‘‰Saturday - Played a match (didn't have my normal energy), felt sick after, still ate pizza (first takeaway in MONTHS)
ğŸ‘‰Sunday - Ate twice - both poor choices
.
.
Monday morning I've woken up, feeling hungover ğŸ˜© Without a drop of alcohol. A cycle like this is really really unusual for me. But it's almost though I eat crap, feel like crap but do it again. It has been years since this has happened before. Normally, I feel good so I keep eating good. My energy levels were low, my mood was low. I felt terrible. It really had a huge impact on how I felt. But it's Monday. It's time to start a fresh. This week is under my control and I've a super important game Saturday which all of my focus is on ğŸ™ Bring it on ğŸ™ŒğŸ™ŒğŸ™Œ #honestyisthebestpolicy #poorfoodchoices #leaveyoufeelingterrible #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #healthyalternative #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitfam #irishfitfam

I am honest on this. Always have been, always will be. People who know me describe me as 'positive' which I am. But there's only so much positive someone can be ğŸ’” I've never discussed this aspect of my life before because I felt I didn't need to... But since I'm a talker and talking usually works for me I feel I need to.
.
.
Those who know me know my Dad died 3 years ago. I was super close to him. I was devastated. That left a family of me, my sister and my mother. I'm not close to my mother and have an amazing relationship with my sister â¤ï¸ My mother suffers from many mental health issues. Did before my Dad died and definitely has since. I've been in as many hospitals with her as I have with my Dad. It's hard. Like really hÃ¡rd and a lot of the time she doesn't help herself (not gonna get too in depth). I am now a next of kin and at 27 you'd think you'd be able for that but it's actually a massive responsibility.
.
.
I am beyond lÃºcky that I have my boyfriend, friends and family â¤ï¸ Anyway long story short, while I myself have never had mental health issues. I have been affected by them. And believe me I know I'm just one in a million of us. But #itsoknottobeok â™¥ï¸ It's OK to ask for help and to talk â¤ï¸ There are so many out there. So many support lines, not just for those with mental heath issues but others affected too â¤ï¸ #yourmentalhealth #lookafteryourself

caption:
Consistency ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯ğŸ’¯
.
.
I had said my page was not going to focus as much on aesthetics and its the truth but sometimes people (myself included) need a reminder about what consistency actually is ğŸ™ˆ
.
.
I'm gonna relate this to fitness but of course it can be related to anything. Consistency is sticking with something, through the good and the bad ğŸ‘Œ I am consistent. Even when I think I'm not I am (no Amanda that chocolate bar at the weekend will not kill you) ğŸ˜‚ If I take a break, it's a short one and I'm 100% back to normality after it. I loooove my lifestyle because its one I can adhere to. Its not restrictive (this is my version of non restrictive but others would probably find it restrictive). I have my treats if I want them. I drink occasionally. But I am consistent. I train regularly and 80% of the food I eat is healthy â¤ï¸
.
.
Anything short of consistency will end in failure. I'll give an example:
- You train 3 - 5 times a week = 3 - 5 hours a week. You eat relatively well during the week but all hell breaks lose at the weekend (probably because you are so restrictive during the week). 1 drink turns into 10 on Saturday and Sunday = takeaway to cure the hangover ğŸ˜­. ALL OF THE ABOVE IS INCONSISTENT. From training times to eating patterns to number of alcohol units. But now let's really throw a spanner in the works. You decide to take 2-6 weeks off training/diet to 'enjoy your summer' or 'holidays' ğŸ˜©ğŸ˜©ğŸ˜© And you wonder why you don't get results ğŸ˜­
.
.
Unless you can find something that you can stick with, something you enjoy, something that is not a chore and are consistent with it, you're really not going anywhere ğŸ™ˆğŸ˜©
.
.
P. S I'm not saying you have to have the same lifestyle as me. But please stop complaining if you're not getting results for putting in minimal effort ğŸ™„âœ‹ #consistencyiskey #consistency #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #balancedlifestyle #fitliving #fitlifestyle #fitgirls #fitchick #fitfam #irishfitfam

caption:
Eating Healthy on a Budget âœ”ï¸âœ”ï¸âœ”ï¸
.
.
This is so do able and this idea that eating healthy is too expensive is absolute nonsense. You don't NEED to eat organically or buy all your food from health food shops. Of course, quality of food is important but if you're swapping from pot noodles to wholefoods you're doing pretty good ğŸ¤—
.
.
Some tips for shopping on a Budget
âœ”ï¸ Look out for Aldi Super 6 on fruit, veg and meat (other supermarkets offer something similar so keep an eye out)
âœ”ï¸ Shop early morning or late in the evening (there is often discounted foods with short best before dates)
âœ”ï¸ Shop with a list
.
.
I have done up a short shopping list and meal plan. Take a look at my story ğŸ‘Œ

#eatforhealth #eatforperformance #healthylifestyle #healthyliving #fitliving #fitlife #fitlifestyle #fitgirls #goodfood #healthyoptions #fitfam #irishfitfam

Are sauces and flavourings denying you results??? ğŸ¶ğŸ¶ğŸ¶
.
.
It's very easy to think marinades or sauces don't count. But unfortunately they do ğŸ™ˆ And they can be a big downfall for people. Take for example this marinade, the first ingredient is sugar ğŸ˜±ğŸ˜±ğŸ˜± When we compare it to natural flavourings like chilli powder or paprika which have minimal calories and very little processing ğŸ¤”
.
.
Another example of this is salad dressings. Salads can go from diet hero to zero in a matter of seconds. A lot of salad dressings are very calorific so be cautious ğŸ‘¹
.
.
The same goes for ordering food when you're out. Theres no point ordering the hake when you get the creamy sauce, creamed potatoes and vegetables lathered in butter. Believe me I'm all for 'treat yoself' but is it really helping you towards your goals? ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”ğŸ¤”

Do you think you need supplements??? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Do you think your diet is sufficient??? ğŸ¤”
.
.
Unfortunately many of us need supplements, even those of u who have a balanced dietğŸ¤·â€â™€ï¸ Why?
ğŸ‘‰ Food quality can be poor even 'organic' and 'wholefoods'
ğŸ‘‰ Our lifestyle - high intensity exercise, high pressure jobs, long days, poor food choices etc
ğŸ‘‰ Lack of availability of certain nutrients
.
.
These are the supplements I take and why
ğŸ’Š Probiotics
Gut health is vital. Your gut sends signals to all the systems in our body and works in conjunction with them all. Day to day, we damage the bacteria in our gut. Not to mention what medication and illness can do to it. I recommend taking a 30 day course of Probiotics every once in awhile
.
.
ğŸ’ŠFish oils
It is recommended to eat fish 2-3 times a week. But did you know that white fish does not contain the same fats that oily fish do? So if you are only eating white fish you are not getting sufficient omega 3 fats. And furthermore, because our food quality has gone to s*#t, oily fish doesn't even contain enough omega 3 fats. So majority of people, even those with a good diet are not getting adequate omega 3 fats. I recommend a fish oil supplement for overall health. When looking for a fish oil supplement look for EPA and DHÃ content
.
.
ğŸ’Š Vitamin D
Also known as the sunshine vitamin. Ireland does not have enough sunlight to produce adequate amounts of vitamin D in the body. We can obtain Vit D in our diet but the preferred form is sunlight. Vitamin D is required to absorb calcium as well as many other functions.
.
.
ğŸ’Š Magnesium
Did you know that magnesium is needed for over 300 chemical reactions in the body? And we only absorb 20-50% of our dietary magnesium. I started taking this for muscle cramps. Magnesium Chloride is the most easily absorbed form. I get mine through magnesium oil. Epsom salts are another good form

What supplements if any do you take and why?
